<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> DeCicco Honored To Coach US Women </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLAREMONT, Calif. (AP) -- Tony DiCicco is the man behind the  
women. 
</P>
<P>
	As perhaps 2,000 fans at Thursday's practice session screamed  
for Mia Hamm, Michelle Akers and the rest of the U.S. soccer squad 
that has taken the nation by storm, DiCicco exited the bus and 
calmly strode, almost unnoticed, toward the field at Pomona-Pitzer 
College. 
</P>
<P>
	When the workout ended, 150 or so media members scrambled to  
surround the players as they sat in different areas of the field. 
Television cameramen jostled for position near Julie Foudy and 
Brandi Chastain. 
</P>
<P>
	DiCicco sat nearby, far from the madding crowd, a handful of  
reporters informally chatting with him. That, generally, is 
DiCicco's way: He stays out of the way, except when his team needs 
some instruction or a dressing down. 
</P>
<P>
	``It has been a privilege to coach this team,'' DiCicco said as  
the Americans prepared for Saturday's final with China. ``It's been 
a wonderful opportunity for all of us. This team has grown together 
and is so close to achieving what it set out to do, and they all 
are outstanding women, too. I can't think of a better job to 
have.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When DiCicco took over the job in August 1994 from Anson  
Dorrance -- who guided the Americans to the first Women's World Cup 
title in 1991 and is the mastermind of the University of North 
Carolina soccer dynasty -- he sought guidance from some of his 
players. Hamm told him to ``coach us like men, treat us like 
women.'' He has never forgotten that advice. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't know much about this team,'' said DiCicco, 50, who  
joined the squad as a goalkeepers' coach in '91. ``I had been 
working with U.S. Soccer and boys youth national teams. This team 
had developed a reputation for good play. 
</P>
<P>
	``Once I experienced this team and saw their passion for the  
game and the goals they set for themselves, it was fun to be around 
them. And it became a dream come true to end up their head coach.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Since taking charge, DiCicco has a 96-8-7 record, including this  
World Cup. He's led the Americans to third place at the '95 World 
Cup, gold medals at the Atlanta Olympics and last year's Goodwill 
Games, and now to the finals of the biggest women's sporting event 
ever. Not bad for someone who claims he didn't consider holding the 
job before he got it. 
</P>
<P>
	``Coaching a national team? I don't know if I ever thought about  
being the women's national coach'' he said. ``But certainly playing 
and coaching at a high level was a dream of mind. I sought to coach 
a team that is motivated, talented and has a chance of winning, and 
that I would be proud to be associated with. 
</P>
<P>
	``All those goals have been answered by this team.''  
</P>
<P>
	As a male among these superb female athletes, DiCicco remains a  
bit of an outsider. That gives him a unique perspective about this 
team that, right now, carries the aura of the biggest rock stars. 
He had to chuckle when someone mentioned the hundreds of yelping 
youngsters who surrounded the team bus as it pulled onto the 
college grounds before practice. 
</P>
<P>
	Might this scene be similar to what Bruce Springsteen or Ricky  
Martin experiences at concerts? 
</P>
<P>
	``One of the things that sets this team apart is that they don't  
want to all be the homecoming queen and do the popular thing,'' he 
said. ``They just want to go out and win games and win 
championships and Olympic gold medals. That's an awesome challenge. 
</P>
<P>
	``The genuine pursuit of their dreams and goals is what is so  
enticing for people. Its kind of snowballed and has turned into a 
wonderful phenomena. They are finally getting their due.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So is he.  
</P>
<P>
	``Tony understands us,'' veteran Joy Fawcett said. ``He  
understands we have a different approach to the game and to the 
relationships we build than the men do. He allows us to be 
ourselves, and that's been a very important part of our success.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
