<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 10:29:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Russia Delays Satellite Launch </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALMATY, Kazakstan (AP) -- Russia was forced today to postpone the  
launch of a Russian-Ukrainian satellite because of Kazakstan's 
temporary ban on use of the Baikonur Cosmodrome, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	The launch of the Ocean-O weather satellite was put off until  
Friday but could be delayed even further, said Khalid Abteshev, the 
acting chief of Kazakstan's Airspace Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Kazakstan suspended all launches from Baikonur on Tuesday  
pending the investigation of Monday's crash of a rocket carrying a 
Russian military satellite. Also under investigation was possible 
environmental damage caused by fuel spilling from the 
disintegrating rocket. 
</P>
<P>
	Kazak Environmental Protection Minister Serikbek Daukeyev said  
Thursday that the crash had showered a large area of central 
Kazakstan with fuel, the Interfax news agency reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Daukeyev said lab tests would determine whether the fuel had  
caused any environmental damage, but that local authorities had 
already taken measures to protect residents against poisoning. 
</P>
<P>
	The ban on launches from Baikonur could be a major inconvenience  
for Russia, which leases the cosmodrome for cargo flights to the 
Mir space station and for launches of commercial and military 
satellites. 
</P>
<P>
	Moscow hopes Kazakstan will limit the ban to launches of the  
Proton-class booster rocket that failed Monday, instead of all 
rockets, Russian Foreign Ministry spokesman Vladimir Rakhmanin said 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia fears that if Kazakstan bans all launches, the two  
countries could ``come to a disruption in bilateral and 
international obligations connected with the use of Baikonur,'' 
Rakhmanin said. 
</P>
<P>
	Moscow is several years behind on its rent payments for  
Baikonur, but says it should be allowed to continue using the 
cosmodrome because Kazakstan has debts to Russia as well. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia has a cargo flight to Mir scheduled for July 14 and a  
launch of a French-Russian Sesat satellite planned for July 28-29. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990708.0008 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 22:40:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Missing Financier Wooed Celebrities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GREENWICH, Conn. (AP) -- Martin Frankel was a name-dropper.  
</P>
<P>
	He tossed around names of rich businessmen, celebrities,  
powerful lawyers, and even saints to attract people to his bogus 
Catholic charity. Lee Iacocca, Walter Cronkite, Robert Strauss, St. 
Francis of Assisi, to name a few. 
</P>
<P>
	In some cases, the mysterious money manager from Greenwich  
really had managed to charm power brokers into supporting his 
purported charitable cause. In others, he simply lied about their 
involvement. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities say Frankel, 44, disappeared in May with at least  
$215 million in assets from several insurance companies. 
</P>
<P>
	Thomas Bolan, a well-known New York attorney and former federal  
prosecutor, was one of those who believed Frankel's elaborate 
stories about wanting to help the needy. 
</P>
<P>
	Bolan did not return telephone calls seeking comment, but his  
attorney, Maurice Nessen, said Bolan was convinced that Frankel was 
eager to raise money for the poor through the St. Francis of Assisi 
Foundation, a charity he established in the British Virgin Islands 
in August 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	The first time Bolan met Frankel at his Greenwich mansion, he  
was led into a room lined with shelves filled with books about the 
Catholic church, saints and church canon, Nessen said. 
</P>
<P>
	Frankel, who always called himself ``David Rosse'' during his  
dealings with Bolan, waxed on and on during their initial 
conversation, showing an in-depth knowledge of the saints, 
especially St. Francis, who was known for helping the poor. 
</P>
<P>
	``He put on a show and the show was very real.''  
</P>
<P>
	Bolan met Frankel through Thomas Corbally, a well-connected New  
York business consultant who introduced Frankel to various movers 
and shakers Frankel hoped would add legitimacy to the St. Francis 
foundation, which authorities now believe was a front for fraud. 
</P>
<P>
	When approached by an Associated Press reporter at his London  
hotel Wednesday evening, Corbally refused to talk about Frankel. He 
told The Express, a London tabloid, that Frankel duped him. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was fooled like everyone else. He was a consummate liar, a  
master of deception,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Frankel has not been seen since May 4, the day before  
firefighters found documents burning inside his Greenwich mansion. 
Federal authorities have issued a warrant for his arrest on wire 
fraud and money laundering charges. 
</P>
<P>
	While 11 insurance companies in five states were horrified to  
learn of the missing assets, so were some prominent people whose 
names had been attached to Frankel's charity without their 
permission. 
</P>
<P>
	Retired CBS newsman Walter Cronkite said he was contacted in  
January by an old friend, the Rev. Peter Jacobs, a priest living in 
Rome, and asked to become a member of the St. Francis foundation's 
advisory board. Jacobs described it as a new organization that was 
being founded to aid charities involving children and health and 
education 
</P>
<P>
	Cronkite said he refused, mainly because he was already busy  
with several other charities. Former Chrysler Chairman Lee Iacocca 
was also listed, although he, too, has denied giving his 
permission. 
</P>
<P>
	In May, after Frankel disappeared, Cronkite learned that despite  
his refusal, his name had been listed as a member of the board on 
the foundation's mission statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Rev. Jacobs called Cronkite and left a message on his answering  
machine: ``This man has apparently run away with all the money.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cronkite told The Associated Press Thursday he is not surprised  
that Frankel convinced so many people to believe his pitch. 
</P>
<P>
	``Anybody who says he's got a billion dollars and is willing to  
give it away is likely to attract an awful lot of people,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Neither Jacobs, nor his lawyer, John Q. Kelly, returned  
telephone calls from The Associated Press seeking comment. Jacobs 
told the Greenwich Time that he and other priests had been 
completely fooled by Frankel. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were the proverbial suckers,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	The foundation listed attorney Robert Strauss, the former U.S.  
ambassador to the Soviet Union, as its legal counsel. 
</P>
<P>
	Strauss' law firm -- Akin, Gump, Strauss, Hauer &AMP; Feld of  
Washington, D.C., confirmed that it had done some legal work for 
the foundation and for Thunor Trust, which owned 11 insurance 
companies, on the prospective acquisition of two other insurance 
companies. The firm did not represent Frankel, or David Rosse, as 
he called himself. 
</P>
<P>
	``None of our lawyers who performed this work were aware of any  
facts or circumstances suggesting that any of our clients were 
involved in unlawful or fraudulent conduct,'' the firm said in a 
statement. 
</P>
<P>
	``Neither of the transactions on which our lawyers worked  
reached closing, and all of the insurance companies owned by the 
Thunor Trust were purchased years before anyone contacted Akin, 
Gump,'' said Mark J. MacDougall, a litigation partner speaking for 
the firm. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
