<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Phillies Win Games, but Not Fans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Jim Abbott pitched against the Philadelphia  
Phillies this week and said it was one of the strangest adventures 
of his new life in the National League. 
</P>
<P>
	He looked at the lineup card and realized he hadn't heard of  
many of the players he was about to face. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think I was probably less familiar with this team than any  
other opponent I've faced,'' the Milwaukee left-hander said. ``I 
don't know why.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Join the club, Jim. The Phillies don't even get any respect in  
their own city. Although they are seven games above .500 for the 
first time since 1995, hardly anyone in Philadelphia has noticed. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think whether people have noticed or not, we just continued  
to go about our business,'' said general manager Ed Wade, who tries 
to ignore the sickly attendance figures announced each night at 
Veterans Stadium. ``That's what we need to do now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Phillies' plight was never more apparent than on Wednesday  
night, when a sparse crowd of 16,593 was on hand to watch Scott 
Rolen's dramatic ninth-inning homer give the Phillies a 5-4 victory 
over the Brewers. 
</P>
<P>
	Curt Schilling, Paul Byrd and Mike Lieberthal had just been  
named to the NL All-Star team. Randy Wolf, the most exciting young 
pitcher to come through the organization in years, was on the 
mound. 
</P>
<P>
	Wolf got a no-decision and failed to become the Phillies' first  
pitcher since Marty Bystrom in 1980 to start his career 5-0. Still, 
the Phillies improved to 45-38, third in the NL East and two games 
behind the second-place Mets. They haven't been seven games above 
.500 since Aug. 1, 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	One problem: There were 45,000 empty seats. The Vet was so  
sparsely populated that Rolen heard a small contingent of fans 
chanting his name from 700 feet away in the upper deck before 
delivering his clutch homer. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought the whole city of Jasper showed up,'' said Rolen,  
born and raised in the small town of Jasper, Ind. 
</P>
<P>
	Rolen is only one of the young stars emerging in Philadelphia,  
unappreciated even though the Phillies play in one of the largest 
markets in the majors and only 100 miles from New York City. 
</P>
<P>
	At the other corner of the infield is Rico Brogna, who might be  
the best defensive first baseman in baseball. The Phillies are 
strong up the middle, with Lieberthal emerging behind the plate and 
Doug Glanville catching just about everything hit to center field. 
</P>
<P>
	Bobby Abreu, among the league leaders with a .330 average, is a  
rising star in right field. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a special group,'' said batting coach Hal McRae.  
``They're young, they're enthusiastic, they play hard. No other 
club in the league outhustles these guys.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One of the few people in baseball who noticed the Phillies was  
NL All-Star manager Bruce Bochy of the Padres. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was very impressed,'' Phillies manager Terry Francona said.  
``He knew everything about all our guys.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Schilling (12-4), headed to his third All-Star game, finally has  
some help in the starting rotation. He's backed up by Wolf and 
Byrd, an inspirational right-hander who went from waiver-wire 
pickup to All-Star in less than a year. 
</P>
<P>
	Schilling and Byrd gave the Phillies two 10-game winners before  
July for the first time since Jim Lonborg and Ken Brett in 1974. 
</P>
<P>
	``All you've got to do is come out and watch us play, and we're  
definitely exciting to watch,'' said Lieberthal, the first Phillies 
catcher to make the All-Star team since Darren Daulton in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	But while Philly's sports fans are some of the most rabid in the  
country, they also might be the most jaded. They know that the 
Phillies entered the season with the fourth-lowest payroll in the 
National League, and resent what they perceive to be small-market 
overtures from management. 
</P>
<P>
	Through 41 home dates, the Phillies have drawn an average of  
22,734 -- nearly 3,000 more than at this point last season but still 
near the bottom of the National League. 
</P>
<P>
	The Phillies are finalizing plans for a new ballpark scheduled  
to open in 2002. A hurdle was cleared this week to facilitate 
making it a downtown stadium, similar to those in Baltimore and 
Cleveland. 
</P>
<P>
	For now, a team that is one of baseball's the best-kept secrets  
continues to toil in anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think we have such a recognizable team,'' Lieberthal  
said. ``Until we actually win, we won't get that notoriety. We're 
starting to get it now. If we keep playing like we are, then we 
will get it.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
