<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Unity'99 Draws White House Hopefuls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- A gathering of the nation's minority journalists  
turned into a must-do political event for presidential hopefuls 
Thursday, with scheduled appearances by Democrats Al Gore and Bill 
Bradley and last-minute stops by Republicans George W. Bush and 
John McCain. 
</P>
<P>
	There was controversy as Bush first declined to come, then added  
a last-minute stop, sans speech. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was just really disappointed,'' said Nancy Baca, president  
of the National Association of Hispanic Journalists. ``He used us 
as a glorified photo opportunity.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush walked briefly through the Unity '99 conference's  
exhibition hall, answered a few shouted questions from a growing 
crowd of delegates, and left after less than 25 minutes. 
</P>
<P>
	Catalina Camia, president of Unity: Journalists of Color,  
denounced the Texas governor's brief visit at a news conference. 
She said she was notified of Bush's visit as his car approached 
Seattle's Convention Center, where more than 6,000 Asian-American, 
black, Hispanic and American Indian journalists are gathered this 
week. 
</P>
<P>
	Calling Bush's stop ``inadequate,'' Camia said, ``This was  
clearly a missed opportunity for the Bush campaign and for the 
convention attendees.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier, she had announced McCain's decision to rearrange his  
plans and speak at the conference. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush's campaign office initially said he was too busy to attend  
the conference. But Bush changed his mind on the plane trip here 
after reading news coverage in which he was criticized for not 
attending the conference while in Seattle. 
</P>
<P>
	At a press conference later, Bush downplayed the political  
ramifications and said he wasn't trying to match McCain, who spoke 
and answered questions for about an hour. 
</P>
<P>
	``My presence there hopefully reaches out and says I'll be an  
inclusive-type president,'' Bush said. 
</P>
<P>
	Delegates said they approved of Bush's decision to attend, but  
felt insulted by the brevity of his visit. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a community that can make or break most candidates,''  
asserted Art Norman, a TV anchorman in Chicago and a member of the 
National Association of Black Journalists. ``He should be here. He 
should not overlook us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McCain said he also made his last-minute decision after reading  
news coverage. After his speech Thursday, a conference delegate 
accused him of ``pandering.'' McCain denied that. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was unhappy that the oversight had taken place, and I  
corrected it,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	A Vietnam war hero and former POW, McCain told the story of an  
Hispanic Medal of Honor recipient to illustrate his respect for 
diversity in America. 
</P>
<P>
	``We should all, Republican and Democrat, be working toward a  
new American unity,'' he said. Asked about affirmative action, 
McCain said he supports it, but only in the form of training and 
education programs that create ``an equal playing field.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley, who spoke shortly before McCain, emphasized the  
difference between his appearance Thursday and those of the 
Republican candidates. 
</P>
<P>
	``Let me just say at the beginning, I did not change my  
schedule,'' Bradley said to much applause and laughter. 
</P>
<P>
	The former New Jersey senator and professional basketball player  
said the defining moment in his life was being present as a 
spectator in the U.S. Senate when it passed the Civil Rights Act of 
1964. 
</P>
<P>
	``One of the fundamental (motivations) for this candidacy is the  
push for racial unity,'' Bradley said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore is scheduled to attend the convention Friday and deliver a  
speech on ``Race, Technology and the Future of the United States.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
