<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Clinton Ending Poverty Tour  
</P>
<P>
	ANAHEIM, Calif. AP) -- President Clinton, ending a ``remarkable  
ride'' through poverty pockets from Appalachia to Watts, today	
called for investment in people in impoverished areas. ``They	
deserve a chance to be whatever they're willing to work hard to	
be,'' Clinton said. Clinton made the remarks at the annual	
conference of the National Academy Foundation, an organization that	
helps youths. Earlier, he visited the Los Angeles community of	
Watts, scarred by historic riots, to make the case for private	
firms helping disadvantaged young people.	

</P>
<P>
	Rains Cause Las Vegas Flood; 2 Dead  
</P>
<P>
	LAS VEGAS (AP) -- Heavy rains pounded the Las Vegas Valley today,  
turning streets into rivers. ``This is the worst flood in Las Vegas 
since at least 1984,'' said Ron McQueen, a meteorologist with the 
National Weather Service. Two deaths were blamed on the weather. 
Motorists were plucked from flooded vehicles by roaming fire trucks 
and, in at least one case, a police helicopter. The severe flooding 
turned sections of busy Interstate 15 into a lake, bringing traffic 
to a standstill. Tourists took shelter inside casinos. No casinos 
reported any major damage. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. May Help in Congo Peacekeeping  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration will consider  
sending U.S. troops to Congo as part of a possible U.N. 
peacekeeping mission following the end of an 11-month civil war in 
the volatile region, a U.S. official said today. If American 
soldiers move into the Central African nation, it will be the first 
time the United States has engaged in peacekeeping duties in 
sub-Saharan Africa since 18 U.S. soldiers were killed in Somalia in 
1993. ``We are eager to be supportive,'' State Department spokesman 
James Foley said. 

</P>
<P>
	New Red Cross Leader Named  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Dr. Bernadine Healy was named today to head  
the American Red Cross. She is filling the post that Elizabeth Dole 
left to pursue a GOP presidential bid. Healy, a heart specialist, 
will be the first physician to head the 118-year-old organization. 
A former head of the National Institutes of Health, she is now dean 
of the Ohio State University College of Medicine and Public Health. 

</P>
<P>
	Amtrak Train Hits Truck, Derails  
</P>
<P>
	EAGLE LAKE, Texas (AP) -- An Amtrak train carrying 235 passengers  
struck a truck today, derailing nine cars and injuring 18 people. 
The eastbound Sunset Limited was traveling from Los Angeles to 
Orlando, Fla., when it hit the rig shortly before noon, Amtrak 
said. Track was torn up and two engines and seven cars were off to 
the side. 

</P>
<P>
	Milosevic's Offices Are Stoned  
</P>
<P>
	PROKUPLJE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Protesters demanding the  
resignation of Slobodan Milosevic stoned his party's headquarters 
here today after a supporter of the Yugoslav president fired 
gunshots into the air to disrupt the rally. Police did not 
interfere with the rally by about 4,000 demonstrators, the latest 
in a series of public protests demanding Milosevic step down. A 
scheduled counter-demonstration by government supporters failed to 
materialize. 

</P>
<P>
	Retail Sales Up; Jobless Claims Off  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The nation's biggest retailers reported  
surprisingly strong sales in June as the robust U.S. economy and 
warm weather sent Americans on a buying bonanza. The Merrill Lynch 
retail index, the investment firm's barometer of sales performance 
at department stores and discount chains, was up 6.3 percent. The 
Labor Department said the number of Americans filing new claims for 
unemployment benefits fell by 6,000 last week to 294,000, the 
second consecutive drop. 

</P>
<P>
	Stocks Mixed; Dow Ends Off 60.47  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock prices were mixed today as strength in  
Internet and computer shares helped the technology sector 
outperform the broader market. The Dow Jones industrials ended down 
60.47 at 11,126.89. On the NYSE, losers led gainers 1,654-1,293. 
The technology-laden Nasdaq rose 28.82 to 2,771.86, a record high. 

</P>
<P>
	Blue Jays 11, Orioles 6  
</P>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- The Toronto Blue Jays today hit six home runs,  
including two each by Willis Otanez and Tony Batista, and completed 
their second three-game sweep of Baltimore in 10 days with an 11-6 
victory. Carlos Delgado and Shannon Stewart also homered for the 
Blue Jays. 

</P>
<P>
	NHL Rangers Get Theo Fleury  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Six-time NHL All-Star forward Theo Fleury signed  
today with the New York Rangers as an unrestricted free agent. 
Reportedly, the deal was for at least four years at $8 million to 
$10 million per year. Fleury, 31, played for 11 years with Calgary 
before being traded to Colorado on Feb. 28. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by HOWARD SINER  

  	   	
</P>
