<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> American Airlines Fined $250,500 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- The Federal Aviation Administration levied a  
$250,000 civil penalty Thursday against American Airlines because 
airline employees and contractors repeatedly failed to display 
their badges in high-security areas at Dallas-Fort Worth 
International Airport. 
</P>
<P>
	American said the workers often stuffed the badges in their  
pockets while they worked in cramped quarters, such as the belly of 
a plane. 
</P>
<P>
	The FAA said that wasn't good enough -- that unless security  
agents could see the badges, it might take too long to stop an 
unauthorized person from planting explosives in bags being loaded 
on an airplane. 
</P>
<P>
	American appealed a February 1998 decision by an administrative  
law judge to FAA Administrator Jane F. Garvey, who upheld the 
ruling in December. 
</P>
<P>
	The airline said Thursday it would drop the matter and not take  
it to federal appeals court. ``We'll pay the civil penalty and move 
on,'' said American spokesman Tim Smith. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've made changes in terms of procedures,'' Smith said.  
``American continually works to ensure the safety of our system and 
passengers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A spokesman for the FAA said the agency would have no additional  
comment. 
</P>
<P>
	The employees and contractors were cited for not wearing their  
badges in a ``security identification display area'' where access 
is limited to protect against terrorism. 
</P>
<P>
	According to FAA documents, American unsuccessfully argued that  
the employees and contractors didn't have to wear their badges as 
long as they could produce them upon request. But the FAA 
administrator said the airline was incorrectly interpreting the 
federal law. 
</P>
<P>
	The airline also complained that the penalty exceeded those of  
similar cases. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
