<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dell European Chief Steps Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AUSTIN (AP) -- Dell Computer Corp.'s top European executive has  
stepped down and will be replaced by Dell's president of 
Asia-Pacific operations, the company announced Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The resignation of Jan Gesmar-Larsen, 39, was due to personal  
reasons, the company said. 
</P>
<P>
	Europe is a critical market for the personal-computer maker, and  
first-quarter sales fell short of company expectations. Dell's 
European revenues grew by 29 percent in the first quarter, down 
from 62 percent in the same quarter last year. 
</P>
<P>
	``Compared to other areas, we would like to have seen higher  
growth,'' company founder and chief executive Michael Dell told 
analysts in May. 
</P>
<P>
	Gesmar-Larsen, a former Apple Computer executive, said Wednesday  
that Dell's results were better than the industry as a whole in 
Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think a lot of people would be proud of it,'' he told the  
Austin American-Statesman. ``I am.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gesmar-Larsen will be replaced by John Legere, president of  
Dell's Asia-Pacific region. Legere joined Dell last year after 18 
years at AT&AMP;T Corp. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
