<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Torre: No Timetable For Retirement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Joe Torre doesn't have a timetable for  
retirement. 
</P>
<P>
	``As long as it's fun, I'm going to keep doing it,'' the New  
York Yankees manager said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Torre, who led the Yankees to a pair of World Series titles in  
his first three seasons, said during an interview Wednesday with 
Fox Sports News: ``I'm not thinking about doing this more than my 
contract,'' which runs through the 2001 season. 
</P>
<P>
	But a day later, he said he's going to take things year to year.  
</P>
<P>
	``When I decide I've had enough, I'll probably say, `This is my  
last year.' I can't project a couple of years down the road,'' 
Torre said. 
</P>
<P>
	When asked if that meant he'd stay at least through 2001, Torre  
said: ``I hope I make it to '01. Let's put it that way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Torre, who will turn 59 later this month, learned he had  
prostate cancer on March 9 after a blood test during a routine 
physical. He had surgery, and doctors said the cancer was caught 
early and his prognosis was good. Torre rejoined the team on May 
19. 
</P>
<P>
	His contract was due to expire after this season, but Torre  
agreed in February to a two-year extension through 2001. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've made no long-term plans after that,'' he said Thursday.  
</P>
<P>
	The Yankees set a major league record last season with 125  
victories, including an AL-record 114 during the regular season. 
</P>
<P>
	Torre hit .297 in a 17-year major league career and was a  
nine-time All-Star. In his 18th year as a manager, he is 
1,246-1,219 in stints with the New York Mets, Atlanta Braves and 
St. Louis Cardinals, as well as the Yankees. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
