<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Heavy Rains Flood Las Vegas Streets  
</P>
<P>
	LAS VEGAS (AP) -- Heavy rains poured on Las Vegas today, creating  
floods that smashed mobile homes, swallowed hundreds of cars and 
led to at least two deaths. ``It's a nightmare,'' said Nevada 
Highway Patrol spokesman Scott Flabi. ``It's one of the worst 
things I've ever seen.'' Sections of busy Interstate 15 resembled a 
lake, bringing traffic to a standstill. Most major intersections 
were under water. Block walls along a flood channel collapsed. 
Firefighters rescued motorists whose cars were sucked into the 
water. 

</P>
<P>
	Amtrak Train Hits Truck, Derails  
</P>
<P>
	EAGLE LAKE, Texas (AP) -- An Amtrak train carrying 235 passengers  
struck a truck today, derailing nine cars and injuring 18 people. 
The eastbound Sunset Limited was traveling from Los Angeles to 
Orlando, Fla., when it hit the rig shortly before noon, an Amtrak 
spokesman said. Track was torn up and two engines and seven cars 
were off to the side. 

</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton May Enlist Husband  
</P>
<P>
	COOPERSTOWN, N.Y. (AP) -- President Clinton can expect to be  
called on to do some campaigning for Hillary Rodham Clinton if she 
moves forward with a New York Senate race in 2000, the first lady 
said today. ``He knows a lot about New York,'' she said. ``He's 
done very well in New York and I would look forward to his 
campaigning for me if I decide to run ... (and) if I can get on his 
schedule.'' Touring upstate New York for a second consecutive day 
today, Mrs. Clinton said she would serve a full six-year term if 
she wins the Democratic nomination and is elected senator. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Tours U.S. Poverty Areas  
</P>
<P>
	ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) -- Ending a four-day tour of poverty pockets  
from Appalachia to Watts, President Clinton today called for 
investment in the ``human capital'' in impoverished areas. Clinton 
attended the National Academy Foundation conference, an 
organization that helps prepare disadvantaged high-school youths 
for careers. Citigroup, Lucent Technologies and other companies 
announced an $8 million initiative today to create ``Information 
Technology Academies'' to begin training boys and girls for careers 
in high-technology. 

</P>
<P>
	UN's Kofi Annan Visits Sierra Leone  
</P>
<P>
	FREETOWN, Sierra Leone (AP) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan  
visited Sierra Leone today to drum up international assistance for 
a new peace accord that has come under attack for including amnesty 
for war criminals. The accord, signed by Sierra Leone President 
Ahmed Tejan Kabbah and rebel Revolutionary United Front leader 
Foday Sankoh in Togo's capital of Lome late yesterday, formally 
ends eight years of civil war that has killed tens of thousands and 
maimed many more. 

</P>
<P>
	Outlook For U.S. Kids Is Good  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The number of kids committing and falling  
victim to crime has been dropping since 1993, according to a 
government report on the state of American children. The report 
painted an improving and mostly hopeful picture of children and 
teens, with vaccinations and preschool enrollment up and teen 
smoking and childbirth down. The entire report, issued by the 
Federal Interagency Forum on Child and Family Statistics, is 
available on the Internet at http://childstats.gov. 

</P>
<P>
	Yahoo! Modifies GeoCities Claim  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Yahoo! Inc. modified the rules for its  
GeoCities Internet community after users called a boycott to 
protest a policy that appeared to claim rights to content posted on 
personal Web sites. Yahoo! announced the change yesterday through a 
message posted on the GeoCities site under the headline: ``We hear 
you!'' ``Yahoo does not claim ownership of content you place on 
your Yahoo GeoCities site,'' the message said. The new rules give 
the company nonexclusive rights that can be used only to display 
and promote the Web sites of GeoCities users. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stocks Fall in Early Trading  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks fell Friday morning as investors  
locked in profits amid a lack of new evidence of recovery in 
Japan's economy. The Nikkei dropped 85.63 to 17,882.02. In New 
York, the Dow industrials ended down 60.47 at 11,126.89. 

</P>
<P>
	Yankees Say Goodbye to Tiger Stadium  
</P>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Tino Martinez hit a tiebreaking leadoff homer in  
the ninth inning as the New York Yankees won their final game in 
Tiger Stadium, beating Detroit 3-2 tonight. Martinez lined a 2-2 
fastball from C.J. Nitkowski (1-3) into the upper deck bleachers in 
right-center to break a 2-2 tie and make a winner out of Orlando 
Hernandez (10-6). 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by JEROME MINERVA  


  	   	
