<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> `Time-Out for Diversity' Needed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- American newspapers have a way to go before they  
reflect the racial and cultural mix of their communities, but they 
say they're making headway in assessing the problem and deciding 
how to tackle it. 
</P>
<P>
	Scores of newspapers around the country took a week in May to  
consider diversity of sources in news stories as an element of 
accuracy, in an exercise sponsored by the Associated Press Managing 
Editors and the American Society of Newspaper Editors. 
</P>
<P>
	Their follow-up reports were distributed here Thursday at Unity  
'99, an eight-day conference for minority journalists that ends 
Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everyone will not get the need for diversity, but they do  
understand making their stories accurate,'' The Dallas Morning News 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The APME and ASNE are calling for a second ``Time-Out for  
Diversity and Accuracy'' in February -- this time including 
journalism schools and the electronic media. 
</P>
<P>
	The spring round of soul-searching involved more than 140  
newspapers as well as domestic bureaus of The Associated Press, 
Reuters, Gannett News Service and the Knight Ridder-Tribune 
service. 
</P>
<P>
	Of the print organizations that signed on, 95 submitted  
follow-up reports -- 94 of them supporting the premise that 
diversity is essential to accuracy. 
</P>
<P>
	``If our newspapers are not inclusive enough to regularly  
portray the diversity of (their) communities, then we are 
presenting a fundamentally inaccurate report,'' said a statement by 
David Yarnold, managing editor of the San Jose Mercury News and 
APME diversity chairman, and Wanda S. Lloyd, his ASNE counterpart 
and news executive for planning at The Greenville News in South 
Carolina. 
</P>
<P>
	The Democrat and Chronicle in Rochester, N.Y., noted that it  
formed a diversity committee that sifts through top stories of the 
day ``to spot opportunities for diversity and mainstreaming.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The paper also changed the way it covered the city -- shifting  
from geographical areas to neighborhoods, and now has a reporter 
covering Rochester's large deaf community. 
</P>
<P>
	The Orange County Register in California and Newsday, in  
Melville, N.Y., created beats covering some underrepresented 
communities and such issues as immigration. 
</P>
<P>
	The Daily News Leader in Staunton, Va., offers a monthly $50  
bonus for the ``most consistent or most creative length a reporter 
or editor goes to in order to diversify our report.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Miami Herald has enlisted its marketing-promotions  
department ``to encourage minority organizations to help us tell 
their story,'' determining that ``we must take a proactive approach 
... rather than passively wait for them to seek us out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Dallas Morning News hopes to continue community tours begun  
during the May time-out: ``We've made it a priority for our 
staffers to go out to areas where they don't live to meet some 
folks they don't know.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Evaluations turned up some missed opportunities and  
inconsistencies. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some days showed a superb range of diverse sources,'' said The  
Des Moines Register in Iowa. ``Others seemed to rely heavily on 
administrative sources or white male news sources.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The San Francisco Examiner found a way to gauge its diversity  
effort: ``In a city that is now majority minority, we know that 
stories are not accurately portraying the community if they do not 
include Asian and Hispanic names.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
