<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Palladium, Coffee Futures Soar  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Grain and soybean futures fell sharply Thursday on the Chicago  
Board of Trade as continued ideal growing weather reinforced 
expectations farmers will harvest bumper crops. 
</P>
<P>
	In other markets, palladium and coffee futures soared.  
</P>
<P>
	Corn and soybean prices collapsed to new lows, with corn  
settling below $2 a bushel for the first time in years, as major 
farm-growing states basked in ideal weather for producing optimal 
crop yields. 
</P>
<P>
	The government is predicting farmers will harvest 9.45 billion  
bushels of corn this year, but market participants now suspect the 
figure will rise close to or above 10 billion bushels. Farmers are 
expected to harvest a record 2.88 billion bushels of soybeans, and 
that figure also is expected to go higher unless crops are affected 
by an early frost. 
</P>
<P>
	Prices have spiraled downward in recent months as investors note  
both U.S. and foreign inventories of corn and soybeans remain high 
despite recent increases in world export activity. Corn available 
for immediate delivery has fallen to its lowest price since 
December 1987, while soybeans are at their lowest levels since 
1972. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat futures also sank to their lowest since the early 1970s as  
harvesting of the winter wheat crop picked up steam. 
</P>
<P>
	Experts predict recovery in the entire farm sector will take a  
year or more, a fact that Thursday led the American Farm Bureau 
Federation to ask for $9 billion in new and previously announced 
federal disaster aid. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for December delivery fell 3 1/2 cents to $2.62 1/2 a bushel;  
December corn fell 4 3/4 cents to $1.99 1/2 a bushel; November soybeans 
fell 7 1/4 cents to $4.15 1/4 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Palladium futures soared on the New York Mercantile Exchange  
amid heavy dealer buying tied to concern Russia will not make large 
shipments of the metal this year. 
</P>
<P>
	While some market participants said Russia continues to make  
unannounced sales of the industrial metal to Western automobile and 
jewelry manufacturers, many investors continue to note the absence 
of long-term shipping contracts. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors also are concerned Russia will maintain a duty on  
metals exports that has halted most shipments since May. Russia 
accounts for nearly three-fourths of the world's palladium supply. 
</P>
<P>
	September palladium rose $9.85 to $331 an ounce. October  
platinum rose $3.80 to $352.20 an ounce. 
</P>
<P>
	Coffee futures surged on the Board of Trade of the City of New  
York as investors bet cooler weather heading into Brazilian growing 
regions would last long enough to cause damage to young trees and 
coffee flowers. 
</P>
<P>
	Forecasters predicted, however, that cooler temperatures would  
not translate into freezing weather over the next six days. Coffee 
prices have been rising and falling in recent months as weather 
forecasts hint at the possibility of cold weather in Brazil, the 
world's largest producer. 
</P>
<P>
	Brazil has harvested bumper crops and is on track to produce  
another large one unless foul weather strikes during its winter 
months. 
</P>
<P>
	Coffee prices also were supported after the Association of  
Coffee Producing Countries, which accounts for 75 percent of world 
shipments, agreed to limit exports to 50 million bags a year 
through June 2001. Some analysts were skeptical, however, since 
many of the member countries regularly exceed their quotas. 
</P>
<P>
	September arabica coffee rose 2.35 cents to 96.45 cents a pound.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
