<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court Rejects Ballot-Label Measure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- The state Supreme Court struck down as  
unconstitutional Thursday a law that would have identified on 
voting ballots whether candidates supported term limits. 
</P>
<P>
	Proposition 225, approved by 52 percent of voters in 1998,  
ordered California's legislators and congressional delegation to 
support a proposed U.S. constitutional amendment on term limits. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposed amendment would limit House members to three  
two-year terms, and senators to two six-year terms. 
</P>
<P>
	Furthermore, the proposition said politicians who did not  
support the amendment would have an inscription alongside their 
names on the ballot reading, ``Disregarded voters' instruction on 
term limits.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Thursday's unanimous ruling stated that the measure, with its  
coercive language, was an improper attempt to amend the U.S. 
Constitution. The Constitution states that only Congress and state 
legislatures can amend it. 
</P>
<P>
	Proposition 225 was scheduled to take statewide effect next  
year. It had already been used in a series of special elections in 
Alameda County, in the San Francisco Bay area. 
</P>
<P>
	It may have influenced the outcome of one close race, in which  
Green Party candidate Audie Bock upset former Oakland Mayor Elihu 
Harris for a state Assembly seat. Alongside the name of Harris, a 
Democrat, was the notation that he had declined to pledge to 
support term limits. 
</P>
<P>
	Commonly known as the ``scarlet letter'' law because of the  
ballot brand, Proposition 225 was sponsored by a group called U.S. 
Term Limits as part of a nationwide campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	An Arkansas law sponsored by the same group, limiting terms of  
the state's representatives in Congress, was ruled unconstitutional 
by the U.S. Supreme Court in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	That ruling invalidated similar laws elsewhere, including an  
initiative passed by California voters in 1992. Term limits for 
California legislators, approved by the voters in 1990, remain in 
effect. 
</P>
<P>
	Courts in eight other states have struck down ``scarlet letter''  
laws on a variety of grounds, including free speech, voting rights 
and interference with the constitutional amendment process. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
