<DOCNO> APW19990708.0040 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 09:50:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Olympic Leaders Suggest Budget Cuts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- Salt Lake Olympics leaders briefed board  
members today on $113 million worth of cuts to the $1.43 billion 
budget for the 2002 Winter Games. 
</P>
<P>
	Salt Lake Organizing Committee president Mitt Romney and chief  
operating officer Fraser Bullock said the cuts will shrink a $300 
million shortfall to $187 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Romney was confident of raising enough money to cover the  
smaller shortfall. He has been traveling around the country to meet 
with potential corporate sponsors. 
</P>
<P>
	``Their interest in the games is not shadowed by the scandal,''  
Romney told the SLOC board of trustees. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the budget cuts, Romney said SLOC will add two full-time  
sales people to drum up sponsorships. ``One thing you never cut 
back on is the people knocking on doors selling,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bullock emphasized that ``our first and foremost objective is to  
have great games.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The leaders' cuts are expected to be adopted by trustees in  
September, lowering the budget to $1.34 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're confident we're not going to be leaving unpaid bills for  
taxpayers or anyone else,'' Romney told a press conference 
Wednesday. ``We're back on track.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The proposed cutbacks come after a dollar-by-dollar review of  
the budget, said Bullock, who also serves as its chief financial 
officer. 
</P>
<P>
	The idea, Bullock said, was to slice everything but essential  
spending for athletes and to leave a legacy for Utah's youth. 
</P>
<P>
	The new budget would leave intact SLOC's $59 million repayment  
for sports facilities and a $40 million endowment for their 
operation after the games. It also would allow U.S. athletes to 
train at the Utah Winter Sports Park between now and the Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	Although an uproar from athletes caused Romney to back off from  
his earlier suggestion that the Utah Winter Sports Park be closed 
at long stretches before the Olympics, the park will skip building 
renovations and equipment purchases to save more than $3 million. 
</P>
<P>
	SLOC's managers came up with $169 million in cuts, but $56  
million of those are offset by added costs. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the additions corrected mistakes in the original budget  
written last year. It also includes such unforeseen costs as $5 
million in legal expenses because of the U.S. Justice Department's 
investigation of Salt Lake's bid committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Executives of the bid committee, the predecessor to the SLOC,  
have been accused of spending lavishly on International Olympic 
Committee members during the city's quest for the games, sparking 
scandal and now reform in the Olympic world. The Justice Department 
has been investigating for more than seven months but has not 
brought criminal charges. 
</P>
<P>
	The Salt Lake Tribune said today that the federal investigators  
have delivered the case to Justice Department prosecutors. The 
newspaper said the next phase could take weeks or months. 
</P>
<P>
	``We continue to investigate,''Justice spokesman Brian Steel  
said. ``There is no timetable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The budget cuts being proposed by the SLOC leaders include items  
amounting to $72 million that they would like to restore if the 
money can be found. The budget keeps a $136 million contingency in 
case expenses are higher than expected. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposed cutbacks are diverse.  
</P>
<P>
	There would be no information booths for spectators unless some  
group in the community steps forward, and the SLOC would spend $5 
million less on opening, closing and other ceremonies. 
</P>
<P>
	The SLOC would cut $2.3 million out of its budget for housing  
games officials, including a portion of IOC members' rooms, and 
$300,000 out of the opening IOC session before the games. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, the number of test events -- athletic contests that give  
staffers a chance to practice -- will be cut from 56 to 52, and the 
full staff, including volunteers, will work at only 17 of those, he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Only those employees who need to learn from the games in Sydney,  
Australia next summer will attend, and when members of the Olympic 
community come to Utah, they can expect fewer dinners. 
</P>
<P>
	Bullock said the budget analysis has been good for pinpointing  
ways money doesn't need to be spent. For example, $5.4 million is 
proposed to be cut from the telecommunications budget, in part 
because a sponsor donated excess cellular phones that bus drivers 
can use rather than radios. 
</P>
<P>
	An expensive and sophisticated software program for tracking  
personnel, which has failed at two prior games, can be replaced 
with off-the-shelf business software, Bullock said. ``I said, 
'simplify, simplify, simplify.'' 
</P>
<P>
	More than half of the cuts are proposed in two areas: getting  
rid of $38 million worth of inflation cushion and saving $30 
million in staff expenses, essentially 18 percent of what was 
budgeted. 
</P>
<P>
	Bullock said the committee has not yet put a number on the  
proposed staff size, since volunteers -- many of them executives on 
loan -- will replace workers and some of the savings comes in hiring 
people later than planned. The SLOC had expected to employ 750 at 
games time. 
</P>
<P>
	On the revenue side, Bullock said staff is considering selling  
more tickets. At present, 55 percent of the 1.6 million event 
tickets will be up for sale after the world's Olympic community and 
media use 45 percent. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
