<HEADLINE>  Moroccan Sets New Mile Run Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ROME (AP) -- Hicham El Guerrouj figures he can break the world  
record in the mile. His own record. The one he set Wednesday night. 
</P>
<P>
	The Moroccan shaved 1.26 seconds off the 6-year-old mark of  
Noureddine Morceli when he outran Kenyan Noah Ngeny down the final 
straightaway to win in 3 minutes, 43.13 seconds at the Golden Gala 
track and field meet. 
</P>
<P>
	``I could have gone as low as 3:42 without the comeback of  
Ngeny, who distracted me in the final 150 meters,'' El Guerrouj, 
24, said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Kenyan also went below Morceli's old record of 3:44.39,  
finishing second in 3:43.40. 
</P>
<P>
	Winner of the 1997 world championship in the 1,500 at Athens,  
Greece, El Guerrouj did not set limits to his ambition after his 
record performance Wednesday night. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope God continues to give me strength because I want to be  
the strongest in the world at all distances between 1,500 and 
5,000,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	El Guerrouj, who broke the world mark set by Morceli in the  
1,500 meters at Rome last year, plans to rest a week in Belgium 
before running the 1,500 in the next IAAF Golden League meet at 
Paris July 21. 
</P>
<P>
	By breaking one of track's most hallowed records, El Guerrouj  
stole the limelight from American sprinters. 
</P>
<P>
	World champion Maurice Greene set a meet record of 9.85 seconds  
in the 100 meters, .06 seconds off the world mark he set at Athens 
last month. 
</P>
<P>
	Michael Johnson, running his first 200 meters in six weeks, beat  
Ato Boldon, who had been the fastest over the distance this season. 
Johnson also set a meet record, 19.93, and said he was just glad 
``because I'm healthy again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He had missed the U.S. championships and the opening Golden  
League meet at Oslo, Norway, last week because of injury. 
</P>
<P>
	Marion Jones extended her four-year unbeaten streak in the  
women's 200 with her second consecutive victory in the Golden 
League series and remained in the running for the $1 million 
jackpot, which she shared last year with El Guerrouj and distance 
runner Haile Gebrselassie of Ethiopia. The money is split among all 
athletes who win the same event in all seven Golden League meets. 
</P>
<P>
	Other still in the running for the jackpot include Allen Johnson  
in the 110-meter hurdles, Wilson Kipketer in the 800, Erick Walder 
in the long jump, Bernard Barmasai in the 3,000 steeplechase, 
Gabriela Szabo in the women's 3,000 and Svetlana Masterkova in the 
women's 800. 
</P>
<P>
	The mile and the 100 meters do not count for the Golden League.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
