<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 22:10:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tobacco Co's Can Minimize Damage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- The tobacco industry is by no means backed into a  
corner as it tries to fend off possibly billions of dollars in 
damage awards, following a jury's verdict holding them responsible 
for making thousands of Florida smokers sick. 
</P>
<P>
	Cigarette makers have numerous legal options available to  
minimize the damage, and those defenses will emerge as the second 
phase of the massive class-action suit begins, legal experts said 
Thursday. Their fight could push back any final ruling from the 
jury on monetary damages for weeks or months. 
</P>
<P>
	In the first class-action lawsuit by smokers to go to trial, the  
jury on Wednesday said five tobacco companies engaged in ``extreme 
and outrageous conduct'' in making a defective product that causes 
emphysema, lung cancer and other illnesses. 
</P>
<P>
	In the next phases, the jury is to decide how much to award the  
lawsuit's nine original plaintiffs. The judge also must deal with 
the complex process of hearing claims of the other members of the 
class, which could number up to 500,000 sick smokers. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a lot of complicated stuff here,'' Stephan Landsman, a  
law professor at DePaul University, said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Perhaps the biggest threat to the suit is the industry's demand  
that the class action be decertified, meaning that the nine smokers 
who have sued would be barred from representing thousands of 
others. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts who folllow tobacco stocks for Wall Street securities  
firms anticipate the case will be decertified, noting Florida is 
the lone state to allow a class-action lawsuit by smokers to reach 
trial. 
</P>
<P>
	``It may take months,'' said David Adelman, a tobacco analyst  
for Morgan Stanley Dean Witter. ``It's going to be thrown out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The suit was filed in 1994 and certified as a class action two  
years later by a Florida appeals court. Circuit Judge Robert Kaye, 
who presided over the trial, will hold a hearing on the issue later 
this month, but is not expected to dissolve the class, meaning an 
appeal to higher courts is a near certainty. 
</P>
<P>
	Most courts thus far have rejected such class actions, saying  
that the reasons for smoking and the diseases are too different to 
bundle all smokers together. 
</P>
<P>
	In May, the U.S. Supreme Court rejected a class-action suit by  
six smokers in Pennsylvania. 
</P>
<P>
	Union health funds have filed class-action suits in 38 states.  
At least nine have been thrown out. 
</P>
<P>
	However, the Louisiana Supreme Court in February upheld a class  
of smokers and ex-smokers seeking money for medical testing. 
</P>
<P>
	In Miami-Dade County Circuit Court Thursday, attorneys and the  
judge discussed when to start the next phase of the case, in which 
evidence will be heard on the health damage suffered by the nine 
main plaintiffs. 
</P>
<P>
	Unlike in the earlier phase, tobacco company lawyers will be  
able to argue that these smokers bear personal responsibility by 
assuming the risk of smoking, knowing it wasn't healthful. 
</P>
<P>
	Since the jury has already sided with the smokers, that defense  
may fail, observers said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nobody's going to go into that case feeling sorry for the  
tobacco companies or even liking them,'' said Robert H. Alexander, 
Jr., co-chairman of the American Bar Association's product 
liability committee. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's still appropriate though for plaintiffs to be (held)  
responsible for creating the situation they're complaining about. 
It's a matter of how receptive the jury is to that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The plaintiffs told Judge Kaye Thursday they will be ready for  
the next phase in two weeks. The tobacco attorneys requested two 
months. Kaye could set the start date on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Florida plaintiffs want at least $200 billion in damages.  
Named as defendants are the nation's five biggest cigarette makers 
and two industry groups: Philip Morris, R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Co., 
Brown &AMP; Williamson Tobacco Corp., Lorillard Tobacco Co. and Liggett 
Group Inc., as well as the Council for Tobacco Research and the 
Tobacco Institute. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
