<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mystery of Solar Wind Solved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Particles streaming out from the sun catch a  
magnetic wave and surf across the solar system at almost two 
million miles an hour, a speed twice as fast as experts had 
predicted, according to new measurements from satellites. 
</P>
<P>
	The high speed flow from the sun, called the solar wind, has  
been a mystery to scientists for 37 years because they expected the 
particles to poke along at a mere one million miles an hour. 
</P>
<P>
	New measurements by two science satellites have solved the  
puzzle, researchers said Thursday, by showing that the solar wind's 
speed is boosted by magnetic waves that spiral out from the sun. 
</P>
<P>
	``The solar wind is accelerated out of the sun by magnetic waves  
in much the same way a surfer rides the waves to the shore,'' said 
John L. Kohl of the Smithsonian Astrophysical Observatory. 
</P>
<P>
	``These findings have revolutionized our understanding of the  
sun's outer atmosphere and the solar wind,'' said George Withbroe, 
a director in NASA's office of space science. 
</P>
<P>
	The solar wind is composed of electrically charged particles --  
atoms and electrons -- constantly flowing from the sun's outer 
atmosphere, or corona. The one-to-two million degree heat of the 
corona strips electrons from oxygen and hydrogen atoms, creating 
the charged particles. The stream of gas and electrons streak 
across the solar system, blasting unprotected planets, and racing 
outward into deep space, reaching a point, experts say, about nine 
billion miles from the sun. 
</P>
<P>
	A magnetic field surrounding the Earth protects it from the  
erosion of the solar wind, but most other planets are not as lucky. 
Experts, for instance, believe it was the solar wind that stripped 
away any atmosphere from Mars. 
</P>
<P>
	``The solar wind is staggering in size. Every eight hours, the  
sun puts out gas equal to all of the gases in the Earth's 
atmosphere,'' said Kohl. 
</P>
<P>
	Scientists had speculated about the solar wind, but its  
existence was not confirmed until the Mariner spacecraft took 
measurements in 1962, the same year that John Glenn made his first 
spaceflight. But the experts were surprised when the Mariner found 
the speed of the winds was twice as fast as expected. 
</P>
<P>
	Ironically, the high-speed mystery was solved with the help of a  
robot spacecraft hauled into orbit aboard the space shuttle that 
returned John Glenn to space last October. 
</P>
<P>
	The solution came from measurements taken by the Spartan 201  
spacecraft, carried into orbit by the shuttle, and by the SOHO, a 
sun-observing spacecraft jointly owned by NASA and the European 
Space Agency. 
</P>
<P>
	The Spartan and SOHO instruments detected oxygen and hydrogen  
atoms spiraling along vibrating magnetic fields that stream out 
from the corona. The atoms pick up speed from the push of the 
wavelike motion of the magnetic fields, Kohl said. 
</P>
<P>
	Two solar diameters out from the sun's outer atmosphere, the  
oxygen atoms are traveling at more than a million miles an hour, 
said Leonard Strachan, an astrophysicist at the Smithsonian 
Astrophysical Observatory. He said the hydrogen atoms travel at a 
lower speed, about 600,000 miles an hour. 
</P>
<P>
	By the time the solar wind reaches the vicinity of the Earth, he  
said, it is traveling at more than 500 miles per second, almost two 
million miles an hour. 
</P>
<P>
	To illustrate this speed, Strachan said it takes the shuttle  
about 90 minutes to orbit the Earth. The oxygen atoms in the solar 
wind, he said, could complete an Earth orbit in one minute. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
