<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 11:40:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Cabinet OKs Economic Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The Cabinet approved a sweeping plan today to  
transform the way Japan does business -- loosening restraints on 
competition, reducing government influence, and gearing the 
capitalist system to serve consumers, not producers. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposals, issued amid Japan's worst recession since World  
War II, reflect a new consensus among officials and normally 
intransigent bureaucrats that things must change, said Economic 
Planning Agency chief Taichi Sakaiya. 
</P>
<P>
	``The future Japan should not be led by government initiative  
but by competition of free individuals,'' Sakaiya said. ``It will 
be a different economy than before.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The changes are dictated by necessity. Record unemployment, a  
spiraling budget deficit and nine years of economic doldrums leave 
no doubt the economic system needs an overhaul. 
</P>
<P>
	``Even measures seen unfeasible three years ago, two years ago,  
last year are being implemented,'' said Sakaiya, promoting the plan 
to make markets more efficient, expand consumer options and give 
better returns to investors. 
</P>
<P>
	Sakaiya said the biggest change is in the role of bureaucrats,  
who during the 1980s were credited with engineering an economic 
miracle by focusing resources on strategic industries. 
</P>
<P>
	The government will no longer actively pick the economy's  
winners and losers, nor coddle endangered industries. It will now 
leave most of that to markets and private enterprise. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, the plan is as short on details as it is sweeping in  
vision. 
</P>
<P>
	Pressed for specifics, Sakaiya pointed to current deregulation  
of the financial sector and said a dozen action plans were in the 
works for some undetermined date. 
</P>
<P>
	He stressed that Thursday's report would not die as similar  
recommendations had before in the face of bureaucratic resistance. 
</P>
<P>
	``This report ... is a Cabinet decision,'' Sakaiya said.  
``Therefore, this report has set the fundamental direction of 
future policy and is binding on all agencies.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The new guidelines come after unemployment hit a record of 4.8  
percent in March and April, though it eased to 4.6 percent in May. 
In another optimistic sign, consumers are already buying more 
computers and compact cars and plan to travel more this summer, 
according to a survey released Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The country is struggling with its deepest recession in 50  
years, and total government debt has outstripped Japan's $4 
trillion economy. 
</P>
<P>
	The government has earmarked more than $500 billion this year  
for tax cuts, spending on roads and bridges and other measures to 
stimulate the economy. Government spending helped push Japan's 
gross domestic product -- the measure of all goods and services 
produced within its borders -- up 1.9 percent in the first quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	Also Thursday, Japan's Cabinet approved $4.25 billion  
supplementary budget to create 720,000 new jobs by subsidizing 
companies and nonprofit organizations to hire workers who have lost 
jobs during the recession. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990708.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 08:23:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Monte Wants Tyson, Who Doesn't? </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Heavyweights, good, bad and mediocre, used to hope to get a  
fight against Mike Tyson because it got them attention and their 
biggest paycheck. 
</P>
<P>
	Now they want Tyson, not only for the celebrity and the money,  
but because his iron cloak of intimidation turns out to be made of 
cloth. 
</P>
<P>
	One who wants to fight Tyson when the former undisputed champion  
comes back yet again, probably in October, is Monte Barrett. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mike ought to give me an opportunity, just like someone gave  
him an opportunity,'' Barrett said. 
</P>
<P>
	It, however, is not going to happen for the 28-year-old New  
Yorker with a 20-0 record and a gift of gab. 
</P>
<P>
	``Not now,'' said Shelly Finkel, a Tyson advisor. ``Monte's a  
sweet kid. I know him, but it's too early.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Perhaps it is. Barrett didn't turn pro until he was 25, and he  
could use seasoning against tougher competition than he has yet 
met. 
</P>
<P>
	On the other hand, Francois Botha proved Tyson, who turned 33  
June 30, is very vulnerable at this stage of his career. Botha got 
knocked out by a perfect right-hand punch in the fifth round Jan. 
16, but until then he made Tyson look small and slow. 
</P>
<P>
	So it might not be good business at this time to match a hungry  
fighter, who is 6-foot-3 and a good athlete, against Tyson, who 
cannot afford to lose. Nor can the money men behind him afford to 
have him lose. 
</P>
<P>
	Like Tyson, Barrett also has a promotional deal with America  
Presents. The promoter, of course, has a lot more money tied up in 
Tyson, who also has deals with Showtime and the MGM Grand at Las 
Vegas. 
</P>
<P>
	The affable Barrett, married with three children, took up boxing  
at age 21 and says he'll be out of it by age 33. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to have more kids and I want to enjoy life,'' Barrett  
said. Once into boxing, however, a lot of guys have had trouble 
getting out. 
</P>
<P>
	Barrett competed in basketball, baseball, gymnastics (floor  
exercises) and football at John Adams High School in Queens and was 
a good enough linebacker to be offered scholarships to Grambling, 
East Carolina and Southern Mississippi. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was a Prop 48 and I went Westchester Community College for a  
year,'' Barrett said. ``Then they dropped football and I dropped 
out and went to work full time in construction.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One day Barrett was lifting weights, he said, ``and this guy was  
hustling guys in the gym, telling them give me $15 a day, I'll 
teach you how to box.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Barrett started in amateur boxing under 83-year-old trainer Al  
Davis, who, with Jimmy Glenn, trains him as a pro. 
</P>
<P>
	After posting a 37-3 record, with 24 knockouts, Barrett turned  
pro in September 1996 under the management of Joe DeGuardia. 
</P>
<P>
	At the time he was preparing to become a pro, he was introduced  
to promoter Don King. 
</P>
<P>
	Barrett said King offered him a $70,000-$80,000 contract, a  
condo and a salary of $900 a week. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked the length of the contract, Barrett said, ``Forever.''  
</P>
<P>
	Barrett said that on his wedding day June 7, 1995, King flew him  
to Ohio to meet Tyson at his boxing camp at Orwell. 
</P>
<P>
	``We talked about people we know and about boxing,'' Barrett  
said of the meeting. ``We played basketball. He was putting dents 
in the backboard, but they (the shots) weren't going in.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The shot Monte Barrett wants is one at Tyson in the ring.  

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
