<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Argentine Truckers End Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) -- More than 200,000 Argentine  
truckers began returning to work today, ending a nationwide strike 
that disrupted shipments of everything from food to gas to 
medicine. 
</P>
<P>
	The crisis eased late Wednesday when Argentine lawmakers agreed  
to delay the start of a controversial new tax on cars, trucks and 
other vehicles until November -- weeks after the country's 
presidential election in October. 
</P>
<P>
	The 98-81 vote by the lower house of Congress came on the third  
day of the strike, in which long caravans of trucks parked 
alongside key highways and refused to deliver goods. 
</P>
<P>
	The controversial tax -- up to 1.5 percent of the value of their  
vehicles -- was adopted earlier this year in an attempt to raise 
$700 million for much-needed increases in teachers' salaries. 
</P>
<P>
	Disgruntled drivers said the new tax amounted to an unfair  
burden of thousands of dollars on their livelihood. 
</P>
<P>
	No major violence was reported from the three-day strike in  
which drivers slowed traffic but did not block highways outright. 
There were reports of scattered incidents, however, with one truck 
carrying dairy goods shot at Tuesday night and a driver of a 
delivery van punched by a group partially blocking a road. 
</P>
<P>
	The three-day stoppage slowed or halted deliveries of gasoline,  
milk and other foodstuffs in some areas, but shipments were back to 
normal on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	President Carlos Menem's government suggested he could go so far  
as to declare a state of siege if the strike had persisted. 
</P>
<P>
	After hours of wrangling, congressional lawmakers voted to  
postpone the deadline for paying the vehicle tax until Nov. 15. 
Senate approval was expected to follow, but was considered 
virtually a formality. 
</P>
<P>
	Argentina has been weathering a recession and continues to  
battle high unemployment, which is 12.4 percent and climbing. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
