<DOCNO> APW19990708.0058 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 08:20:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lighthouse Nears Ocean-Safe Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BUXTON, N.C. (AP) -- Cape Hatteras Lighthouse has made most of  
the move from its old perch on a badly eroded beach ahead of 
schedule. It will take several more weeks for it to settle in at 
its new home. 
</P>
<P>
	Movers still must slide the lighthouse a final 5 feet of the  
2,900-foot trip, then ease it on rails over a concrete pad that 
will be part of the new foundation. A contractor said today that 
crews worked late Wednesday and probably will spend today getting 
the pad ready to receive its huge occupant. 
</P>
<P>
	The 208-foot tower, the tallest brick lighthouse in the United  
States, was moved about 151 feet on Wednesday. Workers spent most 
of the day surveying the final distance and laying wooden supports 
for the moving rails over the foundation. Until this point, the 
rails rested on a gravel roadway built for the move. 
</P>
<P>
	Over the next two months, crews will build a new foundation of  
up to 140,000 bricks for the spiral-striped tower. 
</P>
<P>
	By Wednesday, movers had not yet decided whether the lighthouse  
will be pushed over its new base on Friday or Monday -- ending its 
move to a safer spot 1,600 feet from the rough Atlantic surf. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Park Service decided to spend $10 million to move  
the 4,800-ton landmark before it tumbled into the sea. Some feared 
the move might cause the 129-year-old brick tower to crack or fall 
over, but the lighthouse appeared to be in good shape. 
</P>
<P>
	The move was expected to take four to six weeks, but it took  
only three. 
</P>
<P>
	The lighthouse once guided ships in the treacherous waters off  
Cape Hatteras, known as the Graveyard of the Atlantic. Electronic 
and satellite navigation have superseded its beacon, though the 
light still burned nightly until it was extinguished March 1 for 
the first time since 1950. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Park Service plans to relight the lighthouse on  
Labor Day and open it to the public again next Memorial Day. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
