<DOCNO> APW19990708.0059 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 03:40:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Elite Pros Skipping Milwaukee Open  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MILWAUKEE (AP) -- Like the city in which it is played, the  
Greater Milwaukee Open is working-class and relatively unglamorous 
-- and the working-class, unglamorous golfers in its field like it 
that way. 
</P>
<P>
	The tour's elite players almost never visit Brown Deer Park, the  
public course on which the 32-year-old tournament has been played 
since 1994. The GMO, as the event is widely known, is a chance for 
golf's second-tier players to fatten their wallets and hone their 
games. 
</P>
<P>
	Through schedule changes, venue changes and a yearly struggle to  
attract a topflight field, the event, which begins today, has 
survived and thrived. Tournament director Dan Croak said ticket 
sales are better than last year, and the purse is a record $2.3 
million, with the winner taking home $414,000. 
</P>
<P>
	This year the event was bumped from its traditional Labor Day  
weekend slot to mid-July on the tour schedule, to follow the 
Western Open in suburban Chicago during the tour's summer sweep of 
the Midwest. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a great time to have a golf tournament in Wisconsin,''  
Croak said. ``We were very pleased with the adjustment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	However, next week's event is the British Open, one of golf's  
four majors. Many pros like to take the week off, or travel to the 
British Isles early to combat jet-lag and work on their games. 
</P>
<P>
	But the GMO refuses to see the scheduling move as a setback.  
Croak noted that the tournament's results now count in the Ryder 
Cup points standings, which determine the field for the biennial 
showdown of the world's top golfers. Previously, Ryder Cup teams 
already were named before the tournament was played. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our field is better this year than it was last year, and I  
think it's partly due to the fact the tournament is more important 
to golfers now,'' Croak said. 
</P>
<P>
	Several prominent golfers have visited Brown Deer. Tiger Woods  
made his professional debut here in 1996, and John Daly and Vijay 
Singh both have played in Milwaukee recently. 
</P>
<P>
	The biggest name in the 1999 field is Minnesota native Tom  
Lehman, who is ranked 25th in the world but hasn't won in America 
since 1996. Only two players who have won on tour this year, Carlos 
Franco and Duffy Waldorf, will play. 
</P>
<P>
	Defending champion Jeff Sluman will return, but the galleries'  
sentimental favorite again this year likely will be Steve Stricker 
from Madison, Wis., who was the runner-up to Sluman at the GMO last 
year and finished fifth at last month's U.S. Open. 
</P>
<P>
	Stricker's caddie will be his wife, Nicki. Last year she was too  
busy to tote her husband's bag; she was giving birth to their first 
child. 
</P>
<P>
	Certain golfers on tour wouldn't miss Milwaukee for the world.  
Mark Calcavecchia has played in the last 18 GMOs, while Loren 
Roberts -- who plays so well in the tournament, fellow pro Skip 
Kendall once called it ``the Loren Roberts annuity'' -- has been 
here each year since 1983. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have players who are very loyal to us because we put on a  
good show, and we take care of the players,'' Croak said. ``That's 
the only secret to getting players to play in your event.'' 
</P>
<P>
	John Maginnes will play in the GMO a week after his caddie,  
Garland Dempsey, collapsed during the third round of the Western 
Open. Dempsey is still hospitalized, and tournament officials 
weren't sure Tuesday who would carry Maginnes' bag. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
