<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> US Waiting Answer On Panda Offer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The National Zoo expects to hear from China  
next month about the zoo's offer to pay for borrowing two baby 
pandas, a zoo official said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Zoo officials who traveled to China with the offer ``were  
received warmly, but no commitments were made,'' said Robert J. 
Hoage, chief of public affairs for the zoo. 
</P>
<P>
	Benjamin Beck, the zoo's associate director for biological  
programs; Devra Kleiman, a senior scientist; and Lisa Stevens, 
curator of pandas and primates, spent a week in China just before 
Fourth of July weekend. They are to provide details of their trip 
at a news conference Friday. Officials with the Chinese Embassy 
could not be reached for comment. 
</P>
<P>
	The zoo's one remaining panda, Hsing-Hsing, is 28 years old and  
suffers from severe arthritis and an irreversible kidney condition. 
Zoo officials are not predicting how long he will live, although 
Hoage said pandas in the wild rarely live past their early 20s. 
</P>
<P>
	Hsing-Hsing is feeling better since he's been on medicine for  
arthritis and anemia, antibiotics and a ``Pepcid-like'' stomach 
pill, Hoage said. He's eating about 20 pounds of bamboo a day along 
with sweet potatoes, apples, carrots and a gruel containing cottage 
cheese, rice, honey and vitamins and minerals. 
</P>
<P>
	Hsing-Hsing and another panda, Ling Ling, were diplomatic gifts  
from China in 1972 after President Nixon's historic visit. Ling 
Ling died of hardening of the arteries seven years ago, and none of 
the pair's five cubs survived. 
</P>
<P>
	An estimated 1,000 giant pandas live in the wild in China, their  
only native habitat, and 100 live in Chinese zoos. Since they are 
endangered, China no longer gives pandas as gifts and does not sell 
pandas overseas. 
</P>
<P>
	Zoo Atlanta recently reached an $11 million agreement to lease a  
pair of 2-year-old pandas as part of a 10-year study on why pandas 
are not interested in mating while in captivity. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Zoo, one of the few U.S. zoos that charge no  
admission, cannot afford $11 million, Hoage said. It hopes China 
will accept its offer of $2.5 million over 10 years, along with 
proposals for extensive, collaborative educational and research 
projects, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	They include the developing a national census of giant pandas in  
the wild, a radio tracking and satellite monitoring system and 
hormonal research on what makes it difficult to breed pandas in 
captivity. 
</P>
<P>
	The zoo anticipates possibly as much as $1 million a year in  
financial returns from the pandas through increased concession 
sales if China accepts its offer. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990708.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 16:00:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dock Workers Back, Talks To Resume </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Dock workers who left ships and trucks  
idling for two days at the Port of Oakland returned to work 
Thursday as longshoremen laboring without a contract bedeviled 
management with other tactics across the West Coast. 
</P>
<P>
	``We now have slowdowns at all major ports up and down the coast  
-- Seattle, Tacoma, Portland, Oakland, Los Angeles and Long Beach,'' 
Phil Resch, a spokesman for the management's Pacific Maritime 
Association, said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	By not showing early or working through their lunches, the  
union's 14,500 workers will prevent some ports from keeping their 
gates open and freight moving efficiently throughout the day, Resch 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	It's too early to tell how much the tactics will cost  
businesses, but they were already having an impact at the West 
Coast ports, which collectively handled $266 billion in goods last 
year, the PMA said. 
</P>
<P>
	One cargo ship leaving Seattle Thursday was less than full  
because its containers couldn't be loaded in time, said that port's 
director, Imbert Matthee. 
</P>
<P>
	The union, which began refusing the overtime in Los Angeles and  
Long Beach, Calif., Tuesday morning, expanded the action to all 
ports on Thursday, Resch said. 
</P>
<P>
	``What they're not doing is working extra,'' said Steve  
Stallone, a spokesman for the International Longshore and Warehouse 
Union in San Francisco. ``They feel they're not getting good faith 
from the PMA right now in negotiations, so why should they be 
busting their butts?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Negotiations on a new three-year contract were set to resume  
Friday morning, both sides said. The old contract expired on July 
1. 
</P>
<P>
	The walkout in Oakland, the nation's fourth-largest port, and  
the lack of flextime work at other ports could eventually harm 
retailers importing time-sensitive fashion merchandise and prevent 
manufacturers from getting just-in-time parts deliveries. 
</P>
<P>
	But many companies anticipated labor trouble, planning as early  
as last January to move up shipments or deliver them by air or 
through East Coast ports this month, said Robin Lanier, a lobbyist 
for the Mass Retail Association in Arlington, Va. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was a lot of concern there might be a strike that would  
shut the whole West Coast down,'' she said. ``The disaster 
everybody's been wringing their hands about for six months really 
hasn't happened here, but it was enough to have lit up my phone 
yesterday.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The impact was more immediate in Oakland, where the Port  
Authority collects fees for cranes, dockage and other services that 
can average $60,000 per ship, said Roberta Bradley, a port 
spokeswoman. 
</P>
<P>
	The walkout by the port's 1,400 workers forced Oakland-bound  
ships to slow down across the Pacific or wait at anchor in San 
Francisco Bay. Giant cranes stood motionless and deliveries of 
everything from California fruit and computer components to 
Hawaiian cows sat on the docks and ships. 
</P>
<P>
	Stallone said the walkout was spontaneous and not connected to  
the contract talks. He said it was a safety issue -- management's 
refusal to hire an extra worker under each crane to keep track of 
containers being moved. 
</P>
<P>
	But the PMA, which asked the National Labor Relations Board to  
force the Oakland workers back to the docks, considers the timing 
of the safety request to be suspicious, Resch said. 
</P>
<P>
	``They've been working every day, year-in and year-out without  
this new request that they had. Now all of a sudden they bring it 
up as an issue,'' Resch said. ``Our first question is, is it a 
safety issue or something else?'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
