<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Scramble for World Cup Tickets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Soccer moms and celebrities were leading the  
ticket broker scramble for seats to Saturday's sold-out Women's 
World Cup finale at the Rose Bowl. 
</P>
<P>
	``Maybe half the seats we're selling are going to parents  
getting seats for their daughters,'' said Sandy Simon, owner of 
Good Time Tickets in Hollywood. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 88,000 tickets have been sold for the games pitting  
the United States against China in the final and Brazil and Norway 
in the third place showdown. 
</P>
<P>
	Brokers were getting $75 to $500 for nosebleed seats and $600 to  
$1,000 for the best seats. Newspaper classified ads were jammed 
with private party ads listing tickets from $75 to $1,000. 
</P>
<P>
	On the Internet, a ticket was being offered for $800.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's as big or bigger than a Rose Bowl or Super Bowl game,''  
said Simon, who furiously answered telephones with another 14 
employees taking orders even before Good Time opened its doors. 
</P>
<P>
	The pace may have matched the Super Bowl frenzy for Simon, but  
the prices have a ways to go. Brokered ticket prices for Super 
Bowls have reached $2,500 while scalper prices have reached $4,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Simon said many of his clients belonged to the celebrity crowd.  
``They are bringing their kids, I mean, multi-Academy Award-type 
people,'' he said Thursday, refusing to name names. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're having a lot of fun,'' said John Bober, manager of Tyson  
Ticket Service in Beverly Hills. ``We're selling to families. They 
are taking the kids, the soccer clubs. We sell Dodger tickets to 
the same people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rather than celebrities, Bober said his customers were ``more  
Joe Blow.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Of the 8.6 million soccer players in the United States, 2.5  
million are girls, according to American Youth Soccer Organization. 
About 635,000 boys and girls, ages 5 to 18, play in AYSO's 1,000 
leagues nationwide. 
</P>
<P>
	Hotels and motels around the Rose Bowl have been booked for  
weeks and restaurants are jammed. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've been telling people this event was going to be a big  
deal, but we never thought it would be like this,'' World Cup 
spokesman Steve Vanderpool said. ``It just blows us away at the 
organizing committee.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Credentials have been given to 2,000 media members, including  
300 international journalists. Vanderpool said the thrill for him 
Saturday will be the sound of the crowd with all those youngsters 
in the stands. 
</P>
<P>
	``Instead of a roar, it's a kind of a shriek. It's more like the  
Beatles walking out at Shea Stadium,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	World Cup mania is easily explained, Vanderpool said.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's the common game played by the world. You don't have to be  
big or tall to play. You can be any size and be a good soccer 
player,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Brittany Whitworth, an 18-year-old Glendora resident who's  
played soccer since she was 8, won't get to see the United States 
vs. China matchup. She has to work. 
</P>
<P>
	``But my little sister is going. She's shagging balls. It's all  
sold out and everyone wants to go. I'll just have to watch it on 
TV,'' the teen-ager said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Yes, every AYSO soccer girl wants to go to this. It's a treat  
for us to have all these tickets to sell,'' Simon said, noting that 
his supply was ``getting slim.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Police warned fans without tickets to stay away from the Rose  
Bowl. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm sure there will be scalpers on the premises,'' Simon said.  
``The only risk you take there is somebody could print up a dupe. 
Also, somebody could purchase stolen tickets.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
