<HEADLINE> Poland Lets Coca Cola-Resume Output </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WARSAW, Poland (AP) -- A government agency gave approval Thursday  
for Coca-Cola to resume production at a plant shut down last week 
when bacteria was found in plastic bottles of mineral water. 
</P>
<P>
	But a Coca-Cola spokeswoman said the company would continue its  
own testing Friday at the plant near Wroclaw in southwest Poland 
and hoped to announce the resumption of production next week. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have the go-ahead to be able to begin producing,'' said  
Sonya Soutus, Coca-Cola's Central Europe communications manager. 
``We still want to finish our internal testing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Soutus said details of what caused the bacteria contamination  
would be announced when the company completed its testing. 
</P>
<P>
	Coca-Cola recalled an estimated 180,000 half-liter plastic  
bottles of Bonaqa Plus mineral water last week because of the 
bacteria, which was found to be nonhazardous. It also shut down the 
bottling plant near Wroclaw on July 2 to determine how the 
contamination occurred. 
</P>
<P>
	The recall was the company's second in Poland in a week, after  
all of its one-third liter returnable glass bottles were pulled 
back because of mold found inside some of them. Coca-Cola then 
announced more stringent cleaning methods for the returnable 
bottles. 
</P>
<P>
	No illness has been reported in Poland from Coca-Cola beverages,  
and the company said it took the extraordinary measures of 
recalling its products to maintain consumer confidence. 
</P>
<P>
	The problems in Poland came a few weeks after more than 200  
people complained of illness after drinking Coca-Cola products in 
Belgium and France, forcing the company to make a costly recall of 
its beverages there. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
