<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Holbrooke Nomination Hits More Snags </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Richard Holbrooke's troubled nomination to be  
U.N. ambassador is drawing new opposition, with at least four 
Republican senators now signaling their intentions to hold up a 
floor vote. 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott of Mississippi, Mitch  
McConnell of Kentucky and George Voinovich of Ohio have joined Sen. 
Charles Grassley of Iowa in putting so-called ``holds'' on the 
nomination, various sources said Wednesday. The nomination has been 
delayed more than a year. 
</P>
<P>
	One Republican Senate source suggested as many as six senators  
may be working to delay or block the nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, an effort to select a new envoy to China to replace  
former Sen. James Sasser hit an unexpected snag. In an apparent 
lapse of protocol, the administration neglected to notify the 
Chinese about the proposed nomination of retired Adm. Joseph W. 
Prueher before it became widely reported two months ago, officials 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Still angry over the U.S. bombing of their embassy in  
Yugoslavia, Chinese officials are now voicing displeasure over 
Prueher's role in a U.S. naval operation in the Straits of Taiwan 
in 1996 during a tense period in U.S.-Chinese relations, according 
to congressional and diplomatic sources who spoke on the condition 
of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	Lott and McConnell want to apply pressure on the White House to  
nominate an Ohio law professor for a ``Republican'' position on the 
Federal Election Commission, said the sources. 
</P>
<P>
	The professor, Bradley A. Smith of Capital University in  
Columbus, Ohio, had been recommended by Republican leaders for the 
vacancy on the commission, which is divided between two Democrats 
and two Republicans. 
</P>
<P>
	Lott spokesman John Czwartacki declined to comment on the holds.  
By tradition, any senator can block, at least for a time, any 
nomination, anonymously if he or she chooses. 
</P>
<P>
	However, on the subject of the FEC vacancy, Czwartacki noted  
that presidents traditionally give leaders of the other party the 
prerogative in picking their party's FEC representatives. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've never seen a White House that tried to pick the other  
party's nominees,'' Czwartacki said. 
</P>
<P>
	Voinovich is seeking to delay the nomination for other reasons,  
said his aide, Mike Dawson. Not only does the Ohio Republican want 
to make sure there is a roll call vote on the nomination, but ``he 
has concerns about Holbrooke's nomination for policy reasons,'' 
Dawson said. 
</P>
<P>
	The fourth senator, Sen. Charles Grassley, R-Iowa, had already  
put a hold on Holbrooke to protest what he contends is State 
Department retribution against government employee at the U.N. 
mission in New York for telling members of Congress about waste and 
inefficiency at the international organization. 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Democrats said they hoped the new delays would be short  
lived, and characterized the new holds as an attempt by GOP leaders 
to exert leverage over the White House. 
</P>
<P>
	Holbrooke, a former ambassador to Germany and assistant  
secretary of state, is the architect of the 1995 Bosnia peace 
accord. 
</P>
<P>
	At the White House, spokesman Barry Toiv called Holbrooke  
``supremely qualified'' for the position. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is essential to our national interest that he be put in  
place and the Senate ought to vote on his nomination as soon as 
possible,'' Toiv said. The nomination last week won the support of 
the Senate Foreign Relations Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	On the Beijing post, failing to give China a preview of  
Prueher's selection was a major diplomatic breach of protocol, 
suggest some officials close to the process. 
</P>
<P>
	Yu Shuning, a spokesman for the Chinese Embassy here, said,  
``We've gotten information only from the media. We have not been 
officially notified yet.'' 
</P>
<P>
	However, a spokesman for the White House National Security  
Council, David Leavy, on Wednesday disputed that the delay amounted 
to a diplomatic snub of China. He noted that even though the 
proposed nomination had been widely reported, and confirmed by some 
administration officials, it still had not been announced formally. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're vetting him (Prueher). Our legal office is vetting the  
nomination. When we're done with the process, then we'll move 
forward,'' Leavy said. ``The Chinese don't have a problem'' with 
that. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, State Department spokesman James Foley said the  
United States has delivered a detailed written report to China to 
support its insistence that the May 7 embassy bombing was 
accidental. The bombing killed three Chinese journalists and 
injured 20 other people. 
</P>
<P>
	The Chinese have called the U.S. explanation, earlier delivered  
in person by U.S. diplomat Thomas Pickering, unpersuasive. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will (also) inform the Chinese of all appropriate  
information on any further results of our internal review with 
respect to the question of whether any disciplinary action is 
called for,'' Foley said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
