<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Morris: Pirates Rookie of Year? </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Three months into his first major league  
season, Warren Morris of the Pittsburgh Pirates has received 
perhaps the ultimate compliment for a young second baseman. 
</P>
<P>
	He has earned the Bill Mazeroski seal of approval.  
</P>
<P>
	Mazeroski, regarded as the best-fielding second baseman in  
history, got his first in-person look at Morris this week after 
working with him for 10 days early in spring training. 
</P>
<P>
	Mazeroski's assessment: Good field, good hit, good power, good  
player, good person. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's going to be around a long time,'' said Mazeroski, who  
watches most of his baseball on TV. ``He handles himself well. He's 
got a good head on his shoulders, and he knows how to adjust.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mazeroski also has noticed a little of himself in Morris, even  
if it would be out of character for Mazeroski to discuss it in 
detail. 
</P>
<P>
	Morris is a ballplayer, not a talker, just like Mazeroski was as  
the Pirates' slick-fielding but relatively soft-spoken second 
baseman from 1956-72. 
</P>
<P>
	``He knows how to listen,'' Mazeroski said. ``A lot of the  
younger players today don't know how to do that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Morris also knows how to hit -- not just for average, but for  
power. Like a player named Mazeroski, still the only man to end 
Game 7 of a World Series with a home run, in 1960 against the New 
York Yankees. 
</P>
<P>
	Like Maz, like Morris.  
</P>
<P>
	Morris duplicated Mazeroski in the drama department, ending the  
1996 College World Series with a series-winning homer, his only 
homer all season for LSU. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm flattered to be compared to him in any way,'' said Morris,  
who has helped the surprising Pirates stay around .500 all season. 
``Nothing in me is about individual records or things of that 
nature, I do things quietly.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Except at the plate. With a .294 average, 9 homers and 43 RBIs  
going into Thursday night's game against the Chicago Cubs -- 
excellent power numbers for a middle infielder -- he is being 
mentioned along with Joe McEwing of St. Louis, Preston Wilson and 
Alex Gonzalez of Florida, and Benny Agbayani of the New York Mets 
for the NL Rookie of the Year award. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pirates never have had a Rookie of the Year, not even  
Mazeroski, who hit .255 as a parttime player in 1956. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not campaigning for it,'' Morris said. ``What are you  
trying to do, jinx me? It's way too early to talk about it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So far, Morris has been exactly what general manager Cam Bonifay  
predicted when he traded right-hander Esteban Loaiza to Texas for 
Morris, then a Double-A player, nearly a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Morris doesn't get rattled when he makes a mistake -- and, with  
only seven errors, he has made few. He has the ability to shake off 
a poor night, a perquisite in a sport where the season lasts 162 
games. 
</P>
<P>
	He also has fielded exceptionally well, as evidenced by the  
Pirates' 104 double plays -- the second most in the NL and only 57 
fewer than they had last season. 
</P>
<P>
	``The most important thing is he seems to adjust to breaking  
pitches and fastballs, and a lot of being successful in the big 
leagues is being able to make adjustments,'' manager Gene Lamont 
said. ``You make adjustments, they make adjustments, then you have 
to adjust again and he's been able to do it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Like most minor leaguers, Morris watched a lot of baseball on TV  
before reaching the majors. But he tried not to be too intimidated 
or overwhelmed by the skill level of the game's top players. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't have any preconceived notions going into this  
season,'' he said. ``On TV, every home runs looks like it's 800 
feet, nobody makes errors and they're the fastest runners you've 
ever seen. My attitude was that I would go there and do my best and 
if things didn't work out, so be it.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
