<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gun Dealer's Links Investigated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PEORIA, Ill. (AP) -- Investigators are looking into whether  
racist gunman Benjamin Smith had help carrying out his deadly 
rampage against Jews, blacks and Asians. 
</P>
<P>
	The FBI is questioning Smith's family and friends and is probing  
his ties to the World Church of the Creator, a hate group based in 
East Peoria which Smith followed, said Attorney General Janet Reno 
in Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, federal prosecutors said they could find no evidence  
that the man who sold Smith his weapons, Donald Fiessinger, had 
ties to extremist groups. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal agents had said earlier that they were investigating  
whether Fiessinger, 64, supplied guns to other racist extremists. 
Fiessinger faces a charge of selling firearms without a federal 
firearms permit for the sale of several guns, including two 
handguns bought by Smith. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith is believed to have used the guns on a three-day killing  
spree through Illinois and Indiana that targeted blacks, Jews and 
Asians. Two people were killed and nine others injured. 
</P>
<P>
	The spree ended Sunday with Smith's apparent suicide following a  
police chase. 
</P>
<P>
	But investigators still want to know if Smith had help.  
</P>
<P>
	However, under rules written in the 1970s to curb unwarranted  
FBI probes of civil rights groups and anti-Vietnam War groups, the 
Justice Department must discover evidence of criminal conduct 
before an investigation can be begin against the World Church of 
the Creator. 
</P>
<P>
	``The standard is that we have got to have a reasonable  
indication of criminal conduct on the part of the group,'' Reno 
said. ``And we are going to review all the issues with respect to 
this matter to determine what would be appropriate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Matt Hale, the leader of the World Church of the Creator, was  
interviewed Wednesday by FBI agents at the East Peoria house where 
he lives with his parents, a middle-class home that doubles as the 
headquarters for the hate group. 
</P>
<P>
	Besides Hale, agents have interviewed Smith's parents and his  
ex-girlfriend. 
</P>
<P>
	Hale said he has evidence that Smith was acting on his own: a  
certified letter allegedly handwritten by Smith and postmarked July 
2 from the Chicago suburb of Wilmette. It states that Smith was 
breaking from the church because he was ``unable and unwilling to 
follow a legal revolution of values.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Smith could not legally buy handguns because an ex-girlfriend  
had obtained a protective order against him. But records in 
Fiessinger's home show that he sold cheap, low-caliber handguns to 
more than 50 people over two years. 
</P>
<P>
	Fiessinger became the target of a federal investigation in June  
after agents learned he was allegedly selling guns illegally from 
his apartment in Pekin, a central Illinois town south of Peoria. 
Agents raided his apartment in July, but did not arrest Fiessinger 
because he was cooperative. 
</P>
<P>
	After reading a newspaper description of Smith on Tuesday,  
Fiessinger called investigators to say he sold Smith two pistols in 
June. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
