<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Eddie Jones Sues Ex-Agent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Charlotte Hornets guard Eddie Jones has sued  
his former agent, saying that a former employee of the agent stole 
more than $1 million from Jones and has not repaid all the money. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit, filed in April in U.S. District Court in Camden,  
N.J., claims that a former bookkeeper and assistant of agent Sal 
DiFazio stole the money from Jones by depositing it in the accounts 
of two other professional basketball clients of the company. The 
suit doesn't explain how the money was later taken from those 
accounts. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit said Atlantic Sports Management Inc. and DiFazio  
have repaid about $960,000 to Jones, a former Temple University 
player. Jones, who also seeks more than $500,000 in compensatory 
damages and interest, contends he is still owed more than $540,000. 
</P>
<P>
	DiFazio disputes the dollar figure, saying an auditor for  
Atlantic Sports has told him the amount is ``substantially less.'' 
He has until July 19 to file a response with the federal court. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have taken every possible measure to correct the problem  
after the fact, including repaying all the monies which were known 
to be misappropriated'' DiFazio said. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones' attorney and current agent, Leon Rose, refused to comment  
because the case is in litigation. He said Rose was in Florida 
running a basketball camp. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit claims that two checks totaling $302,802 were drawn  
on Jones' checking account and deposited between March and May 
1998, into the account of another player, Aaron McKie. A third 
check for $89,500 was deposited into player Marc Jackson's account. 
The suit doesn't explain how the money was taken from those 
accounts. 
</P>
<P>
	The suit also claimed that beginning in 1996, certain agents and  
officers of Atlantic Sports, including bookkeeper Debi Donnelly, 
began working together to systematically steal from Jones' 
accounts. It doesn't specify how much else was stolen. 
</P>
<P>
	The alleged fraud came to light in October 1998, when Jones  
requested an audit. He ended all contractual relationships with 
DiFazio Jan. 20. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
