<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 21:10:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Religion in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- A new book of Mormon humor? The very idea  
draws horselaughs from some members of the faith known for its 
seriousness and sobriety. Yet it's true -- and the publisher is The 
Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints. 
</P>
<P>
	``We tried hard not to offend anybody,'' said Jack Lyon,  
managing editor of church-owned Deseret Book, which released 
``Best-Loved Humor of the LDS People'' this spring. ``We did select 
things people could use if giving a talk in church.'' 
</P>
<P>
	An example:  
</P>
<P>
	``Question: How are bishops chosen?  
</P>
<P>
	``Answer: The stake leaders find the most righteous, spiritual,  
most loved person in the ward -- and then they call her husband.'' 
</P>
<P>
	OK, this is not comedy club stuff. But it's heading in the right  
direction, say those who want to show there's fun beneath the 
faith's buttoned-down image. 
</P>
<P>
	Robert Kirby, considered by many the preeminent Mormon humorist  
today, thought for years that most of his fellow believers were a 
pretty pinched lot. 
</P>
<P>
	``I equated Mormons with the way they behaved in church,'' said  
Kirby, a humor columnist for The Salt Lake Tribune. 
</P>
<P>
	This was, after all, the church whose canonical Doctrine and  
Covenants states: ``Therefore, cease from all your light speeches, 
from all laughter, from all your lustful desires, from all your 
pride and light-mindedness, and from all your wicked doings.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kirby continued: ``I operated on the premise that church was a  
place where humorless people go. I misinterpreted reverence for 
humorlessness.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That changed with Kirby's first foray into Mormon humor, a  
satirical column about five types of Mormons, which he wrote for a 
newspaper where he used to work. Though his Mormon publisher hated 
it, the column brought a flood of letters from church members who 
loved it. 
</P>
<P>
	Kirby felt like a miner cracking his shins on the mother lode.  
</P>
<P>
	``I was surprised that Mormons, particularly -- I know Jewish  
people do it and Catholics to a large extent -- used humor to make 
their lot in life a little more tolerable,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``And the depth of it was even more surprising, because you get  
people who are very staunch members of the church who laugh about 
the inconsistencies or the vagaries in our behavior and the 
mysteries of the gospel.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In other words, they are able to laugh at themselves.  
</P>
<P>
	Psst! begins a joke that has made the rounds, though it isn't in  
the new book: How do you tell the difference between a Mormon 
wedding and a non-Mormon wedding? At the Mormon wedding, the 
bride's mother is pregnant. 
</P>
<P>
	The punch line plays on the traditional Mormon propensity for  
large families. 
</P>
<P>
	``The really funny Mormon stuff is uniquely Mormon. It's  
something that comes from being part of the family,'' said Pat 
Bagley, political cartoonist at the Tribune. 
</P>
<P>
	Mormons use humor as a decompression device, ``a way to let off  
some of the pressure that builds up'' and to say things that are 
true but which, unadorned with humor, might seem heretical or mean. 
For example, he says, ``It's not politic to say 19-year-old 
missionaries are dumb,'' but it's safe to say the same thing in a 
joke or cartoon. 
</P>
<P>
	Elouise Bell, a retired Brigham Young University English  
professor and author of a collection of humorous essays titled 
``Only When I Laugh,'' observed: ``The essence of really good humor 
is a kind of surprise. Well, I think culturally Mormons don't like 
surprises in outward things. I mean, look at the architecture. And 
there are very few startling pronouncements made from pulpits week 
to week, year to year, decade to decade.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Irreverent humor can be both unsettling and subversive, and its  
purveyors scorned as impious or worse. 
</P>
<P>
	``A humorist is a person who thinks otherwise,'' Bell said.  
``Well, thinking otherwise can get you into trouble in any 
establishment -- in the military, in most churches, in most 
educational institutions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The pitfalls associated with thinking otherwise were very much  
on the minds of three editors who compiled the material for 
``Best-Loved Humor of the LDS People.'' (Kirby likes to call it, 
``The Correlation Committee-Approved Humor of the LDS People.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Oddly, among the dozens of examples of humor from church leaders  
there is nothing in the book from church President Gordon B. 
Hinckley, known for his sense of humor. 
</P>
<P>
	Said editor Jay Parry, ``He is delightful and he is very funny.  
But it's the kind of thing that you had to have been there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kirby credits Hinckley with sensing that Mormonism, in the midst  
of a global expansion, needs to lighten up. 
</P>
<P>
	``How do you assimilate all different types of people into one  
religion?'' It's best done through tolerance and making a human 
connection, he said, ``and humor for me is the best way to do 
that.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990708.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 09:40:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Compromise Close on Olympic Bands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- The chief executive for the Sydney  
Olympics has ruled out United States and Japanese school band 
members from the opening ceremony of next year's Summer Games but 
says a compromise deal is close to being finalized. 
</P>
<P>
	Sandy Hollway met with United States, Japanese and Australian  
band leaders for nearly four hours at SOCOG's headquarters 
Thursday. While a compromise was close, he said, ``There is no hope 
that they will play in the Olympic opening ceremony.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The band leaders will meet with SOCOG again Friday to complete a  
deal which is likely to see the children perform at other Olympic 
venues and at Sydney landmarks such as the Opera House. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. band leader Roy Anthony, who before the meeting described a  
deal as unlikely and warned of possible legal action, reversed his 
stance by the end of the proceedings, saying he felt ``very 
comfortable'' with the talks. 
</P>
<P>
	The only detail confirmed was that the bands will be retained to  
play at various Olympic venues and in Sydney during the games. 
</P>
<P>
	Sydney's Olympic ticket drive has been drowned out by the  
marching band controversy. 
</P>
<P>
	About 1,300 Americans and 200 Japanese marching band members  
were booked to play at the opening ceremony only to be rejected 
after a public outcry in Australia. 
</P>
<P>
	A statement released by the band leaders, including those in  
Atlanta, ahead of Thursday's meeting with Hollway, described SOCOG 
president Michael Knight as ``harsh and insensitive'' over the 
decision. 
</P>
<P>
	``Each of us has an invitation on SOCOG letterhead, signed by  
(ceremonies director) Ric Birch, indicating that we were to be a 
representative part of the 2000 piece marching band from around the 
Pacific Rim,'' the statement said. ``We also have a video 
presentation of Mr. Birch offering the same invitation to each of 
our students. We indicated to Mr. Knight that we feel that SOCOG is 
indeed involved in this concern.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The leaders also accused SOCOG of ``cultural hypocrisy'' for  
inviting Italian opera star Luciano Pavarotti to open the Olympic 
basketball and gymnastics venues while dropping the bands because 
they are not Australians. 
</P>
<P>
	Anthony said the children were invited last September to perform  
at the Sept. 16, 2000, opening ceremony and had been preparing ever 
since. He said the students had taken alternative courses in their 
studies to be ready for the Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	``The students have been turned out for doing nothing wrong,''  
Anthony said. ``We were invited by SOCOG. We didn't solicit this. 
They asked us to come and be part of it. 
</P>
<P>
	``The kids are going to have a hard time accepting that we've  
abided by all (SOCOG'S) demands and all their wishes and yet 
they're saying no.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Knight said of the compromise deal, ``It's a step down from the  
opening ceremony and no-one pretends otherwise.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``If we have to go to court we would strenuously defend our  
position but I don't believe that's likely,'' Knight said. ``I 
think we will reach the compromise, I think that the overwhelming 
majority of kids would like to embrace the compromise.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990708.0088 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 09:10:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Mixed; Dow Down 78.51 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mixed today amid rising interest  
rates and a mixed batch of second-quarter earnings reports. 
</P>
<P>
	At 11 a.m. on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was  
down 0.95 at 11,186.41, having pared a loss of 95 points in the 
first hour of trading. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators recovered from early declines. The  
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was up 2.45 at 1,398.31, and the Nasdaq 
composite index was up 24.85 at 2,767.89. 
</P>
<P>
	Bond prices tumbled today, with the 30-year Treasury bond  
dropping 1/2 point in price and its yield rising to 6.08 percent from 
6.04 percent late Wednesday. The rising yield served as a reminder 
to investors that higher interest rates are taking hold in the 
buoyant economy, and could threaten earnings in future quarters. 
</P>
<P>
	Banks and brokerages, seen as most vulnerable to interest rate  
increases, were among the big losers today. J.P. Morgan, a 
component of the Dow, fell 1 3/4 to 144 1/4. 
</P>
<P>
	Stocks had risen to record levels in recent sessions, due  
largely to a strong outlook for second-quarter profits. But mixed 
earnings today put stocks on divergent paths. 
</P>
<P>
	General Electric beat analysts' estimates by a penny. Its stock,  
which rose sharply Wednesday in advance of the report, slipped 9/16 
to 117 3/8 as investors locked in their profits from Wednesday's gain. 
</P>
<P>
	Nasdaq drew some of its strength from Yahoo!, which rose 4 1/4 to  
171 5/16 after reporting earnings that topped expectations. 
</P>
<P>
	But other companies continued to warn of weakness. Airborne  
Freight said late Wednesday it will miss analysts' expectations by 
as much as 18 cents per share. Its shares fell 1 11/16 to 25 1/2, and 
other package delivery company stocks fell along with it. 
</P>
<P>
	Philip Morris rose 1 1/8 to 39. Its shares had dropped in late  
trading Wednesday afternoon after a Florida jury ruled that tobacco 
makers are liable for making a defective product that causes 
emphysema, lung cancer and other illnesses. The verdict, if it 
stands, is expected to cost the tobacco industry billions in 
damages. 
</P>
<P>
	Today, however, analysts said the verdict was no real surprise.  
Investors bought back the stock on the belief that legal wrangling 
may delay payments to plaintiffs for many years. 
</P>
<P>
	Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 3-to-2 margin on the  
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 254.7 million shares, 
ahead of Wednesday's pace. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index was down 0.23 at 656.24, and the  
American Stock Exchange composite index was down 3.82 at 798.32. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
