<HEADLINE> Girl, 13, Convicted of Plot To Kill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) -- A 13-year-old girl faces up to  
eight years in a juvenile detention center after being convicted of 
plotting to kill teachers and students, then blow up her school. 
</P>
<P>
	The plot was discovered in April, just days after the massacre  
at Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo. 
</P>
<P>
	The eighth-grader, whose name was not released because of her  
age, had made a hit list and drawn a map of Bair Middle School in 
Sunrise, with the location of security cameras and stick figures 
representing the victims. 
</P>
<P>
	``The sabotage at the end of the year will be known as the South  
Florida massacre,'' she wrote in a letter outlining her plans. 
</P>
<P>
	The girl was found guilty Wednesday of soliciting at least seven  
people to help her carry out the killings. Sentencing was set for 
July 22. 
</P>
<P>
	Defense attorney Kenneth Hassett said the incident was an  
immature child's attempt to get attention. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
