<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 18:00:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Regulators Take Over Mexican Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Mexican financial regulators on Thursday took  
control of Grupo Financiero Serfin SA, the country's third largest 
financial services company and the largest yet to fall victim to 
the fallout of Mexico's 1994 peso collapse. 
</P>
<P>
	The government Bank Savings Protection Institute said it would  
auction the company. 
</P>
<P>
	It is the latest step by the Mexican government to keep the  
fragile banking system afloat despite unpaid loans and volatile 
markets in the wake of the December 1994 peso devaluation. 
</P>
<P>
	The takeover of Serfin was widely expected since last month. The  
bank had reported some $1.4 billion losses and financial regulators 
had ordered shareholders to inject fresh capital to cover about 
$1.4 billion in reserves, deferred taxes and obligations. 
</P>
<P>
	At a meeting earlier Thursday, shareholders declined to do so  
and agreed to accept a takeover. 
</P>
<P>
	The government's Bank Savings Protection Institute, known as  
IPAB, will oversee the bank. 
</P>
<P>
	Serfin has 560 branches throughout Mexico, more than 12,000  
employees, 2.5 million clients and 13 percent of Mexico's banking 
market. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the units of the financial group will be sold together,  
including its brokerage and insurance units, to increase the value 
of the sale, said IPAB executive secretary Vicente Corta. 
</P>
<P>
	However, pension fund manager Afore Garante, in which Serfin has  
a 51 percent stake, may be sold in a separate process. Afore 
Garante is also backed by Chilean pension fund manager Habitat, 
with a 9 percent stake, and Citigroup's local banking unit Citibank 
Mexico, with the remaining 40 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Current Serfin management will continue to run the institution  
and will pursue plans to reduce staff to 10,000 by the end of this 
year, increase deposits and intensify collection of bad loans, 
Corta said. 
</P>
<P>
	Corta told a news conference that London-based HSBC Holdings PLC  
will retain its 19.9 percent stake in the group, at least until 
Serfin is auctioned between six and eight months from now. 
</P>
<P>
	He said HSBC was interested in participating in the auction, but  
declined to mention which other banks may take part. 
</P>
<P>
	Government officials have taken over about a dozen banks since  
the sudden peso devaluation sent interest rates soaring, leading to 
widespread defaults amid Mexico's worst economic setback since the 
Great Depression. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990708.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 07:50:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Drug Antitrust Suit Stays in Place </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The federal government will proceed with a  
$120 million lawsuit accusing a generic drug maker of causing 
prices of two widely prescribed tranquilizers to skyrocket. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge Thomas F. Hogan, in refusing Wednesday to  
dismiss the antitrust case, said the Federal Trade Commission may 
ask the court to permanently block the practices of Mylan 
Laboratories Inc. and award monetary damages. 
</P>
<P>
	Mylan lawyers had argued that the remedies sought exceeded those  
permitted by law because the FTC's authorizing statute did not 
specifically allow them. Mylan also argued that the commission's 
authority to bring antitrust cases to court is limited. 
</P>
<P>
	While keeping alive the federal complaint, Hogan narrowed a  
companion claim filed by 31 states and the District of Columbia. 
</P>
<P>
	The FTC seeks at least $120 million for refunds to consumers of  
the two anti-anxiety drugs, lorazepam and clorazepate. The states 
did not set a price tag. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're gratified by the decision,'' FTC spokeswoman Victoria  
Streitfeld said. ``It's good news for consumers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The government accuses Mylan of cutting off competition by  
reaching an exclusive deal with a key supplier, Profarmaco S.R.L. 
of Milan, Italy. Other suppliers cannot make adequate quantities 
for Mylan's competitors, essentially shutting them out, the 
government argues. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the lawsuits, the exclusive deal caused prices of  
lorazepam and clorazepate to rise by more than 25 times virtually 
overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	Mylan says the exclusive deal was designed to guarantee an  
uninterrupted source of ingredients. The company notes that prices 
for generic drugs still are much less than the amount brand-name 
manufacturers charge. 
</P>
<P>
	Dana G. Barnett, executive vice president for Mylan, said the  
Pittsburgh-based drug maker remained confident that it would 
prevail in a trial, which is not expected for at least a year. 
</P>
<P>
	``There remains no basis in fact for the FTC's charges against  
Mylan,'' he said. ``Mylan never had a monopoly in lorazepam or 
clorazepate, as the FTC charges.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hogan dismissed portions of the states' complaints that seek to  
recover damages from Mylan for purchases from its competitors. The 
states had argued that the competitors also were able to raise 
prices because of Mylan's actions. 
</P>
<P>
	The judge also ruled that states cannot sue on behalf of  
indirect purchasers, such as wholesalers that buy the drugs from 
Mylan, unless state law specifically permits it. Those claims by 
several states were dismissed. 
</P>
<P>
	Doctors each year issue more than 18 million prescriptions for  
lorazepam, a generic version of Ativan, for treating anxiety, 
tension, agitation and insomnia. More than 3 million prescriptions 
for clorazepate are issued a year. Clorazepate, the generic version 
of Tranxene, is used to treat anxiety and hypertension. 
</P>
<P>
	The states that filed the complaint are Alaska, Arkansas,  
California, Colorado, Connecticut, Florida, Idaho, Illinois, Iowa, 
Kentucky, Louisiana, Maine, Michigan, Minnesota, Missouri, New 
Mexico, New York, North Carolina, Ohio, Oklahoma, Oregon, 
Pennsylvania, South Carolina, South Dakota, Texas, Tennessee, Utah, 
Vermont, Washington, West Virginia and Wisconsin. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
