<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Key Index in Japan Closes Higher / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The approval of a supplementary budget by Japan's  
Cabinet boosted the key index on the Tokyo stock exchange today. 
The dollar edged higher against the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained 8.75 points,  
or 0.05 percent, to 17,967.65 at the close of trading. On 
Wednesday, the average closed down 91.83 points, or 0.51 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 122.38 yen in late afternoon trading, up 0.42  
yen from late Wednesday in Tokyo and slightly above its late New 
York level of 122.23 yen overnight. The U.S. currency ranged 
between 122.22 yen and 122.44 yen in today's trading. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, share prices rose after the Cabinet  
approved a supplementary budget worth $4.25 billion aimed at 
stimulating the ailing labor market, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	They added, however, that investors were awaiting a second  
additional budget to pay for public works -- something Finance 
Minister Kiichi Miyazawa said he won't consider until economic 
growth data for the April-June quarter is released later this year. 
</P>
<P>
	The funds set aside in the proposed budget would go to finance  
the government's program to create about 720,000 jobs through 
measures such as subsidies to companies and nonprofit organizations 
hiring displaced workers, the Finance Ministry said. 
</P>
<P>
	The budget was still awaiting approval by Japan's Parliament.  
</P>
<P>
	Traders also noted that investors continued to cash in on the  
stock market's recent gains. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, the Nikkei added 202.59 points, or 1.13 percent,  
finishing at 18,135.06 -- its highest closing level since Sept. 25, 
1997. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section fell 7.93 points, or 0.54 percent, to 1,469.09. The 
TOPIX closed down 1.70 points, or 0.11 percent, the day before. 
</P>
<P>
	An estimated 597.15 million shares changed hands on the first  
section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange, down from 644.96 million 
shares Wednesday. Declines outnumbered advances 698 to 488, while 
140 issues were unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency trading, the dollar edged higher against the yen,  
benefiting from weakness in the euro, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro was quoted at $1.0200 in late afternoon trading, down  
from $1.0243 late Wednesday in Tokyo. But it was up slightly from a 
low earlier in the day of dlrs 1.0186. 
</P>
<P>
	Against the Japanese currency, the euro was quoted in late  
afternoon trading at 124.94 yen, down from 125.06 yen late 
Wednesday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	While the dollar gained against the yen in the wake of the  
euro's decline, comments by U.S. Treasury Secretary Lawrence 
Summers limited the greenback's rise, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	In an interview Wednesday in the United States, Summers warned  
Japan's central bank against intervening to prop up the U.S. 
currency -- something it has done several times in recent weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan's ``manipulation'' of its currency would not help restore  
prosperity, Summers said, adding that ``the focus in Japan has to 
be on strengthening the fundamentals.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Japanese government has said it wants to limit the yen's  
rise, as a stronger Japanese currency makes the nation's exports 
more expensive abroad and reduces the yen value of companies' 
foreign profits. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond fell in late  
afternoon trading to 1.6250 percent from Wednesday's finish of 
1.6350 percent, driving its price up to 101.52 yen from 101.43 yen 
the previous day. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
