<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 2 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Anti-Milosevic Protests Continue  
</P>
<P>
	PROKUPLJE, Yugoslavia (AP ) -- Opposition protesters kept up  
demands for President Slobodan Milosevic to resign, brawling	
briefly with a handful of his supporters and ignoring gunshots	
fired in the air to disrupt the demonstration. About 4,000 people	
demonstrated Thursday in the southern Serbian town of Prokuplje,	
the latest in a series of almost daily protests aimed at bringing	
down Milosevic. No one was seriously injured, but tensions soared	
as protesters and a handful of government supporters shoved each	
other and traded punches, while protest leaders and a few police	
appealed for calm.	

</P>
<P>
	Research: Tea Reduces Heart Attack  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- An apple a day may keep the doctor away, but  
researchers now say a daily cup of tea could do the job just as 
well, reducing the chance of a heart attack by 44 percent. The 
study by Dr. Michael Gaziano, a heart specialist at the Harvard 
Medical School-affiliated Brigham and Women's Hospital in Boston, 
suggests that may be because tea contains powerful amounts of 
flavonoids, natural substances that make blood cells less prone to 
clots, which can cause heart attacks. Flavonoids also are one of 
the most powerful antioxidants, which offset the damaging effects 
of oxygen in the body, such as fatty deposits in the arteries. 

</P>
<P>
	Many Colombians Dead After Fighting  
</P>
<P>
	BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- Leftist guerillas attacked a mobile army  
encampment in mountains just south of Colombia's capital Thursday, 
touching off fierce clashes that killed dozens of soldiers and 
rebels. The army claimed it had beaten back a guerrilla drive on 
Bogota, a modern city whose roughly 6 million inhabitants live 
relatively untouched by a 35-year civil conflict felt more directly 
in the poor countryside. There were conflicting estimates of each 
side's casualties in the combat, which began at dawn near 
Gutierrez, a small Andean town 27 miles south of Bogota. 

</P>
<P>
	Las Vegas Streets Flooded by Heavy Rains  
</P>
<P>
	LAS VEGAS (AP) -- Heavy rains poured on Las Vegas today, creating  
floods that smashed mobile homes, swallowed hundreds of cars and 
led to at least two deaths. ``It's a nightmare,'' said Nevada 
Highway Patrol spokesman Scott Flabi. ``It's one of the worst 
things I've ever seen.'' Sections of busy Interstate 15 resembled a 
lake, bringing traffic to a standstill. Most major intersections 
were under water. Block walls along a flood channel collapsed. 
Firefighters rescued motorists whose cars were sucked into the 
water. 

</P>
<P>
	Amtrak Train Hits Truck, Derails  
</P>
<P>
	EAGLE LAKE, Texas (AP) -- An Amtrak train carrying 235 passengers  
struck a truck today, derailing nine cars and injuring 18 people. 
The eastbound Sunset Limited was traveling from Los Angeles to 
Orlando, Fla., when it hit the rig shortly before noon, an Amtrak 
spokesman said. Track was torn up and two engines and seven cars 
were off to the side. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Tours U.S. Poverty Areas  
</P>
<P>
	ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) -- Ending a four-day tour of poverty pockets  
from Appalachia to Watts, President Clinton today called for 
investment in the ``human capital'' in impoverished areas. Clinton 
attended the National Academy Foundation conference, an 
organization that helps prepare disadvantaged high-school youths 
for careers. Citigroup, Lucent Technologies and other companies 
announced an $8 million initiative today to create ``Information 
Technology Academies'' to begin training boys and girls for careers 
in high-technology. 

</P>
<P>
	UN's Kofi Annan Visits Sierra Leone  
</P>
<P>
	FREETOWN, Sierra Leone (AP) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan  
visited Sierra Leone today to drum up international assistance for 
a new peace accord that has come under attack for including amnesty 
for war criminals. The accord, signed by Sierra Leone President 
Ahmed Tejan Kabbah and rebel Revolutionary United Front leader 
Foday Sankoh in Togo's capital of Lome late yesterday, formally 
ends eight years of civil war that has killed tens of thousands and 
maimed many more. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stocks Fall in Midday Trading  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks fell Friday morning as investors  
locked in profits amid a lack of new evidence of recovery in 
Japan's economy. The Nikkei dropped 97.64 to 17,840.01. 

</P>
<P>
	Indians 9, Twins 2  
</P>
<P>
	MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Charles Nagy won for the eighth time in nine  
decisions and David Justice had three hits and three RBIs as the 
Cleveland Indians beat the Minnesota Twins 9-2 Thursday night. Nagy 
beat the Twins for the third time in as many starts this year. He 
pitched seven innings, giving up nine hits and two runs with four 
strikeouts and one walk. Over his past 11 starts, Nagy is 8-1 with 
a 3.44 ERA. He has lowered his ERA over that period from 6.17 to 
4.43. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by VINCENT K. WILLIS  
  	   	
</P>
