<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cipollini Again Sprints To Tour Win </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AMIENS, France (AP) -- Mario Cipollini surged to victory in  
today's fifth stage of the Tour de France for his second 
consecutive stage triumph in cycling's showcase race. 
</P>
<P>
	The Italian, known as ``Lion King'' and the ``King of Sprints,''  
is living up to his nicknames at this year's Tour after a slow 
start. 
</P>
<P>
	Tom Steels of Belgium finished second, followed by Estonian Jaan  
Kirsipuu, who retained the yellow leader's jersey for the fourth 
day. Robbie McEwen of Australia was fourth, and German Erik Zabel 
fifth. 
</P>
<P>
	The fifth stage was one of the longest of the Tour, a 145-mile  
ride through rolling wheat fields and past grand cathedrals like 
the Gothic masterpiece at Chartres, with its famed stained-glass 
windows. 
</P>
<P>
	Unlike Wednesday, when a favorable tailwind led to a record  
speed for the stage, the riders faced a headwind today and the 
average speed was nearly 6 miles slower. 
</P>
<P>
	In the overall standings, Steels moved up to second and Stuart  
O'Grady was third. Lance Armstrong, on the comeback from testicular 
cancer, was fourth, and Cipollini fifth. 
</P>
<P>
	The race was marked by an early breakaway, this time at the  
2-mile mark. A group of 10 riders made the break, instigated by 
Frenchman Jacky Durand and his Belgian teammate on Lotto-Mobistar, 
Thierry Marechal. 
</P>
<P>
	The group had as much as a 6-minute, 15-second lead, but that  
soon was whittled down by the advancing pack. 
</P>
<P>
	Sweden's Magnus Backstedt held a brief lead near the end, but  
was soon overtaken, and the race was set for another furious, 
wide-open sprint. Cipollini's Saeco teammates again moved him into 
position, and the Italian sprinted to victory. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, Cipollini chose the former home of French kings to  
win the fastest stage in tour history. 
</P>
<P>
	In the town of Blois, in view of the imposing royal castle, he  
came off a stone bridge spanning the Loire River to surge past 
Zabel and win the fourth stage in a photo finish. 
</P>
<P>
	A tailwind, cool weather conditions, a relatively straight  
course and wide, flat roads all set the scene for an average speed 
of 31.290 mph, shattering the previous record of 30.707 mph, set in 
1993. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990708.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 08:20:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Montoya Nearing Rookie Records </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ELKHART LAKE, Wis. (AP) -- The CART FedEx Championship Series  
season reaches the halfway point with Sunday's Texaco/Havoline 200 
and Juan Montoya already is closing in on some impressive records. 
</P>
<P>
	Montoya, a 23-year-old Colombian, replaced Alex Zanardi after  
the two-time PPG Cup champion returned to Formula One this season. 
Since taking over the seat at Target/Chip Ganassi Racing, ``The 
Great Juan'' has been sensational. 
</P>
<P>
	He has four poles and four wins in his first nine CART events.  
That is one victory short of the rookie record of five, set by 
Nigel Mansell in 1993. Mansell also set the record of seven poles 
by a first-year driver. 
</P>
<P>
	Montoya has led in eight races this season, for a total of 564  
laps at the front of the pack. That puts him within easy reach of 
Zanardi's rookie record, set in 1996, of 610 laps led. 
</P>
<P>
	``Records are nice, but I am just trying to be consistent,''  
Montoya said. ``If we keep doing things the way we have been, then 
the records will come. But the championship is most important.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Montoya has the lead in that race, too.  
</P>
<P>
	The kid, who was last year's European Formula 3000 champion,  
holds a 112 to 87 points lead over Gil de Ferran in the series 
standings. Dario Franchitti is third with 85, followed by 
three-time Road America winner Michael Andretti with 78. 
</P>
<P>
	``The championship is still wide open,'' Andretti said. ``There  
are 11 more races to go, but this is the time to start gathering 
some points and keep Montoya from building up too big a lead.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The race on the four-mile road course is the first in a stretch  
of six events in seven weeks, the busiest part of the 20-race CART 
schedule. 
</P>
<P>
	This is another new track for Montoya, but that hasn't stopped  
him from shining on any of the other road or street circuits he has 
seen for the first time this season. 
</P>
<P>
	Montoya won from the pole on the temporary street circit in Long  
Beach, Calif.; he finished second from the pole on the natural 
terrain road course in Portland, Ore.; and he won from the pole two 
weeks ago on the temporary road course at Cleveland's Burke 
Lakefront Airport. 
</P>
<P>
	Overall, he earned 59 of a possible 66 points in those three  
events. 
</P>
<P>
	``Road racing is what I grew up with,'' Montoya said. ``I like  
the ovals. They are new and fun, but the road circuits are more 
familiar and a little easier for me to learn.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He is looking forward to racing at Road America, the longest and  
fastest of CART's road circuits. 
</P>
<P>
	``We tested here and I loved it,'' Montoya said.  
</P>
<P>
	Franchitti, who earned his first CART victory last year at Road  
America, feels much the same way about the track. His win ignited a 
run that carried Franchitti to two more victories and moved him 
from eighth to third in the standings. 
</P>
<P>
	``I love Elkhart,'' Franchitti said. ``It's a fun track to drive  
on. It's long, it's fast and it's interesting. Even if you don't 
win, it's a great place to race.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Practice and provisional qualifying are scheduled Friday.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
