<DOCNO> APW19990708.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 15:30:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> First Lady May Seek Husband's Help </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COOPERSTOWN, N.Y. (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton said Thursday  
that she would ask her husband, President Clinton, to do some 
campaigning for her if she moves forward with a New York Senate 
race. 
</P>
<P>
	``He knows a lot about New York,'' she said. ``He's done very  
well in New York and I would look forward to his campaigning for me 
if I decide to run ... (and) if I can get on his schedule.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meeting with reporters on the second day of her inaugural  
campaign tour of New York, Mrs. Clinton said she would serve a full 
six-year term if she wins the Democratic nomination and is elected 
senator. 
</P>
<P>
	New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, eyeing the Republican Senate  
nomination, has refused to say whether he would serve the entire 
six years. 
</P>
<P>
	Critics of both have questioned whether Mrs. Clinton and  
Giuliani want to use the Senate as a stepping stone for a White 
House bid in 2004. 
</P>
<P>
	At a health care discussion with employees the Bassett  
Healthcare Center, Mrs. Clinton said her experience as architect of 
the Clinton administration's failed health care reform effort 
convinced her that progress toward universal health care must be 
made incrementally. 
</P>
<P>
	``Certainly, coming out of that experience I remain committed to  
the idea of providing quality, affordable health care for every 
American, but I now come from the school of smaller steps,'' she 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Later, she stopped for lunch, fittingly, in the village of  
Clinton, where she was greeted by a crowd of more than 500. Among 
them was Gilda Mazzura, who held a hand-lettered sign that read: 
``I'm 92 and I'll vote 4-U.'' Mrs. Clinton hugged the elderly 
woman. 
</P>
<P>
	She paused to sign 13-year-old Zach Kussin's leg cast. He fell  
off his bike and broke his leg last month. 
</P>
<P>
	While most of the crowd was welcoming, one person held a sign  
that read, ``Go back to Arkansas.'' Mrs. Clinton has never lived or 
worked in New York, prompting charges from some Republicans, 
including Giuliani, that she is a carpetbagger. 
</P>
<P>
	In Utica, Mrs. Clinton talked with senior citizens and others.  
After a member of the audience remarked that she would still be 
repaying the cost of her college education when she became a senior 
citizen, Mrs. Clinton said, ``I have long favored making college 
tuition tax deductible.'' 
</P>
<P>
	New York's junior senator, Democrat Charles Schumer, had made  
the tuition tax deduction proposal a centerpiece of his successful 
campaign last year to unseat the Republican incumbent, Alfonse 
D'Amato. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton formed a committee earlier this week aimed at  
exploring a possible Senate race. 
</P>
<P>
	She told reporters that forming the exploratory committee ``is  
not the final step'' and that she wanted to make sure that New 
Yorkers ``are receptive and willing to support me and my ideas.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And while Mrs. Clinton said she was enjoying the campaigning,  
she conceded ``it is a different feeling to be the person who is in 
the spotlight voluntarily and speaking on my own behalf.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On other issues, she said she is in favor of the death penalty  
as ``appropriate for society,'' but added that she was not ``an 
enthusiastic death penalty supporter.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton refused to answer a question about whether she  
thought Giuliani had been a good mayor. ``That is something for the 
people of New York to decide,'' she said. She also refused to say 
how she differed from Giuliani politically, claiming ``there will 
be plenty of time in a campaign to go into that.'' In fact, the two 
agree on such things as support for abortion and gay rights and gun 
control. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990708.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 12:40:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Theo Fleury Signs With Rangers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Six-time All-Star Theo Fleury, expected to help  
fill a void created by Wayne Gretzky's retirement, signed Thursday 
with the New York Rangers as an unrestricted free agent. 
</P>
<P>
	The 31-year-old right wing, who played all or part of 11 NHL  
seasons for the Calgary Flames before being traded to the Colorado 
Avalanche in March, said he had some contact with Gretzky. 
</P>
<P>
	``He pointed out the good things about New York and talked about  
his experiences of playing in New York,'' Fleury said during a 
conference call. 
</P>
<P>
	The Rangers announced it was a multiyear contract, but declined  
to disclose any details. Reportedly, the deal was for at least four 
years at $8 million to $10 million per year with an option for a 
fifth year. 
</P>
<P>
	Fleury, however, said, ``At the end of three years. it will give  
me a good idea if I can keep playing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He also said there was a no-trade clause in the contract  
``because I'm a guy who likes to know where I'm going to be from 
year to year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Avalanche did not want to give Fleury a no-trade deal.  
</P>
<P>
	``I have no bitter feelings against Colorado,'' he said. ``I was  
excited to be in the playoffs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He had five goals and 12 assists in 18 playoff games for the  
Avalanche, who were beaten in seven games by Dallas in the Western 
Conference finals. His numbers for the season were 40 goals and 53 
assists in 75 games. He has 374 goals and 480 assists in his 
regular-season career. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm excited to be a Ranger,'' Fleury said, adding he was  
surprised and impressed by a trip to Winnipeg to talk to him by 
Neil Smith, president and general manager of the Rangers, and Dave 
Checketts, president and CEO of Madison Square Garden. 
</P>
<P>
	``So far they've gone out and improved the team tremendously  
since last year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Rangers, who failed to make the playoffs last season,  
earlier signed free agents Valeri Kamensky, a left wing for the 
Avalanche, and Stephane Quintal, a defenseman, who played for the 
Montreal Canadiens. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990708.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 10:13:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Eddie Jones Sues Ex-Agent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Charlotte Hornets guard Eddie Jones has sued  
his former agent, saying that a former employee of the agent stole 
more than $1 million from Jones and has not repaid all the money. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit, filed in April in U.S. District Court in Camden,  
N.J., claims that a former bookkeeper and assistant of agent Sal 
DiFazio stole the money from Jones by depositing it in the accounts 
of two other professional basketball clients of the company. The 
suit doesn't explain how the money was later taken from those 
accounts. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit said Atlantic Sports Management Inc. and DiFazio  
have repaid about $960,000 to Jones, a former Temple University 
player. Jones, who also seeks more than $500,000 in compensatory 
damages and interest, contends he is still owed more than $540,000. 
</P>
<P>
	DiFazio disputes the dollar figure, saying an auditor for  
Atlantic Sports has told him the amount is ``substantially less.'' 
He has until July 19 to file a response with the federal court. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have taken every possible measure to correct the problem  
after the fact, including repaying all the monies which were known 
to be misappropriated'' DiFazio said. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones' attorney and current agent, Leon Rose, refused to comment  
because the case is in litigation. He said Rose was in Florida 
running a basketball camp. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit claims that two checks totaling $302,802 were drawn  
on Jones' checking account and deposited between March and May 
1998, into the account of another player, Aaron McKie. A third 
check for $89,500 was deposited into player Marc Jackson's account. 
The suit doesn't explain how the money was taken from those 
accounts. 
</P>
<P>
	The suit also claimed that beginning in 1996, certain agents and  
officers of Atlantic Sports, including bookkeeper Debi Donnelly, 
began working together to systematically steal from Jones' 
accounts. It doesn't specify how much else was stolen. 
</P>
<P>
	The alleged fraud came to light in October 1998, when Jones  
requested an audit. He ended all contractual relationships with 
DiFazio Jan. 20. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990708.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 12:40:18 </DATE_TIME>
