<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NBC, GE Equity Up ValueVision Stake </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EDEN PRAIRIE, Minn. (AP) -- NBC and GE Equity have doubled their  
stake in ValueVision International Inc. to nearly 40 percent by 
exercising warrants to purchase about $175 million worth of stock 
in the direct marketer. 
</P>
<P>
	The two companies, both divisions of General Electric Co.,  
already owned a 19.9 percent stake in ValueVision. 
</P>
<P>
	The purchase, announced Wednesday, ``is a huge credibility boost  
for ValueVision,'' said Bob Evans, an analyst with Craig-Hallum 
Capital Group in Minneapolis. 
</P>
<P>
	ValueVision announced earlier this week that it had boosted its  
television reach by 50 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Founded in 1991, ValueVision for years floundered as the  
nation's third-largest home shopping network, behind QVC and the 
Home Shopping Network. 
</P>
<P>
	But in the past year, under new chairman and CEO Gene McCaffery,  
ValueVision has expanded from late-night television sales into 
other avenues of retailing, particularly electronic commerce. 
</P>
<P>
	Executives from ValueVision, NBC and GE Equity, as well as  
analysts, say the world of broadcast and cable television and the 
Internet are quickly converging to create a powerful retail selling 
medium. 
</P>
<P>
	``In a world of increasing convergence, the importance of  
electronic shopping opportunities via the television should grow 
dramatically,'' said Tom Rogers, president of NBC Cable and an NBC 
executive vice president. 
</P>
<P>
	Shoppers can view merchandise on television and then order  
online. Or viewers can buy merchandise tied to NBC programming on 
VVTV, or via the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	McCaffery believes ValueVision now will be in an ideal position  
to sell to both Internet shoppers and TV home shoppers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
