<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> N.J. Man Charged in Terrorism Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Prosecutors have charged a New Jersey man with  
lying to a federal grand jury investigating the World Trade Center 
bombing and other terrorist activity. 
</P>
<P>
	Mustafa Elnore, 39, was arrested at his Jersey City, N.J., home  
and charged with 10 counts accusing him of giving false testimony 
about his attendance at firearms training and participation in 
bomb-making activities. 
</P>
<P>
	The indictment unsealed Wednesday said Elnore lied to a grand  
jury investigating terrorism in the United States, including the 
Feb. 26, 1993, World Trade Center bombing that killed six people 
and injured more than 1,000 others. 
</P>
<P>
	Elnore was questioned in late 1997 and early 1998 as the grand  
jury turned its attention to terrorist groups linked to the 
bombing. 
</P>
<P>
	Elnore has denied any wrongdoing, said his lawyer, Mahmoud  
Ramadan. 
</P>
<P>
	If convicted, Elnore faces a maximum sentence of five years in  
prison on each count. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors also are investigating whether Elnore was involved  
in a conspiracy to murder Rabbi Meir Kahane nine years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Elnore denied knowing anything about a plot to kill Kahane, the  
leader of the Jewish Defense League who was slain Nov. 5, 1990 in a 
Manhattan hotel ballroom. 
</P>
<P>
	Another man, El Sayyid A. Nosair, was acquitted of the murder in  
a 1991 state trial, but was convicted in 1995 on a federal charge 
of murder in aid of racketeering. He was sentenced to life in 
prison. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
