<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Fall in Midday Trading / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo share prices slipped moderately Friday  
morning as investors took profits amid a lack of new evidence of 
recovery in Japan's economy. The dollar edged up against the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average shed 97.64 points,  
or 0.54 percent, to 17,840.01 points at the end of the morning 
session. On Thursday, the average gained 8.75 points, or 0.05 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 122.62 yen in late morning, up 0.24 yen from  
late Thursday in Tokyo and marginally above its late New York level 
of 122.61 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	Stock prices started lower following a decline on Wall Street.  
Prices also suffered some investor concern about the outcome of the 
``special quotation'' settlement for July Nikkei option contracts. 
</P>
<P>
	But with a lack of new signs about the health of the Japanese  
economy, analysts said the quotation shouldn't push the benchmark 
average too far from Thursday's close. 
</P>
<P>
	``There really are no real incentives for investors to buy or  
sell this morning,'' said Kunihiro Hatae, general manager of the 
stock division at Tokyo Securities Co. 
</P>
<P>
	And while approval of a supplementary budget by Japan's Cabinet  
gave stocks a boost Thursday, analysts said the market is already 
looking for a second spending package. 
</P>
<P>
	In the meantime, investors were cashing in on the stock market's  
recent rally, which saw the Nikkei index hit an almost two-year 
high of 18,135.06 points Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section was down 11.81 points, or 0.80 percent, to 1,457.28. 
The TOPIX fell 7.93 points, or 0.54 percent, the day before. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency trading, the dollar changed little from its late New  
York level as many investors remained on the sidelines ahead of the 
weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders said dollar-selling interest among players seems to be  
fading somewhat, but the greenback's rise will be capped as 
enthusiasm for purchasing the currency is also waning. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was quoted at 125.34 yen, up from  
124.94 late Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond rose  
to 1.6750 percent from Thursday's finish of 1.6350 percent, driving 
its price down to 101.08 yen from 101.43 yen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
