<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  3 Track Records Broken in 21 Days </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- With three of track and field's most prestigious  
world records broken in 21 days, and the possibility of more to 
come, the sport is buzzing in the buildup to next month's World 
Championships. 
</P>
<P>
	Records have fallen in succession in the men's 100 meters,  
decathlon and mile, setting standards in the defining sprint, 
multi-event and middle-distance disciplines. 
</P>
<P>
	Morocco's Hicham El Guerrouj smashed the mile record Wednesday  
night at the Golden Gala meet in Rome, clocking 3 minutes, 43.13 
seconds, slicing 1.26 seconds off Noureddine Morceli's 6-year-old 
mark of 3:44.39. 
</P>
<P>
	Noah Ngeny, a 20-year-old Kenyan, also ran under the previous  
record, finishing second in 3:43.40. 
</P>
<P>
	On Sunday at Prague, Tomas Dvorak of the Czech Republic broke  
Dan O'Brien's 7-year-old record in the decathlon. Dvorak amassed 
8,994 points, beating O'Brien's mark by 103 points and falling just 
short of the ``magical barrier'' of 9,000 points. 
</P>
<P>
	The record spree began June 16 at Athens, Greece, where Maurice  
Greene ran 9.79 in the 100, eclipsing Donovan Bailey's 1996 record 
of 9.84. 
</P>
<P>
	Greene kept up his scintillating season by running 9.85 at Rome,  
equaling the third-fastest 100 in history. It was the fastest time 
ever run without being a world record. 
</P>
<P>
	Records in those and other events could be threatened during the  
course of the summer, which includes the World Championships at 
Seville, Spain, Aug. 20-29. 
</P>
<P>
	Primo Nebiolo, president of the International Amateur Athletic  
Federation, said the sport is going through ``a magical moment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``These record results are incredible, and let's hope it  
continues,'' he told The Associated Press. ``It's important that we 
have a big turnover of stars, and from a range of countries. The 
sport keeps evolving.'' 
</P>
<P>
	El Guerrouj broke the mile record on the same track where he set  
the 1,500-meter mark of 3:26.00 a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	After being helped by Kenyan pacemakers Robert Kibet and William  
Tanui until the bell lap, El Guerrouj found himself in a thrilling 
head-to-head duel in the final lap with Ngeny, who broke Jim Ryun's 
world junior record two years ago. El Guerrouj finished just a 
couple of strides ahead. 
</P>
<P>
	The 24-year-old Moroccan joined a select group who have held the  
mile and 1,500-meter records at the same time, including former 
British stars Sebastian Coe and Steve Cram. 
</P>
<P>
	El Guerrouj will next run at Nice July 17, when he will attack  
the 2,000-meter record, held by Morceli. Then he plans to try and 
better his 1,500 mark in a Golden League meet at Paris July 21. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, El Guerrouj has designs on Haile Gebrselassie's  
world record for the 5,000 of 12:19.36. 
</P>
<P>
	Nicknamed the ``Prince of the Desert,'' El Guerrouj has assumed  
the mantle of his great Moroccan predecessor, Said Aouita. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to hold every record that Aouita did,'' he said. ``I  
want to be the strongest in the world at all distances between 
1,500 meters and 5,000. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was Said Aouita, then Morceli. Now it's the hour of  
Hicham. Now I believe only the clock can beat me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	El Guerrouj has won world 1,500-meter titles indoors and  
outdoors, holds world records at 1,500 indoors and outdoors, and 
holds the indoor mile record. 
</P>
<P>
	The only major title missing from his collection is an Olympic  
gold medal. He tripped and fell during the 1996 Olympic 1,500-meter 
final when he was favored for the gold. After El Guerrouj's fall, 
Morceli went to win the race. 
</P>
<P>
	Double Olympic champion Michael Johnson, meanwhile, looks to be  
back in top form, after a quadriceps injury kept him out of the USA 
Championships. He won the 200 meters at Rome in 19.93, his first 
sub-20 clocking since setting the world record of 19.32 at the 1996 
Atlanta Games. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson plans to attack the 400 record of 43.29, held for 11  
years by Butch Reynolds. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
