<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Female Trouble: Now Believable? </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) -- When his cult classic film ``Female  
Trouble'' came out in 1974, its premise seemed really farfetched, 
but now it's almost believable, writer-director John Waters says. 
</P>
<P>
	The film cast the late cross-dressing actor Divine as Dawn  
Davenport, a suburban misfit who wants to be famous so badly she 
sees going to the electric chair as a career highlight. She becomes 
an unwed mother, stripper, prostitute, mugger, child abuser, 
beautician's wife, junkie and a murderous nightclub performer. 
</P>
<P>
	Kicking off a B-movie film series at Ohio State University on  
Wednesday night, Waters introduced the director's cut of ``Female 
Trouble,'' which is scheduled for theatrical release early next 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	He pointed out that the film's treatment of homosexuality and  
incest seems a lot less shocking than it was 25 years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Waters told students gathered at the campus arts center that his  
kind of creativity was discouraged at every school he attended. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can make a snuff movie now and get an A,'' he joked.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
