<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GE Profits Rise 15 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FAIRFIELD, Conn. (AP) -- General Electric Co. reported its  
second-quarter profits rose 15 percent, led by strong performances 
in its aircraft engines, power systems and financial services 
units. 
</P>
<P>
	The nation's fifth-biggest corporation said Thursday it earned  
$2.82 billion, or 85 cents per share, compared with $2.45 billion, 
or 74 cents per share, in the same period last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenues increased 9 percent to $27.41 billion, up from $25.07  
billion, reflecting growth from globalization and product services. 
</P>
<P>
	GE's results were 1 cent per share ahead of analyst  
expectations, according to First Call Corp. However, GE stock was 
down 93 3/4 cents to $117 on the New York Stock Exchange as traders 
took profits after bidding the share price up in recent days. 
</P>
<P>
	At GE Capital Services, GE's financial unit, profits rose 17  
percent to $1.09 billion, up from $933 million in the same period 
last year. 
</P>
<P>
	At GE Power Systems, profits increased 34 percent to $499  
million, up from $372 million a year ago. Profits in the aircraft 
engines division rose 20 percent to $512 million from $427 million 
as the unit won more than 50 percent of the world's engine orders 
for airline passenger jets. 
</P>
<P>
	NBC's profits rose 15 percent to $544 million from $475 million  
as the TV network had strong ratings during the key May sweeps 
period. 
</P>
<P>
	For the first six months of the year, GE's companywise earnings  
rose 15 percent to $4.98 billion, or $1.50 per share, compared with 
$4.34 billion, or $1.31 per share, in the same period in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenues increased 8 percent in the first six months to $51.58  
billion, up from $47.69 billion a year ago. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
