<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> First Lady Courts Jewish Leaders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton, in pursuit of a U.S.  
Senate seat from New York, is assuring Jewish leaders she considers 
Jerusalem ``the eternal and indivisible capital'' of Israel. 
</P>
<P>
	She also says she will actively advocate locating the U.S.  
Embassy there. 
</P>
<P>
	``Of course, the timing of such a move must be sensitive to  
Israel's interest in achieving a secure peace with its neighbors,'' 
Mrs. Clinton wrote Mandell I. Ganchrow, the president of the Union 
of Orthodox Jewish Congregations of America, which represents 
nearly 1,000 Orthodox synagogues in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	In a telephone interview Thursday, Ganchrow called the statement  
by the first lady significant. ``I think it is important she 
understands the seriousness of the issue,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We would want to meet with her and try to gauge her emotional  
attachment to these issues,'' the retired surgeon said. ``I think 
that's fair.'' 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton, in his campaign for the White House in 1992,  
also said Jerusalem should be recognized as Israel's capital. He 
did not follow through once in office, saying the future of the 
city was to be determined by Israel and the Palestinian Authority 
in negotiations. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, Clinton has blocked the shift of the U.S. Embassy to  
Jerusalem from Tel Aviv, using a waiver provision in a 1995 law 
that had authorized the relocation. He cited the prospect of 
negotiations and concerns about the security of Americans and U.S. 
installations. 
</P>
<P>
	Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat is determined to establish a  
state on the West Bank and in Gaza, with its capital in Jerusalem. 
</P>
<P>
	A copy of Mrs. Clinton's letter, dated last Friday and  
responding to a written inquiry from Ganchrow, was obtained by The 
Associated Press after an account was published in Forward, a 
Jewish newspaper. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton is hoping to succeed Sen. Daniel P. Moynihan,  
D-N.Y., a leader in the congressional effort to move the U.S. 
Embassy to Jerusalem. 
</P>
<P>
	A potential opponent in the Senate race, Republican Mayor  
Rudolph Giuliani of New York, has taken strong stands in support of 
Israel and against crime. 
</P>
<P>
	Jews traditionally vote Democratic in New York and across the  
nation, although Giuliani has received strong Jewish support in his 
two successful mayoral campaigns. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton had voiced support for a Palestinian state, a  
position that could alienate some Jewish voters. 
</P>
<P>
	In her letter she made no mention of Palestinian aspirations,  
which the president has supported without specifically calling for 
a state. Instead, Mrs. Clinton stressed her ``strong support for 
Israel and the example it sets as a stable democracy in the Middle 
East.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I personally consider Jerusalem the eternal and indivisible  
capital of Israel, and I admire the leadership of Senator Moynihan 
on this issue,'' she wrote the Orthodox leader. 
</P>
<P>
	In reply, Ganchrow thanked the first lady for her ``strong  
support for Israel'' and her ``stated view'' on Jerusalem as its 
capital. 
</P>
<P>
	The State Department deputy spokesman James Foley said Mrs.  
Clinton had expressed her own views. He said Israel and the 
Palestinians had agreed to take up Jerusalem in negotiations. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990708.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 15:30:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tobacco Co's Can Minimize Damage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- Cigarette makers have a number of legal weapons  
available to minimize the damage caused by a jury's verdict holding 
them responsible for making thousands of Florida smokers sick. 
</P>
<P>
	Those weapons will emerge as the second phase of the massive  
class-action suit begins, pushing back any final ruling from the 
jury on monetary damages for weeks or months, legal experts said 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	In the first class-action lawsuit by smokers to go to trial, the  
jury on Wednesday said five tobacco companies engaged in ``extreme 
and outrageous conduct'' in making a defective product that causes 
emphysema, lung cancer and other illnesses. 
</P>
<P>
	In the next phases, the jury is to decide how much to award the  
lawsuit's nine original plaintiffs. The judge also must deal with 
the complex process of hearing claims of the other members of the 
class, which could number up to 500,000 sick smokers. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a lot of complicated stuff here,'' Stephan Landsman, a  
law professor at DePaul University, said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Perhaps the biggest threat to the suit is the industry's demand  
that the class action be decertified, meaning that the nine smokers 
who have sued would be barred from representing thousands of 
others. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts who folllow tobacco stocks for Wall Street securities  
firms anticipate the case will be decertified, noting Florida is 
the lone state to allow a class-action lawsuit by smokers to reach 
trial. 
</P>
<P>
	``It may take months,'' said David Adelman, a tobacco analyst  
for Morgan Stanley Dean Witter. ``It's going to be thrown out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The suit was filed in 1994 and certified as a class action two  
years later by a Florida appeals court. Circuit Judge Robert Kaye, 
who presided over the trial, will hold a hearing on the issue later 
this month, but is not expected to dissolve the class, meaning an 
appeal to higher courts is a near certainty. 
</P>
<P>
	Most courts thus far have rejected such class actions, saying  
that the reasons for smoking and the diseases are too different to 
bundle all smokers together. 
</P>
<P>
	In May, the U.S. Supreme Court rejected a class-action suit by  
six smokers in Pennsylvania. 
</P>
<P>
	Union health funds have filed class-action suits in 38 states.  
At least nine have been thrown out. 
</P>
<P>
	However, the Louisiana Supreme Court in February upheld a class  
of smokers and ex-smokers seeking money for medical testing. 
</P>
<P>
	In Miami-Dade County Circuit Court Thursday, attorneys and the  
judge discussed when to start the next phase of the case, in which 
evidence will be heard on the health damage suffered by the nine 
main plaintiffs. 
</P>
<P>
	Unlike in the earlier phase, tobacco company lawyers will be  
able to argue that these smokers bear personal responsibility by 
assuming the risk of smoking, knowing it wasn't healthful. 
</P>
<P>
	Since the jury has already sided with the smokers, that defense  
may fail, observers said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nobody's going to go into that case feeling sorry for the  
tobacco companies or even liking them,'' said Robert H. Alexander, 
Jr., co-chairman of the American Bar Association's product 
liability committee. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's still appropriate though for plaintiffs to be (held)  
responsible for creating the situation they're complaining about. 
It's a matter of how receptive the jury is to that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The plaintiffs told Judge Kaye Thursday they will be ready for  
the next phase in two weeks. The tobacco attorneys requested two 
months. Kaye could set the start date on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Florida plaintiffs want at least $200 billion in damages.  
Named as defendants are the nation's five biggest cigarette makers 
and two industry groups: Philip Morris, R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Co., 
Brown &AMP; Williamson Tobacco Corp., Lorillard Tobacco Co. and Liggett 
Group Inc., as well as the Council for Tobacco Research and the 
Tobacco Institute. 
</P>
<P>
	Stocks of most of the companies continued to fall Thursday, just  
as they had after the verdict. 
</P>
<P>
	R.J. Reynolds lost 75 cents to close at $30.12 1/2 on the New York  
Stock Exchange. Loews Corp., parent of Lorillard, lost $1.12 1/2 to 
$77.93 3/4. British American Tobacco, parent of Brown &AMP; Williamson, 
fell 56 1/4 cents to $17.75. Brooke Group, parent of Lorillard, fell 
$1.56 1/4 to $21.93 3/4. 
</P>
<P>
	Philip Morris, which suffered the heaviest loss Wednesday, rose  
slightly, gaining 37 1/2 cents to $38.25. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
