<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tobacco Industry Lawsuits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	U.S. juries have awarded damages in smoking liability cases only  
five times -- twice in Florida and once in New Jersey, Oregon and 
California. The Florida and New Jersey verdicts were overturned on 
appeal. The Oregon and California cases, which were handed down 
this year, are being appealed. 
</P>
<P>
	A look at tobacco-related verdicts that have been handed down in  
1999, not including Wednesday's ruling in Florida. 

</P>
<P>
 *AGAINST TOBACCO:   	
</P>
<P>
	-- Feb. 9, in San Francisco: A San Francisco Superior Court jury  
awards women with inoperable lung cancer $51.5 million in her 
lawsuit against Philip Morris. The judge cuts the award to $26.5 
million on April 6. 
</P>
<P>
	-- March 30, in Portland, Ore.: A state court jury orders Philip  
Morris to pay $80.3 million to the family of a Marlboro smoker who 
died of lung cancer in 1997. The judge reduces the award to $32.8 
million on May 13, which stands as the largest judgment ever 
against a tobacco company. 

</P>
<P>
 *FOR TOBACCO:   	
</P>
<P>
	-- March 18, Akron, Ohio: A federal jury rejects a $2 billion  
attempt by Ohio union health funds to recover the costs of treating 
workers' smoking-related illnesses. 
</P>
<P>
	-- May 10, Memphis, Tenn.: A state court clears three of the  
nation's largest tobacco companies of liability in the deaths of 
three smokers whose families claimed the companies and their 
cigarettes were responsible.. 
</P>
<P>
	-- May 13, Kansas City, Mo.: A federal jury rules in favor of  
Brown &AMP; Williamson Tobacco Corp. deciding they were not at fault in 
the case of a smoker who died of lung cancer in 1995. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
