<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Euro Hits Another Low; Dollar Rises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The euro slipped to another low against the  
dollar in New York Thursday but rebounded on rumors that the 
European Central Bank might intervene in markets to support its 
flagging currency. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro went as low as 1.0146, its latest in a series of new  
lows against the dollar, but rose back to $1.0214 in late New York 
trading on market rumors of ECB intervention. The euro was quoted 
at $1.0226 late Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro has been struggling since its debut in January as signs  
of weakness in the European economy and the conflict in Kosovo have 
darkened prospects for the region's new currency. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar also rose against other major currencies amid signs  
of continued strength in the U.S. economy. Bullish comments from 
incoming Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers Thursday reinforced 
the positive sentiment toward the dollar. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel good about where the economy is,'' Summers said in a  
television interview on NBC's ``Today,'' just one week into his 
job. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar was quoted at 122.61 Japanese yen, up from 122.23.  
The dollar also was quoted at 1.5713 Swiss francs, up from 1.5693, 
and 1.4720 Canadian dollars, up from 1.4700. The British pound fell 
to $1.5588 from $1.5603. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate. 
Based on Thursday's euro rate, the dollar was worth: 1.9150 German 
marks, up from 1.9128 and 6.4226 French francs, up from 6.4144. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
