<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Air Canada, Attendants Reach Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OTTAWA (AP) -- Reaching a deal just minutes after a strike  
deadline passed, Air Canada and its 5,100-member flight attendants 
union agreed on a new contract today and averted a systemwide 
shutdown. 
</P>
<P>
	Pamela Sachs, head of the flight attendants section of the  
Canadian Union of Public Employees, said the union negotiated 
improved retirement income, safer and healthier working conditions 
and wage increases of 5 percent, 4 percent and 3 percent over three 
years. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is a good contract for our 5,000 members, it is a good  
contract for the company and the future of labor relations, and it 
will allow us to give superior service to our customers,'' she 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Sachs said the union didn't get everything it was looking for in  
retirement benefits, but she was satisfied that the company agreed 
to a task force to study the pension plan. 
</P>
<P>
	The settlement came too late for many travelers, who had already  
been forced to re-book flights, find other airlines or cancel their 
plans because of the potential for a strike. 
</P>
<P>
	The airline, which handles about 60,000 passengers a day on 660  
to 700 flights, had said it would halt all its flights if there was 
a strike. The airline had stopped taking reservations for flights 
from Thursday through July 14. 
</P>
<P>
	Air Canada had offered refunds on tickets and helped with  
alternative travel arrangements as it tried to avoid stranding 
passengers for the third time in less than a year. 
</P>
<P>
	``We regret the inconvenience caused to our customers over the  
uncertainty of the past few days and we thank them for their 
understanding,'' said Jean-Jacques Bourgeault, senior executive 
vice-president of the company. 
</P>
<P>
	Air Canada said full details of the agreement will not be  
released until union members ratify the agreement. Union officials 
will be briefing members across the country next week and a 
ratification vote will be held the week of July 19. 
</P>
<P>
	The labor dispute came as Canada's largest airline has just  
started to emerge from the effects of last September's pilots 
strike. That dispute shut down Air Canada for two weeks, alienating 
customers and burdening the airline with a big 1998 loss. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990708.0141 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 06:40:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Elf Plans To Fight TotalFina Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- Elf Aquitaine SA chairman Philippe Jaffre vowed  
Thursday that the French oil company will fight an unsolicited $43 
billion takeover bid from rival TotalFina SA. 
</P>
<P>
	In a speech to senior management, Jaffre said it was too early  
to outline Elf's defense, but he predicted that Total's bid would 
fail. 
</P>
<P>
	TotalFina launched its offer Monday in an attempt to create the  
world's fourth largest oil company in terms of capitalization. The 
proposed group also would be Europe's biggest. 
</P>
<P>
	Elf has rejected the all-stock bid as hostile, although the bid  
has the backing of the French government. 
</P>
<P>
	Jaffre said TotalFina's offer was badly timed because the merger  
would lead to a duplication of exploration and production 
activities as well as overcapacity in refining operations. 
</P>
<P>
	Another factor against a merger would be the need to sell the  
chemical assets of the combined group at some point, Jaffre said in 
comments to Elf staff that were released to news media. 
</P>
<P>
	``I won't hide from you that we have ourselves studied the idea  
of a linkup with Total, but (these) three issues have convinced us 
that it was premature,'' Jaffre said. 
</P>
<P>
	Jaffre said TotalFina's chairman, Thierry Desmarest, had not  
attempted to convince Elf of the merits of his proposal. 
</P>
<P>
	``We might have been able to work together to find satisfactory  
solutions, but hostility and the poor timing instantly destroys the 
key degree of trust between equals needed to build a real merger,'' 
Jaffre said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Elf is master of its own destiny,'' Jaffre said. ``The Total  
bid will fail.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Total and Elf have been under presser to increase their size  
because of the recent consolidation in the oil sector. Total moved 
first by concluding a merger with Belgium's Petrafina. 
</P>
<P>
	Elf failed in a hostile bid to take over Norway's Saga Petroleum  
last week. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
