<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 07:30:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Outrage Toward U.S. Lamb Decision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- Outraged at new penalty tariffs on  
their lamb exports, Australia and New Zealand today accused the 
United States of hypocrisy and promised to seek retribution in 
international trade forums. 
</P>
<P>
	The new tariffs on foreign lamb shipped into the United States  
were announced in an effort to protect U.S. producers, who had 
complained their livelihoods were threatened by cheaper lamb 
shipped from New Zealand and Australia. 
</P>
<P>
	But Australian Prime Minister John Howard, on a Tokyo visit,  
said he would tell President Clinton at a meeting scheduled in 
Washington next week that he is appalled by the decision. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is no possible justification for this,'' Howard told  
reporters. ``On every score, it is deserving of total 
condemnation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Australian Agriculture Minister Mark Vaile used the Australian  
slang for genuine -- dinkum -- as he criticized the U.S. decision. 
</P>
<P>
	``This action demonstrates to the world that the U.S. is not  
fair dinkum about fair trade,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton's decision, effective July 22, will impose a border tax  
of 9 percent on the first 31,851 metric tons -- about 70 million 
pounds -- of foreign lamb, the amount imported into the United 
States last year. Lamb imports above that level will carry a 40 
percent tariff, the White House said. 
</P>
<P>
	Australia and New Zealand have built lamb markets in the United  
States worth more than $150 million a year. About 95 percent of 
lamb sold in America now comes from those two countries. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. announcement on Wednesday that it would impose the  
tariffs comes just months before it will host World Trade 
Organization talks in Seattle. 
</P>
<P>
	As a member of the Asia Pacific Economic Cooperation forum, the  
United States last month called for the WTO to launch a new world 
trade round, and for it to include agricultural trade. 
</P>
<P>
	Australia and New Zealand said they would jointly take the issue  
before the WTO, which mediates trade disputes. 
</P>
<P>
	``New Zealand cannot and will not let the matter rest,'' said  
Prime Minister Jenny Shipley. ``We have immediately started active 
consideration of our WTO options.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Howard said the United States has argued ``long and loudly that  
it favors free trade and the opening up, in particular, of 
agricultural markets.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It's now taken a decision which strikes at the credibility of  
its rhetoric,'' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
