<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NBA Players To Face Marijuana Tests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NASSAU, Bahamas (AP) -- NBA players are being warned by their  
union reps: Smoking marijuana in July could lead to a failed drug 
test in October. 
</P>
<P>
	``Certainly there are guys out there using, and hopefully  
they'll get the message that they have to stop,'' player rep Jim 
McIlvaine of the New Jersey Nets said Wednesday at the union's 
annual meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	A fact sheet being handed out to player representatives for the  
29 teams states that marijuana can stay in a person's system for 
60-90 days. 
</P>
<P>
	And with marijuana being added to the NBA's list of banned  
substances for the 1999-2000 season, the union wants its 
pot-smoking members to knock it off now so they won't produce a 
dirty urine sample when training camps open. 
</P>
<P>
	``When the testing comes, the proof will be in the pudding,''  
said union director Billy Hunter, who scoffed at a report in 1997 
saying about 70 percent of the league's players either use 
marijuana or are heavy drinkers. 
</P>
<P>
	Many players taking part in the union meeting said there are a  
number of marijuana users, although they claim the total is nothing 
close to 70 percent of the player population. 
</P>
<P>
	Several players, including Chris Webber, Mookie Blaylock, Vernon  
Maxwell and J.R. Rider, have been arrested on marijuana-related 
charges. 
</P>
<P>
	Sacramento Kings guard Jason Williams was kicked off his college  
team at Florida for testing positive for marijuana twice. 
</P>
<P>
	NBA players who test positive at training camp must undergo a  
mandatory counseling program. A second positive test brings a 
$15,000 fine, and any third or subsequent positive test results in 
a five-game suspension. 
</P>
<P>
	All players will be tested when training camps open in October,  
and rookies will be tested four times per season on a random basis. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would think that if guys are using, they got the message  
last year that they'll be tested,'' Tyrone Corbin of the Atlanta 
Hawks said. ``Some guys, just like society in general, don't get 
the message until they're caught. Hopefully, they'll get this 
message and it won't put their careers in jeopardy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Steroids were also added to the league's banned substances list  
during the last collective bargaining negotiations. 
Androstenedione, the testosterone-producing substance taken by 
baseball slugger Mark McGwire and others, is not on the list. 
</P>
<P>
	``The NBA is like any industry, there's going to be people on  
drugs,'' Jim McIlvaine of the New Jersey Nets said. ``As role 
models, people need to know that we don't condone its use. 
</P>
<P>
	A player also can be tested during the regular season if an  
arbitrator decides, after a hearing, there is reasonable cause to 
believe a player has used, possessed or distributed any prohibited 
substance. 
</P>
<P>
	Anyone testing positive for steroids gets a five-game suspension  
for the first offense, a 10-game suspension for a second offense 
and a 25-game suspension for a third offense. 
</P>
<P>
	Penalties for such illegal narcotics as cocaine, heroin and PCP  
are much more severe. A positive drug test -- or a conviction or 
guilty plea to a crime involving one of those drugs -- can lead to 
disqualification from the NBA. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think it's a very big problem in the league,'' said  
Corbin, who was at Vancouver's airport in 1997 when Blaylock, his 
Hawks teammate, was found to be carrying marijuana by a 
drug-sniffing dog. 
</P>
<P>
	Danny Schayes of the Orlando Magic said reports of widespread  
usage are overblown. However, he said drug use -- and not just 
marijuana -- was a serious problem when he entered the league in 
1981. 
</P>
<P>
	``Anything going on today is mild compared to 20 years ago,'' he  
said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
