<HEADLINE> Ben Crenshaw Exits British Open  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CARNOUSTIE, Scotland (AP) -- U.S. Ryder Cup captain Ben Crenshaw  
pulled out of next week's British Open, organizers said today. 
</P>
<P>
	Crenshaw faxed the Royal and Ancient Club saying he did not  
consider his game up to the championship. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to give my space to somebody who could make better use  
of it,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Crenshaw, 47, has finished 213th and 268th on the U.S. Tour the  
last two seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	He was exempt from qualifying for the Open by virtue of his 1995  
Masters victory. Crenshaw tied for second at the British Open 
behind Jack Nicklaus in 1978 at St. Andrews, and Seve Ballesteros 
at Lytham in 1980. 
</P>
<P>
	His withdrawal came a day after former Ryder Cup captain Tom  
Kite announced he was pulling out because of poor form. 
</P>
<P>
	Nicklaus will miss the Open with a hip injury.  
  	   	
</P>
