<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> No Air Bag Probe for DaimlerChrysler </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal transportation officials have decided  
against opening a formal investigation of children killed by air 
bags in DaimlerChrysler minivans, saying the number is in line with 
similar incidents involving other vehicles. 
</P>
<P>
	A National Highway Traffic Safety Administration official said  
Wednesday that while the total number of such deaths was higher 
than those in other vehicles, when the rate was calculated it was 
no worse than that of other vehicles because DaimlerChrysler was 
the first to offer passenger-side airbags 
</P>
<P>
	The NHTSA did decide to launch a formal defects investigation of  
Hyundai Motor Co.'s two-door Accent model. Passenger-side airbags 
in the Accent had killed five people, all children or small adults, 
the official said, speaking on condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the NHTSA will continue to gather further information  
about DaimlerChrysler's air bags, and those of other automakers. 
</P>
<P>
	In May, NHTSA laboratory testing found that inflating air bags  
in some DaimlerChrysler minivans could seriously injure or kill 
short female passengers. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to continue to monitor the situation, because  
although we don't see any evidence in the real world of a problem, 
we nevertheless continue to be concerned about the results we had 
in the laboratory,'' the NHTSA official said. 
</P>
<P>
	Consumer advocacy groups have urged the safety agency to force  
DaimlerChrysler to recall the more than 2 million minivans the 
company has built since 1994 and replace the air bags with less 
forceful ones. Most of those minivans were built before Chrysler 
Corp.'s acquisition last year by Germany's Daimler-Benz. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990708.0156 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 15:00:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Amtrak Train Hits Truck, Derails </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EAGLE LAKE, Texas (AP) -- An Amtrak train carrying 235 passengers  
struck a truck Thursday, derailing nine cars and injuring 18 
people. 
</P>
<P>
	The eastbound Sunset Limited was traveling from Los Angeles to  
Orlando, Fla., when it hit the rig shortly before noon, Steven 
Taub, an Amtrak spokesman, said. Track was torn up and two engines 
and seven cars were off to the side. 
</P>
<P>
	``It wasn't that big of a bump,'' said Sally Brichler, 36, of  
Deltona, Fla., who was traveling with her daughters, ages 9 and 5. 
``A couple of big jolts. It didn't even knock the milk off our 
tray.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Passengers said they heard the train's whistle blowing just  
before the collision with the truck, which was pulling a salt water 
tank. Some riders crawled through a window as smoke filled the 
cars. Screaming could be heard, they said. 
</P>
<P>
	An engineer and an engineer in training had to be pulled from  
the wreckage by rescuers who broke out the engine windshield. The 
engineer was listed in guarded condition with a head injury, 
hospital officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	The truck driver was unharmed.  
</P>
<P>
	David Keith, administrator of the Rice Medical Center in Eagle  
Lake, said most of the injured had bumps, bruises or were suffering 
from heat exhaustion. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nothing we would consider serious,'' he said. ``A lot of them  
were shaken up. A lot of them were in tears.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jason Goggans, an assistant conductor on the train, said  
passengers were calm in the aftermath of the accident. 
</P>
<P>
	``I felt the brakes go into emergency before we actually hit,''  
he said. ``You just grab on. You don't know what to expect. We knew 
something was going to happen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There were no warning lights or gates at the rural crossing  
where the accident happened, about 62 miles west of Houston. About 
16 trains a day travel on the track. 
</P>
<P>
	Passengers gathered under trees to shade them from the  
90-plus-degree heat and school buses were being used to take them 
to Eagle Lake. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the passengers were Cindy McCain, the wife of Sen. John  
McCain, and their 13-year-old son, Jack. They two, who were unhurt, 
were headed to Florida for a vacation, said McCain spokesman Howard 
Opinsky. The senator himself was on a plane, headed to Seattle for 
a speech. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sunset Limited was involved in the worst accident in  
Amtrak's 28-year history. On Sept. 22, 1993, 42 passengers and five 
crew members died when the train went off a bridge into a bayou 
near Mobile, Ala. The bridge had been damaged minutes earlier when 
it was hit by a towboat. 
</P>
<P>
	In March, Amtrak's City of New Orleans ran into a truck at a  
crossing in Bourbonnais, Ill., killing 11 people and injuring more 
than 100. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990708.0157 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 13:10:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> McCarty: NCAA Title to WNBA Bench </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- Anyone who doubts the role of confidence  
in basketball hasn't talked to Stephanie McCarty. In three months, 
she has gone from the toast of the NCAA tournament to getting 
benched in the WNBA. 
</P>
<P>
	The top scorer on the best team in college basketball last  
season, McCarty followed her Purdue career by quickly working her 
way into the Charlotte Sting's starting lineup. But she responded 
to her promotion by lapsing into an uncharacteristic shooting slump 
that hurt her team and landed her back in a reserve role. 
</P>
<P>
	``Right now I'm going through a little funk,'' said McCarty, who  
has come off the bench in the past two games after shooting only 23 
percent during her five games as a starter. 
</P>
<P>
	The inconsistency of McCarty's rookie season has been a stark  
turnabout for a player who had perhaps the greatest prep career by 
a woman in Indiana history before becoming the second-leading 
career scorer at Purdue. 
</P>
<P>
	After scoring a state-record 2,869 points in high school,  
McCarty scored 2,182 in college, including an average of 20.4 as a 
senior. She was an All-American and the top female athlete in the 
Big Ten, and topped off her college career by becoming the first 
player to cut down the nets after the Boilermakers' 17-point 
victory over Duke in the title game. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sting, who made the playoffs in each of the WNBA's first two  
seasons, drafted McCarty with the hope that the addition of a good 
outside shooter would help them challenge Houston for league 
supremacy. Early signs were that Charlotte made a wise choice. 
</P>
<P>
	Coming off the bench, McCarty made 55 percent of her field-goal  
attempts over the Sting's first three games and scored in double 
figures each time. So when small forward Tracy Reid went on the 
injured list with a sore knee, it seemed natural to fill her spot 
in the starting lineup with McCarty. 
</P>
<P>
	But McCarty scored only 17 points over the next five games,  
missing 20 of 26 field-goal attempts. After McCarty missed all 
eight of her shots in a two-game stretch, coach Marynell Meadors 
sent her back to the bench. 
</P>
<P>
	McCarty has made five of eight shots in the two games since her  
demotion, and Charlotte has won both times to climb into second 
place in the Eastern Conference. 
</P>
<P>
	``I like having Stephanie come off the bench now,'' Meadors  
said. ``It seems to be good for her. She's more relaxed, and 
there's not as much pressure.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McCarty, who scored in double figures in every game of her  
senior season, said there are no easy answers for her struggles in 
the WNBA. 
</P>
<P>
	``The biggest thing is mental,'' she said. ``When I go out and  
miss a couple of shots, I get down. I'm my hardest critic. I know I 
can shoot. I need to go out and do it. And if it's not falling, I 
need to keep shooting.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McCarty has had to make the usual adjustments that college  
players encounter in the jump to the pros: dealing with compressed 
schedules, more travel and players who are bigger, stronger and 
faster. 
</P>
<P>
	A big difference she has found is that she can't take as much  
time to shoot in the pros because the defenders can close on her 
faster. Meadors is working with McCarty in practice to help develop 
a quicker release. 
</P>
<P>
	``What it comes down to is I need to get more confidence,''  
McCarty said. ``I'm not here to do anything flashy. I just want to 
help this team win, and confidence is a big part of that.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990708.0158 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 10:10:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  1 Dead, Hundreds Rescued From Ferry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GOTEBORG, Sweden (AP) -- The smell of acrid smoke and the sound  
of fire alarms woke passengers on an overnight ferry from Germany 
to Norway today, when a fire below decks forced a pre-dawn 
evacuation of hundreds of tourists. 
</P>
<P>
	A distress call from the Prinsesse Ragnhild went out at 2:13  
a.m., within moments of the fire's detection, and the decision was 
quickly made to abandon the ferry, which had 1,167 passengers and 
172 crew members on board. 
</P>
<P>
	The fire broke out -- either in the engine or machine room -- from  
causes still unknown. 
</P>
<P>
	A 70-year-old woman died hours later of heart failure in a  
hospital in this Swedish port city, where the ferry was towed, said 
Per Oertenvall, a physician. He refused to release her name or 
nationality, although news reports said she was Norwegian. 
</P>
<P>
	Reported injuries were limited to three passengers treated for  
smoke inhalation -- in what experts praised as a textbook evacuation 
of the 670-foot-long ferry sailing from Kiel, Germany, to Oslo, 
Norway. The passengers evacuated the boat 11 miles off Sweden's 
coast. 
</P>
<P>
	``I noticed the smell of smoke in the cabin ... and then the  
alarm sounded ... and then it was just a matter of getting dressed 
as fast as you could and take your most important things with 
you,'' Knut Gran of Norway told Norway state radio NRK. 
</P>
<P>
	While passengers filed into lifeboats, another ferry and a  
smaller boat pulled alongside within a half hour, taking on 500 
passengers. Twenty other vessels and six helicopters later joined 
the effort, rescuers said. 
</P>
<P>
	Calm seas and windless weather helped the evacuation. Within  
about four hours, the fire was under control and virtually all 
passengers -- most of them Norwegian tourists -- were taken off and 
brought to Goteborg. The ship was also towed to the Swedish port 
city. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was never any panic,'' 70-year-old Marit  
Stakvik-Joergensen of Oslo told Swedish news agency TT. ``Some 
probably thought at first that it was just a drill, but when they 
put the life jackets on and felt the smoke, then they understood it 
was serious.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But for many, it was still jarring.  
</P>
<P>
	``It was pretty scary,'' said a young Norwegian boy, Marius  
Johansen. ``It felt like a long time in the little boat, but really 
it was probably half an hour.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Anne-Lise Gaustad, an elderly woman from Norway, said she and  
others were given wet towels to breathe through because of smoke. 
``I still have a headache,'' she said. ``We're pretty shaken.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The engine room seems badly damaged and ``looks like an  
ashtray,'' Arne Slorafoss, a Norwegian passenger, told NRK. 
Slorafoss, a truck driver, volunteered to stay aboard and help the 
crew with salvage efforts. 
</P>
<P>
	The close call chilled Scandinavians who recalled two ferry  
disasters in the region this decade. 
</P>
<P>
	On April 7, 1990, the Scandinavian Star passenger ferry caught  
fire on an overnight run from Denmark to Norway, killing 159 people 
in the same waters off western Sweden. 
</P>
<P>
	In September 1994, 852 people died when the Estonia ferry went  
down in heavy seas en route to Stockholm from the Estonian capital 
Tallinn. Only 137 people survived. 
</P>
<P>
	Konrad Havig of Norway's Maritime Directorate said the earlier  
disasters brought about safety improvements, including improved 
signs and markings for evacuation and smoke detectors. 
</P>
<P>
	The evacuation of the Prinsesse Ragnhild ``is a textbook example  
of how something like this should be handled. It seems that way, at 
least,'' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990708.0159 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 10:10:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  1 Dead, Hundreds Rescued From Ferry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GOTEBORG, Sweden (AP) -- The smell of acrid smoke and the sound  
of fire alarms woke passengers on an overnight ferry from Germany 
to Norway today, when a fire below decks forced a pre-dawn 
evacuation of hundreds of tourists. 
</P>
<P>
	A distress call from the Prinsesse Ragnhild went out at 2:13  
a.m., within moments of the fire's detection, and the decision was 
quickly made to abandon the ferry, which had 1,167 passengers and 
172 crew members on board. 
</P>
<P>
	The fire broke out -- either in the engine or machine room -- from  
causes still unknown. 
</P>
<P>
	A 70-year-old woman died hours later of heart failure in a  
hospital in this Swedish port city, where the ferry was towed, said 
Per Oertenvall, a physician. He refused to release her name or 
nationality, although news reports said she was Norwegian. 
</P>
<P>
	Reported injuries were limited to three passengers treated for  
smoke inhalation -- in what experts praised as a textbook evacuation 
of the 670-foot-long ferry sailing from Kiel, Germany, to Oslo, 
Norway. The passengers evacuated the boat 11 miles off Sweden's 
coast. 
</P>
<P>
	``I noticed the smell of smoke in the cabin ... and then the  
alarm sounded ... and then it was just a matter of getting dressed 
as fast as you could and take your most important things with 
you,'' Knut Gran of Norway told Norway state radio NRK. 
</P>
<P>
	While passengers filed into lifeboats, another ferry and a  
smaller boat pulled alongside within a half hour, taking on 500 
passengers. Twenty other vessels and six helicopters later joined 
the effort, rescuers said. 
</P>
<P>
	Calm seas and windless weather helped the evacuation. Within  
about four hours, the fire was under control and virtually all 
passengers -- most of them Norwegian tourists -- were taken off and 
brought to Goteborg. The ship was also towed to the Swedish port 
city. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was never any panic,'' 70-year-old Marit  
Stakvik-Joergensen of Oslo told Swedish news agency TT. ``Some 
probably thought at first that it was just a drill, but when they 
put the life jackets on and felt the smoke, then they understood it 
was serious.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But for many, it was still jarring.  
</P>
<P>
	``It was pretty scary,'' said a young Norwegian boy, Marius  
Johansen. ``It felt like a long time in the little boat, but really 
it was probably half an hour.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Anne-Lise Gaustad, an elderly woman from Norway, said she and  
others were given wet towels to breathe through because of smoke. 
``I still have a headache,'' she said. ``We're pretty shaken.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The engine room seems badly damaged and ``looks like an  
ashtray,'' Arne Slorafoss, a Norwegian passenger, told NRK. 
Slorafoss, a truck driver, volunteered to stay aboard and help the 
crew with salvage efforts. 
</P>
<P>
	The close call chilled Scandinavians who recalled two ferry  
disasters in the region this decade. 
</P>
<P>
	On April 7, 1990, the Scandinavian Star passenger ferry caught  
fire on an overnight run from Denmark to Norway, killing 159 people 
in the same waters off western Sweden. 
</P>
<P>
	In September 1994, 852 people died when the Estonia ferry went  
down in heavy seas en route to Stockholm from the Estonian capital 
Tallinn. Only 137 people survived. 
</P>
<P>
	Konrad Havig of Norway's Maritime Directorate said the earlier  
disasters brought about safety improvements, including improved 
signs and markings for evacuation and smoke detectors. 
</P>
<P>
	The evacuation of the Prinsesse Ragnhild ``is a textbook example  
of how something like this should be handled. It seems that way, at 
least,'' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
