<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Charge for Complaining in Dallas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- At the Better Business Bureau here, you can  
complain all you want to -- but it'll cost you. 
</P>
<P>
	The agency, which has traditionally had no fees for its service,  
began this month to charge $9.50 for handling each complaint 
against a business. The bureau contends the fee is needed to speed 
up services, but officials at other BBB offices say that charging 
money is against their mission. 
</P>
<P>
	In Dallas, a current exception to the fee is when a complaint is  
filed over the bureau's World Wide Web site. Also, the fee will be 
waived for consumers who say they can't afford it, according to Jay 
Newman, president of the bureau. 
</P>
<P>
	The Council of Better Business Bureaus, the Virginia-based  
overseer of BBB offices, now forbids charging for the agency's 
Internet services. But the Dallas bureau will seek permission from 
the council in October to charge $9.50 for handling complaints 
filed on the Web. 
</P>
<P>
	Newman contends that such revenues will allow the Dallas BBB to  
expand and speed up services for consumers as well as invest more 
in technology. He says the bureau spends $19.90 to process a 
complaint, excluding arbitration and mediation expenses. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dallas bureau, which serves 13 counties, handles an average  
of about 1,400 complaints monthly. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not going to charge somebody who's already been scammed  
for the privilege of telling me about it,'' John Riggins, president 
of the Better Business Bureau of Fort Worth, told The Dallas 
Morning News in Thursday's editions. 
</P>
<P>
	Only about a dozen of the 132 BBB chapters in the United States  
and Puerto Rico now charge for various services, the newspaper 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I applaud the desire to want to cut new ground, but we're  
tax-exempt for a reason,'' said Riggins, ``and one is to serve the 
public. I just don't think that we want to charge. It flies in the 
face of the mission of the organization.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
