<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AutoNation Buys 16 More Franchises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- AutoNation Inc., the largest owner of car  
dealerships, announced plans Thursday to acquire 16 more franchises 
in five states for about $200 million cash as part of its 
continuing expansion into the nation's major markets. 
</P>
<P>
	AutoNation said the dealerships combined generate about $1  
billion in annual revenue. And more deals are on the way: Spokesman 
Oscar Suris said dealerships worth an additional $10 billion in 
revenue are in the acquisition pipeline. 
</P>
<P>
	The Fort Lauderdale, Fla.-based company, formerly called  
Republic Industries Inc., plans eventually to turn its dealerships 
into a nationwide network of one-stop shopping centers for new and 
used cars, service, parts, rentals and accessories under the 
AutoNation USA name. 
</P>
<P>
	Run by billionaire financier H. Wayne Huizenga, AutoNation began  
buying new-car dealerships in December 1996 and within months was 
the largest automotive retailer in the nation. The latest additions 
to the AutoNation chain are in California, Colorado, Florida, Texas 
and Washington state. 
</P>
<P>
	In Southern California, AutoNation is buying the nine-franchise  
York Automotive Group, which will give it 69 franchises in the 
region. York operates seven franchises in Valencia, a Ford 
dealership in Huntington Beach and a Land Rover franchise in 
Encino. 
</P>
<P>
	In Washington, AutoNation plans to buy the six-franchise Maria  
Smith Automotive Group, which includes Town &AMP; Country Chrysler in 
Seattle, Kirkland Ford, Bellevue Dodge and Kirkland 
Pontiac-Buick-GMC. The company also is buying Prestige Ford in 
Bellevue. 
</P>
<P>
	AutoNation also said it will buy Shamrock Ford in Dublin,  
Calif., near San Francisco; Phil Steakley Chevrolet in Dallas; 
Smith Toyota in Sunrise, Fla.; and Courtesy Ford in Littleton, 
Colo., near Denver. 
</P>
<P>
	Only the Maria Smith deal has closed; the others are still  
subject to approval by the automakers and state governments, Suris 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	AutoNation also recently announced plans to expand its ability  
to sell cars over the Internet through a new nationwide World Wide 
Web site, AutoNationDirect.com. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of AutoNation closed down 56 1/2 cents Thursday, at $15.50,  
on the New York Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	The company, which also owns National Car Rental Systems Inc.  
and Alamo Rent-A-Car Inc., had 1998 sales of $17.5 billion. With 
the latest deals, AutoNation will have 276 dealerships with 394 
new-car franchises in the nation's top 50 markets. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990708.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 03:40:15 </DATE_TIME>
