<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Moroccan Sets New Mile Run Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ROME (AP) -- Hicham El Guerrouj figures he can break the world  
record in the mile. His own record. The one he set Wednesday night. 
</P>
<P>
	The Moroccan shaved 1.26 seconds off the 6-year-old mark of  
Noureddine Morceli when he outsprinted Kenyan Noah N'Geny on the 
final stretch at the Gold Gala track and field meet. 
</P>
<P>
	``I could have gone as low as 3:42 without the comeback of  
N'Geny, who distracted me in the final 150 meters,'' the 
24-year-old El Guerrouj said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Kenyan also went below Morceli's old record, finishing  
second in 3:43.30. 
</P>
<P>
	A 1977 world champion in the 1,500 at Athens, Greece, El  
Guerrouj set a mile record of 3:43.13 but did not set limits to his 
ambition. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope God continues to give me strength because I want to be  
the strongest in the world at all distances between 1,500 and 
5,000,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	El Guerrouj, who broke the world mark set by Morceli in the  
1,500 meters at Rome last year, said he planned to rest a week in 
Belgium before running the 1,500 meters at the next stage of the 
IAAF Golden League in Paris on July 21. 
</P>
<P>
	By breaking one of track's most hallowed records, El Guerrouj  
stole the limelight from American sprinters who still produced 
outstanding performances at the Italian meet. 
</P>
<P>
	World champion Maurice Greene set a meet record of 9.85 seconds  
in the 100 meters, .06 off his world mark set in Athens last month. 
</P>
<P>
	Michael Johnson, running his first 200 meters in six weeks,  
upset Ato Boldon, who had been the fastest over the distance so far 
this season. Johnson also set a meet record, in 19.93, and said he 
was just glad ``because I'm healthy again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He had missed the U.S. championships and the opening GL stage in  
Oslo, Norway, last week because of injury. 
</P>
<P>
	Marion Jones extended her four-year unbeaten streak in the  
women's 200 by scoring her second consecutive victory in the Golden 
League Series and staying in the running for the $1 million 
jackpot. The rich money prize is shared by all athletes who win the 
same event in all seven GL meets. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones, who shared last year's jackpot with El Guerrouj and long  
distance runner Haile Gebrselassie, said she was returning home to 
stay with the family and train quietly before the next GL leg. 
</P>
<P>
	Those keeping a winning streak for the jackpot after the Golden  
Gala included Allen Johnson in the 110-meter hurdles, Wilson 
Kipketer in the 800, Erick Walder in the long jump, Bernard 
Barmasai in the 3,000 steeplechase, Gabriela Szabo in the women's 
3,000 and Svetlana Masterkova in the women's 800. 
</P>
<P>
	The mile and the 100 meters do not count for the Golden League.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990708.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 15:40:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NASA Clears Telescope for Launch </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) -- The largest and most powerful X-ray  
telescope ever to be launched will leave aboard the space shuttle 
Columbia on July 20, the anniversary of man's first moon landing, 
NASA said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The five-day shuttle mission, led by Eileen Collins, NASA's  
first female commander, is scheduled to be launched at 12:36 a.m. 
</P>
<P>
	The mission had been surrounded in uncertainty since an Air  
Force rocket left a military satellite in the wrong orbit back in 
April. The problem was traced to an upper-stage motor. 
</P>
<P>
	The $1.5 billion Chandra X-ray Observatory has the same type of  
motor, and NASA wanted to be sure there was nothing wrong with it. 
</P>
<P>
	Chandra's attached motor is supposed to place it in an oval  
orbit, with a high point one-third of the way to the moon. 
</P>
<P>
	In development since the 1970s, Chandra is meant to detect faint  
sources of cosmic X-rays, such as quasars, exploded stars and 
possibly black holes. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990708.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 14:56:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  McCarty: NCAA Title to WNBA Bench </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- Anyone who doubts the role of confidence  
in basketball hasn't talked to Stephanie McCarty. In three months, 
she has gone from the toast of the NCAA tournament to getting 
benched in the WNBA. 
</P>
<P>
	The top scorer on the best team in college basketball last  
season, McCarty followed her Purdue career by quickly working her 
way into the Charlotte Sting's starting lineup. But she responded 
to her promotion by lapsing into an uncharacteristic shooting slump 
that hurt her team and landed her back in a reserve role. 
</P>
<P>
	``Right now I'm going through a little funk,'' said McCarty, who  
has come off the bench in the past two games after shooting only 23 
percent during her five games as a starter. 
</P>
<P>
	The inconsistency of McCarty's rookie season has been a stark  
turnabout for a player who had perhaps the greatest prep career by 
a woman in Indiana history before becoming the second-leading 
career scorer at Purdue. 
</P>
<P>
	After scoring a state-record 2,869 points in high school,  
McCarty scored 2,182 in college, including an average of 20.4 as a 
senior. She was an All-American and the top female athlete in the 
Big Ten, and topped off her college career by becoming the first 
player to cut down the nets after the Boilermakers' 17-point 
victory over Duke in the title game. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sting, who made the playoffs in each of the WNBA's first two  
seasons, drafted McCarty with the hope that the addition of a good 
outside shooter would help them challenge Houston for league 
supremacy. Early signs were that Charlotte made a wise choice. 
</P>
<P>
	Coming off the bench, McCarty made 55 percent of her field-goal  
attempts over the Sting's first three games and scored in double 
figures each time. So when small forward Tracy Reid went on the 
injured list with a sore knee, it seemed natural to fill her spot 
in the starting lineup with McCarty. 
</P>
<P>
	But McCarty scored only 17 points over the next five games,  
missing 20 of 26 field-goal attempts. After McCarty missed all 
eight of her shots in a two-game stretch, coach Marynell Meadors 
sent her back to the bench. 
</P>
<P>
	McCarty has made five of eight shots in the two games since her  
demotion, and Charlotte has won both times to climb into second 
place in the Eastern Conference. 
</P>
<P>
	``I like having Stephanie come off the bench now,'' Meadors  
said. ``It seems to be good for her. She's more relaxed, and 
there's not as much pressure.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McCarty, who scored in double figures in every game of her  
senior season, said there are no easy answers for her struggles in 
the WNBA. 
</P>
<P>
	``The biggest thing is mental,'' she said. ``When I go out and  
miss a couple of shots, I get down. I'm my hardest critic. I know I 
can shoot. I need to go out and do it. And if it's not falling, I 
need to keep shooting.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McCarty has had to make the usual adjustments that college  
players encounter in the jump to the pros: dealing with compressed 
schedules, more travel and players who are bigger, stronger and 
faster. 
</P>
<P>
	A big difference she has found is that she can't take as much  
time to shoot in the pros because the defenders can close on her 
faster. Meadors is working with McCarty in practice to help develop 
a quicker release. 
</P>
<P>
	``What it comes down to is I need to get more confidence,''  
McCarty said. ``I'm not here to do anything flashy. I just want to 
help this team win, and confidence is a big part of that.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990708.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 09:00:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mother of Switched Baby Upset </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	STAFFORD, Va. (AP) -- The mother of one of two girls switched at  
birth more than four years ago reacted angrily when a judge ordered 
the custody hearing moved to the hometown of the other family. 
</P>
<P>
	Screaming ``she's my child'' outside the Stafford County  
courthouse where the ruling was made Wednesday, Paula Johnson vowed 
to get custody of Rebecca Grace Chittum from the families that have 
been raising her, the Free Lance-Star of Fredericksburg reported 
today. 
</P>
<P>
	Juvenile and Domestic Relations Court Judge J. Martin Bass  
refused to hear Ms. Johnson's custody bid for her biological 
daughte, who was switched with another newborn in 1995. Bass handed 
the case to the court in Buena Vista, where Rebecca lives with 
families rearing her. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Johnson said Wednesday night she will appeal the ruling.  
</P>
<P>
	Efforts to reach Ms. Johnson at her Stafford County home today  
were unsuccessful. Her lawyer was in court and unavailable for 
comment, his office said. 
</P>
<P>
	After the switch was discovered, the families raising the two  
girls -- Callie Conley and Rebecca -- agreed to work together and 
share visitation rights. 
</P>
<P>
	But discord has been growing, and now both sides have filed  
court papers seeking custody of both girls. 
</P>
<P>
	The girls were inadvertently switched at the University of  
Virginia Medical Center more than four years ago, but the mistake 
was not discovered until last year during DNA testing conducted as 
part of a child support disagreement. 
</P>
<P>
	Callie, the biological daughter of Kevin Chittum and Whitney  
Rogers, went home with Ms. Johnson. Chittum and Ms. Rogers died in 
a car accident a year ago, around the time the switch was 
discovered. 
</P>
<P>
	Rebecca, the biological daughter of Ms. Johnson and her former  
boyfriend, Carlton Conley, went home with Chittum and Ms. Rogers, 
and has been raised since their death by the dead couple's two sets 
of parents. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990708.0166 </DOCNO>
