<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Oakland Dock Workers End Walkout </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) -- Dock workers returned to their jobs today  
after shutting down the Oakland port for two days in the middle of 
contract negotiations. 
</P>
<P>
	Giant cranes were once again lifting cargo on and off ships at  
the port, where containers of everything from California fruit and 
computer components to Hawaiian cows had been stuck in transit, 
port spokeswoman Roberta Bradley said. 
</P>
<P>
	The walkout by 1,400 workers forced cargo-laden vessels to slow  
down across the Pacific Ocean or wait at anchor in San Francisco 
Bay just outside the port, which handles 12 percent of West Coast 
shipping. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everyone is back at work,'' said Steve Stallone, a spokesman  
for the International Longshore and Warehouse Union local 
representing the stevedores at Oakland. 
</P>
<P>
	He said talks would resume Friday in San Francisco with  
management's Pacific Maritime Association over a new three-year 
contract with the West Coast's 10,000 longshoremen. They have been 
working without a contract since July 1. 
</P>
<P>
	The PMA had asked the National Labor Relations Board to force  
the longshoremen back to the docks. Stallone said union members 
decided Wednesday night to return to work and put the issue that 
prompted the walkout to an arbitrator once a contract is in place. 
</P>
<P>
	Stallone said the work stoppage was spontaneous and not directed  
by union leaders. 
</P>
<P>
	The walkout began Tuesday morning in protest of a management  
decision not to hire a second ``signalman'' below each of the 
port's massive cranes. It's a safety issue, the union said, 
pointing to the potential for serious accidents as the cranes 
transfer trucking containers between tractor-trailers and cargo 
vessels. 
</P>
<P>
	Management characterized the demand as an illegal and  
unnecessarily expensive padding of the work force. 
</P>
<P>
	The work stoppage was limited to the Oakland port, although  
longshoremen in Los Angeles and Long Beach refused to work overtime 
or during lunch. Dock work continued normally in San Diego, Seattle 
and Portland, Ore. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest management contract offer includes a 32 percent boost  
in pension benefits to future retirees and a 15 percent raise for 
those currently retired. 
</P>
<P>
	Pay in 1998 averaged $99,000 for dock workers, $117,617 for  
clerks and $156,251 for foremen, according to the association. 
Stallone said these figures represent total employer costs, 
including taxes and benefits. He said actual salaries are far 
lower. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
