<HEADLINE> Report: China City Cites McDonald's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- A Chinese city has accused McDonald's Corp. of  
breaking the country's labor law and failing to provide more than 
1,000 part-time workers old age and medical insurance, a report 
said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Security Bureau of the southern city of Shenzhen said a  
recent investigation showed that only 400 of McDonald's 1,480 
part-time employees were insured, China's semi-official China News 
Agency reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Although the part-time workers never signed any labor contracts  
with the restaurant, the American fastfood chain is still 
responsible to sign them up for state-run insurance as required by 
law, the agency said. 
</P>
<P>
	Security officials have issued a letter to the company  
requesting an unspecified amount of back payments for the workers, 
except students and people who already have coverage at other 
companies they work for, the agency reported. 
</P>
<P>
	McDonald's greater China representatives were not available for  
comment late Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Most employees work for four to eight hours a day for 50 to 88  
cents per hour, the report said. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
