<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FBI Examines Secret Beckwith Tapes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JACKSON, Miss. (AP) -- The FBI is examining secretly recorded  
jailhouse conversations in which segregationist Byron De La 
Beckwith purportedly brags of shooting blacks and talks about how 
to dispose of bodies in a lake. 
</P>
<P>
	Beckwith, 78, was convicted in 1994 of the ambush killing of  
NAACP official Medgar Evers outside his home in 1963. He is serving 
a life sentence. 
</P>
<P>
	The recordings were made from 1996 to 1998 by Donald Tominello,  
a onetime Beckwith family friend who says he intends to use the 
material to write a book, The Clarion-Ledger reported Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The newspaper included excerpts from a recording supposedly made  
in 1997, in which Beckwith is said to admit shooting blacks ``once 
in awhile, and what's wrong with that?'' 
</P>
<P>
	The FBI said agents are reviewing that tape and about 30 others,  
along with letters written by Beckwith. The tapes have been sent to 
an FBI lab in Washington to determine their authenticity. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities decided to examine the tapes primarily because of a  
conversation Tominello supposedly had with Beckwith regarding the 
possibility of bodies in McIntyre Lake, not far from Beckwith's 
hometown of Greenwood. 
</P>
<P>
	Beckwith questions whether anything would be found if the lake  
were dredged. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you threw somebody in the lake, they usually float up a  
few days later,'' he is quoted as saying. ``What you should do is 
cut 'em open and then tie things around them.'' In that way, ``the 
fish will just eat him up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Beckwith's attorney, Merrida Coxwell Jr., said that even if  
Beckwith is the person speaking on the tapes, the information can't 
be trusted because of Beckwith's failing health. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would be skeptical what he has said about involvement in  
something else,'' Coxwell said. ``I certainly don't know that I 
would run and drain a lake.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990708.0187 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 13:10:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dirty Scopes Sicken Lung Patients </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Pencil-thin scopes used to look inside patients'  
lungs sickened two people in New York state because the instruments 
were not properly disinfected, the government said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention said the  
instruments, called bronchoscopes, were contaminated with bacteria 
because they weren't connected properly to machines that flush them 
with disinfectant. 
</P>
<P>
	Bronchoscopes are used to diagnose respiratory diseases such as  
tuberculosis and lung cancer. The tubes, about 5 feet long, are 
inserted into a patient's lungs through the mouth. 
</P>
<P>
	The CDC investigated cases of 30 patients at three New York  
state hospitals whose lung fluids were contaminated by bacteria 
from bronchoscopes in 1996 and 1998. Two of the patients became ill 
with pneumonia-like symptoms, the CDC said. 
</P>
<P>
	A third patient tested positive for tuberculosis, but  
researchers couldn't determine if it was caused by a contaminated 
bronchoscope. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
