<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 4 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Clinton Goes to Los Angeles  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- President Clinton today visited the Los  
Angeles neighborhood of Watts, scarred by riots nearly 30 years 
apart. He wants private firms to help disadvantaged young people 
gain the skills they need for high-tech jobs. With Clinton was 
Magic Johnson, the former Los Angeles Lakers star who has 
revitalized South Central L.A. with multiplex movie theaters. 
Clinton also was to go to nearby Anaheim for a conference of the 
National Academy Foundation -- where chief executives are huddling 
to discuss ways to connect employers with disadvantaged youth. 

</P>
<P>
	UN Says Life in Kosovo Is Grim  
</P>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- The U.N. refugee agency gave a grim  
assessment today of life in Kosovo: contaminated water, wrecked 
health facilities and short supplies of vital foods. ``Hopes that 
the humanitarian situation may not be as serious as initially 
feared seem to be over-optimistic,'' said the UNHCR report, which 
surveyed 141 villages. 

</P>
<P>
	New Red Cross Leader Named  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Dr. Bernadine Healy was named today to head  
the American Red Cross, filling the position Elizabeth Dole quit to 
pursue presidential aspirations. Healy, a heart specialist, will be 
the first physician to head the 118-year-old organization. A former 
head of the National Institutes of Health, she is now dean of the 
Ohio State University College of Medicine and Public Health. 

</P>
<P>
	Irish Leader Urges IRA Pledge  
</P>
<P>
	BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) -- Ireland's prime minister  
appealed today for the outlawed Irish Republican Army to provide 
``a clear, unambiguous'' commitment to surrendering its weapons. 
Bertie Ahern said it is key to securing agreement on a new 
Protestant-Catholic government for Northern Ireland. Ulster 
Unionists are refusing to give the Sinn Fein party two seats in a 
12-member administration unless the IRA disarms. 

</P>
<P>
	Japan OKs Economic Plan  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The Cabinet approved a sweeping plan today to  
transform the way Japan does business -- loosening restraints on 
competition, reducing government influence, and gearing the 
capitalist system to serve consumers, not producers. The proposals, 
issued amid Japan's worst recession since World War II, reflect a 
new consensus among officials and normally intransigent bureaucrats 
that things must change, said Economic Planning Agency chief Taichi 
Sakaiya. 

</P>
<P>
	Biowarfare Test Is Canceled  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ALAMOS, N.M. (AP) -- Unable to ease public fears, Los Alamos  
National Laboratory canceled plans today to release a common strain 
of bacteria into the atmosphere to test new biowarfare detectors. 
Don Cobb, the lab's associate director for threat reduction, said 
the tests were ``provably safe.'' But he said he canceled them 
because ``the trust and confidence of our neighbors is essential.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Oakland Dock Workers Return  
</P>
<P>
	OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) -- Dock workers returned to their jobs today  
at the Port of Oakland, which was shut down for two days by a 
walkout during negotiations over a new contract for 10,000 West 
Coast longshoremen. The International Longshore and Warehouse Union 
local said talks will resume tomorrow in San Francisco with 
management's Pacific Maritime Association over a new three-year 
contract. 

</P>
<P>
	Strong Retail Sales Cited  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The nation's biggest retailers reported  
surprisingly strong sales in June as the robust U.S. economy and 
warm weather sent Americans on a buying bonanza. The Merrill Lynch 
retail index, the investment firm's barometer of sales performance 
at department stores and discount chains, was up 6.3 percent. The 
Labor Department said the number of Americans filing new claims for 
unemployment benefits fell by 6,000 last week to 294,000, the 
second consecutive drop. 

</P>
<P>
	Stock Prices Are Mixed  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mixed today as strength in Internet  
and computer shares helped the technology sector outperform the 
broader market. Just before the close, the Dow industrials were 
down 64.58 to 11,122.78. The Nasdaq Composite Index was up 22.13 to 
2,765.17. 

</P>
<P>
	NHL Rangers Get Theo Fleury  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Six-time NHL All-Star forward Theo Fleury signed  
today with the New York Rangers as an unrestricted free agent. 
Reportedly, the deal was for at least four years at $8-to-$10 
million per year. Fleury, 31, played for 11 years with Calgary 
before going to Colorado on Feb. 28. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by HOWARD SINER  

  	   	
