<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bob Hill To Become Fordham Coach </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Former NBA coach Bob Hill will be hired as men's  
basketball coach at Fordham, a source close to the university told 
the Associated Press on Thursday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Hill, who compiled a 257-212 record in parts of seven seasons  
with New York, Indiana and San Antonio, will replace the departed 
Nick Macarchuk, according to a source, who spoke on condition of 
anonymity. A news conference announcing Hill's hiring is likely to 
be scheduled early next week, the source added. Details of a 
contract weren't immediately available. 
</P>
<P>
	Macarchuk, who coached the Rams for 12 years, resigned to take  
the coaching job at Stony Brook, which is moving up to Division I 
as an independent starting next season. 
</P>
<P>
	Fordham was prepared to name Hofstra's Jay Wright as the coach  
on June 16, but Wright had a change of heart the night before. 
Siena's Paul Hewitt and Lafayette's Fran O'Hanlon were mentioned as 
candidates for the job. 
</P>
<P>
	Hill's last coaching job was with San Antonio. He was fired by  
general manager Gregg Popovich in 1996 after the team got off to a 
3-15 start. Popovich replaced Hill on the bench and last month 
completed San Antonio's surge to its first-ever NBA title. 
</P>
<P>
	Hill, who has also been an assistant at Bowling Green,  
Pittsburgh and Kansas, was recently mentioned as a candidate for 
the Cleveland and Orlando NBA jobs, both of which have since been 
filled. 
</P>
<P>
	Fordham moved to the Atlantic 10 Conference from the Patriot  
League in 1995 and has had little success, losing 80 of 108 games 
in four seasons. The Rams have not played in the NCAA tournament 
since 1992. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
