<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Republicans Seek Delay in Primaries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- A Republican National Committee panel  
searched Thursday for a way to goad states into pushing back their 
presidential primaries. 
</P>
<P>
	Traditionally the Iowa caucus and the New Hampshire primary have  
launched the nominating season. Other states have been scheduling 
their primaries earlier and earlier in an effort to have more say 
in who gets the party's nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm horrendously opposed to front-loading because a long  
process over many months is about the only way we have of assessing 
presidential candidates in this country,'' said RNC member Morton 
Blackwell of Virginia told the party's Rules Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	The RNC sought to address the issue in 1996 by instituting rules  
that award states more delegates if they push back their primary 
contests. ``This particular bundle of carrots has not been an 
efficient incentive,'' said John Ryder, an RNC member from 
Tennessee. 
</P>
<P>
	An impromptu survey by RNC Rules Committee Chairman Tom  
Sansonetti showed that only three states pushed back their primary 
dates since 1996 -- and 17 states moved them forward. Twenty-four 
states didn't change. 
</P>
<P>
	Blackwell proposed to do away with the 1996 rules and start  
fresh, but his effort was rejected. Tom Rath of New Hampshire said 
the incentives might have ``retarded some of the rush'' to hold 
earlier primaries. 
</P>
<P>
	Nicholson is putting together a separate advisory panel of  
senior Republicans to study the issue. The panel will issue 
findings by the end of the year, so suggestions can be considered 
during the RNC winter meeting in California next January. 
</P>
<P>
	Any changes to existing party rules would take effect with the  
2004 Republican primary. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
