<HEADLINE> MSNBC Cancels Hockenberry Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- MSNBC has canceled newsman John Hockenberry's  
nightly talk show after six months on the air, the second time the 
correspondent has lost a show on the network in two years. 
</P>
<P>
	Hockenberry announced on the air Wednesday that the next night's  
show would be his last. One of his final discussion topics, he told 
viewers, might be why cable TV ``sucks.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He did not immediately return a call to his office Thursday.  
</P>
<P>
	MSNBC spokesman Cory Shields confirmed the cancellation but had  
no further comment. MSNBC, which is struggling in prime time 
against Fox News Channel, is expected to announce a new schedule 
soon. 
</P>
<P>
	It is expected to include a new hour-long biography series  
anchored by Matt Lauer, ``Headliners and Legends.'' CNBC's 
``Hardball,'' with Chris Matthews as host, may also soon shift to 
MSNBC as CNBC prepares to expand its financial news coverage. 
</P>
<P>
	Hockenberry will return to ``Dateline NBC,'' where he is a  
reporter. His weekend newsmagazine, ``Edgewise,'' was canceled by 
MSNBC two years ago. 
  	   	
</P>
