<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ford Offer Swells to $30 Million </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) -- The amount Ford Motor Co. has agreed to  
pay to settle potential lawsuits brought by relatives of the six 
people killed and 14 injured in a February explosion has swelled to 
$30 million, attorneys said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford had said last month that it planned to pay $20 million.  
</P>
<P>
	In a two-page memorandum obtained by The Detroit News, Ford said  
it will offer each of the 20 families a $1-million lump sum 
payment. The company also will pay the salaries, benefits and 
medical insurance for the injured workers, and the families of the 
six deceased workers, until they are or would have been 65. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford also will provide trust funds for the minor children of the  
workers killed and injured. The trust funds are valued at about 
$100,000 each, the memorandum said. 
</P>
<P>
	Each family also will receive a separate $25,000 payment that  
can be used for any purpose, including to pay for a memorial or to 
donate to charity. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford spokesman John Spelich declined to elaborate on Ford's  
written offers. 
</P>
<P>
	``Out of respect for the privacy of the families, we will not  
discuss this matter further publicly,'' Spelich told the News for a 
report Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford will submit a more complete, legally binding settlement  
offer in the next two weeks, and officials on both sides hope to 
have settlements signed and completed by the end of the month or 
early August. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the agreement, Ford would pay a minimum of $11.7 million  
in estimated salaries and benefits for the employees over the next 
20 years, while the state would pay more than $5 million in workers 
compensation insurance benefits. 
</P>
<P>
	The offer would require the families to waive all claims against  
Ford, Rouge Steel and any other company. 
</P>
<P>
	``The families have the confidential offers from Ford and I  
continue to recommend that they accept what is a very generous 
offer from Ford,'' David Christensen, an attorney for one of the 
families, said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Six workers were killed and 14 seriously injured when a  
six-story boiler exploded without warning at the powerhouse that 
provided electricity for the 1,100-acre complex in Dearborn. The 
complex is home to six Ford plants and Rouge Steel, which employ a 
total of 10,000 workers there. 
</P>
<P>
	To date, three employees have filed suits in Wayne Circuit Court  
against Rouge Steel, but not against Ford. The three are the family 
of Ken Anderson, 44 of Wyandotte, who died as a result of injuries 
sustained in the accident; Patrick Pilzninski, 46, of Westland; and 
Ralph Irvin, 53, of Detroit. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
