<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Officers in Cuban Episode Moved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- Eight Coast Guard officers who tried to stop six  
Cuban refugees from swimming to shore last week have been removed 
from law enforcement duty. 
</P>
<P>
	The officers currently are working on search-and-rescue missions  
or environmental duties, spokesman Lt. Ron LeBrec said Thursday. 
They will not return to law enforcement until an internal 
investigation is completed, probably within two weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	Televised reports showed the Coast Guard blasting the refugees  
with a hose as they stood in their 14-foot rowboat about 150 yards 
from shore June 29. The agency swarmed them as they jumped 
overboard and swam toward land. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the swimmers was doused with pepper spray. Two reached  
the beach and four were plucked from the water and detained aboard 
a Coast Guard cutter. 
</P>
<P>
	Miami's Cuban community protested the Coast Guard's actions,  
blocking off the only road connecting Miami Beach's trendy South 
Beach and downtown Miami, and a major highway west of the city. 
</P>
<P>
	Under U.S. policy, foreigners who reach U.S. shores are allowed  
to seek asylum, but those intercepted at sea are returned to their 
homeland or another country. 
</P>
<P>
	The six were taken to an Immigration and Naturalization Service  
detention center for processing and released the next day. 
</P>
<P>
	``We in the Coast Guard feel for the plight of these illegal  
migrants,'' said Admiral Thad Allen, commander of the Coast Guard 
district which includes South Florida. ``However, the Coast Guard 
is mandated to enforce U.S. laws.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The admiral said he will review the use of hoses against the  
refugees, but is not willing to ban the practice because of its 
effectiveness. 
</P>
<P>
	Coast Guard statistics show 940 Cuban refugees have been  
detained at sea and returned to their homeland so far this year. 
That is almost as many as the 1,047 interdictions for all of 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
