<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 12:50:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House GOP Wants Education Tax Cuts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Continuing a weeklong trickle of  
announcements, House Republicans said Thursday that tax breaks to 
help pay for private education and public school construction will 
be part of their tax cut bill. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest proposal from Rep. Bill Archer, chairman of the House  
Ways and Means Committee, sets the GOP on a collision course with 
President Clinton, who vetoed a bill with similar private school 
benefits last year. 
</P>
<P>
	But Archer, R-Texas, said the measure -- a priority for  
Republican conservatives -- would ``lighten the education tax bite'' 
and give parents ``more choices as they design the best education 
for their children.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The plan, a version of which is already moving in the Senate,  
would allow private universities for the first time to offer 
prepaid tuition programs like those currently used by 19 states for 
public universities. It would also make both types of plans 
completely tax-exempt instead of deferring taxes, as current law 
permits. 
</P>
<P>
	Archer also wants to expand IRA-like savings accounts for  
education so that they apply to the costs of public or private 
elementary and secondary schools, not just higher education. The 
maximum annual amount that could be contributed would rise from 
$500 to $2,000. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, the proposal would change rules for revenue bonds  
so that state and local governments could more easily raise money 
for public school construction projects. 
</P>
<P>
	All told, the three proposals would cost about $8 billion over  
10 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats said the private school benefits would divert too much  
federal money away from public schools and would do less than a 
Clinton alternative to help needy public schools modernize or 
replace dilapidated buildings. 
</P>
<P>
	``While they purport to provide assistance to millions of  
families, the benefit is a pittance to all but the very wealthy,'' 
said Rep. Charles Rangel of New York, top Democrat on the Ways and 
Means Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Archer, whose committee initiates all tax legislation in  
Congress, has taken advantage of the Capitol Hill news lull during 
the weeklong Independence Day recess to release several parts of a 
tax relief bill expected to total about $850 billion over 10 years 
using projected budget surpluses. 
</P>
<P>
	Previous announcements sketched out plans to cut top capital  
gains rates from 20 percent to 15 percent and create new tax breaks 
for people who care for an elderly relative at home. 
</P>
<P>
	Still to come are some of the most costly pieces of the plan,  
including a broad reduction in income taxes, cuts in inheritance 
taxes and elimination of the ``marriage penalty'' in which millions 
of two-earner couples pay more tax than if they were single. 
</P>
<P>
	Aides say Archer is considering three alternatives for the cut  
in income taxes: adjusting one or more brackets so that more income 
is taxed at lower rates, an across-the-board rate reduction that 
would gradually reach 10 percent over a decade and a 
``bottom-line'' cut in which taxpayers could take a certain 
percentage off their taxes on Internal Revenue Service forms. 
</P>
<P>
	The Ways and Means Committee plans to begin moving its tax  
package next week. Its greatest significance may be as a Republican 
political statement, since Clinton is unlikely to sign it into law 
and wants some of the money used for Medicare and increased 
spending. It also faces uncertainty in the Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. William Roth, chairman of the Finance Committee, also  
favors a broad tax cut in addition to several more specific 
reductions, said spokeswoman Ginny Flynn. Roth, R-Del., is 
considering an adjustment to the lowest 15 percent tax bracket so 
that people pay lower rates on more of their earnings. 
</P>
<P>
	But there are likely to be significant differences between Roth  
and Archer on the tax bill, starting with the total. 
</P>
<P>
	Roth is planning for a bill costing $792 billion over 10 years  
and wants some of projected budget surpluses specifically set aside 
for Medicare reform. Archer's bill is expected to reach $850 
billion and is less definite about Medicare. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, Roth is less likely to include a cut in capital  
gains taxes and more likely to advance major proposals to expand 
private retirement savings. His name, after all, is now in 
Webster's dictionary because of the popular Roth IRA. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990708.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 03:40:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Two Rookies Favored in Senior Open  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WEST DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- Allen Doyle and Bruce Fleisher were  
walking up to the 18th hole on the final day of the Senior Tour 
qualifying school when Fleisher breathed a sign of relief. 
</P>
<P>
	It had been a tough week and it was almost over. Doyle, though,  
saw it differently. 
</P>
<P>
	``I said to him, `You know, there are going to be two or three  
guys out of this tour school that are going to win over a million 
dollars and they are going to have real good years.' He said, `Why 
shouldn't that be us?''' 
</P>
<P>
	Less than a year later, Fleisher and Doyle rank 1-2 on the  
Senior Tour money list and, yes, each has made more than $1 
million. Today, they began play in the U.S. Senior Open as two of 
the favorites. 
</P>
<P>
	``He has asked me, did I expect to have done what I did?'' Doyle  
said. ``And you know, I said, `Not really.' And he pretty much 
acknowledged that he really hadn't expected to do quite as well as 
he had done.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Neither received much professional acclaim before this year.  
</P>
<P>
	Doyle, whose unorthodox swing resembles a slap shot in hockey,  
spent most of his career as an amateur before becoming, at the age 
of 47, the oldest rookie ever on the PGA Tour. 
</P>
<P>
	Fleisher had a nondescript career as a touring pro and even  
dropped off the tour for a few years in the 1980s to work as a club 
pro so he could make ends meet. 
</P>
<P>
	But they've found new life on the Senior Tour, where younger is  
definitely better. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm finally starting to have some fun this year,'' said  
Fleisher, who became eligible for the Senior Tour when he turned 50 
last October. 
</P>
<P>
	Defending champion Hale Irwin is starting to have some fun again  
after struggling early in the year. He entered the Open with 
victories in three of his last five tournaments, including a 
seven-stroke win in the Senior Players Championship at the TPC of 
Michigan two weeks ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Also in 156-man field were Larry Nelson, No. 3 on the money  
list; Vicente Fernandez, last year's runner-up; Graham Marsh, 
winner of The Tradition this year; and Christy O'Connor, coming off 
a victory in the State Farm Classic. 
</P>
<P>
	The tournament is being played at Des Moines Golf and Country  
Club, a 6,888-yard, par-72 layout that never before had been the 
site of a major tournament. With its undulating greens, the course 
puts a premium on approach shots and putting. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's going to be an exciting tournament,'' Fleisher  
said. ``Hopefully, no one will get so hot like Irwin did a couple 
of weeks ago and blow everybody away. He may do it again. Who 
knows? 
</P>
<P>
	``But I don't think a low number is going to be the answer this  
week,'' he said. ``I think the greens are too difficult. I don't 
know if anyone knows the greens that well to really excel at this 
time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Irwin said a golfer will have to master those greens to win.  
</P>
<P>
	``It is going to be a significant test for all of us,'' he said.  
``I think ... a good majority of the test will come around the 
greens -- not terribly unlike the U.S. Open this year where a good 
bit of the test was around the greens. I think we will see much the 
same here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Handling the course also will require patience, Doyle said. With  
72 holes to play, he said there's no reason to get upset over one 
or two mistakes. 
</P>
<P>
	``You have to handle it properly and realize there is a long way  
to go,'' he said. ``It's not so much the guy who makes the most 
birdies that is going to win, but the guy who makes the fewest 
bogeys.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As for that sour-looking swing, Doyle said he knows it offends  
the purists, but it works for him. 
</P>
<P>
	``As a kid, the club pro used to tell me, `If you can drive it  
pretty good and you've got a pretty good short game, you will be 
able to score,''' Doyle said. ```So don't ever pay attention to 
anybody that can't beat you.' 
</P>
<P>
	``I always have kept that to heart.''  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
