<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Baker Hughes Accused of Trade Theft </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- A Mexican firm is suing Baker Hughes for $400  
million, accusing the Houston-based energy supply company of 
stealing trade secrets after backing out of an acquisition 
agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	Ambar Mexicana, an oil drilling service based in Ciudad del  
Carmen, Mexico, claims Baker Hughes was trying to buy Ambar so it 
could enter the Mexican market. 
</P>
<P>
	Ambar's suit, filed in federal court in Houston, says Baker  
Hughes backed out of the deal and purchased a Mexican competitor of 
Ambar, then used Ambar's trade secrets to unfairly compete against 
it. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't comment on pending litigation,'' said Gary Flaharty,  
Baker Hughes' director of investor relations. 
</P>
<P>
	The suit, filed by attorney Herbert Lackshin of Houston, seeks  
$100 million in compensatory damages and $300 million in punitive 
damages. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1998, during acquisition talks, Baker Hughes ``continued to  
reassure Ambar of its intent to acquire Ambar's business'' and 
instructed Ambar not to bid new contracts in Ambar's name so the 
contracts could be bid and awarded jointly to Baker Hughes and 
Ambar, the suit says. 
</P>
<P>
	Unknown to Ambar at the time, Baker Hughes had purchased one of  
Ambar's competitors, Zapata International. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ambar has reason to believe that (Baker Hughes), through  
Zapata, is using Ambar's prices, business plan, marketing 
information, customer information, and all of Ambar's proprietary 
business information and trade secrets to unfairly compete with 
Ambar,'' the suit said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
