<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cycling Union: Drug Report Is Untrue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- The International Cycling Union denied today a  
published report that a Tour de France cyclist tested positive for 
a banned drug. 
</P>
<P>
	The French sports daily L'Equipe reported that one of four  
riders tested were found to have taken corticosteroids after 
Saturday's prologue. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was not one positive case,'' UCI spokesman Enrico  
Carpani told The Associated Press. 
</P>
<P>
	Corticosteroids, anti-inflammatory and painkilling drugs which  
are not classed as steroids, are banned unless prescribed by 
doctors for specific medical conditions such as asthma and 
rhinitis. 
</P>
<P>
	Four cyclists were tested after Saturday's prologue, including  
Lance Armstrong as winner of the stage. 
</P>
<P>
	Denmark's Bo Hamburger, Spain's Manuel Beltran and Colombia's  
Joaquim Castelblanco were the others tested, L'Equipe said. 
</P>
<P>
	The official who carried out the test, Jacques de Ceaurriz,  
director of France's national laboratory for testing and drugs, 
refused to confirm the report. 
</P>
<P>
	He said it was up to the UCI to act on the matter.  
</P>
<P>
	``The UCI manages the files,'' Ceaurriz said.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
