<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> EEOC: Toyota Unit Exclusionary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- By filling positions mainly through union  
and personal referrals, a unit of Toyota Motor Sales U.S.A. Inc. at 
Port Newark illegally excluded blacks and women from its work 
force, the U.S. Equal Employment Opportunity Commission charged 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``These policies and practices have resulted in an applicant  
pool which does not reflect labor market availability for females 
and blacks,'' the EEOC said in a federal civil rights lawsuit 
against Toyota Logistics Services Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	The practices violate Title VII, the agency said, asserting the  
law bars hiring discrimination including how an employer announces 
vacancies. 
</P>
<P>
	In a statement, the EEOC said the practices, while  
``superficially neutral,'' made it hard for blacks and women to 
learn of openings for drivers and auto accessories installers. 
</P>
<P>
	``White males as a group were the ones able to get knowledge of  
the company's jobs from the union or present employees who are 
generally white males themselves,'' the agency said. 
</P>
<P>
	When women did learn of openings, Toyota Logistics did not hire  
them, the EEOC lawsuit claimed, citing the case of Sandra Burrows, 
a qualified black woman who put in an application in August 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite being told she would be called when Toyota Logistics was  
hiring, she was never called, although the company continued to 
hire men into those positions, the lawsuit said. 
</P>
<P>
	Burrows, 39, learned of the openings -- which carry union wages  
and benefits -- from her husband, who works for another employer at 
Port Newark, said a person familiar with the case who requested 
anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	Toyota spokeswoman Diana DeJoseph said the company had no  
comment on the lawsuit. 
</P>
<P>
	The Port Newark operation employs about 175 workers and 12  
managers, who handle about 130,000 vehicles arriving from Japan and 
U.S. plants before sending them to dealers in the Northeast and New 
England, DeJoseph said from the company's U.S. headquarters in 
Torrance, Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	The EEOC is seeking monetary damages of up to $300,000 for every  
victim. It has no estimate yet on how many people it believes were 
discriminated against. 
</P>
<P>
	It also seeks a judge's order barring Toyota Logistics from  
engaging in biased hiring practices. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
