<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Filings Detail Execs' Compensation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Charles K. ``Chad'' Gifford, head of BankBoston,  
will receive a stock compensation plan worth millions of dollars 
following the company's proposed acquisition by Fleet Financial 
Group, Inc., according to documents filed Thursday with the 
Securities and Exchange Commission. 
</P>
<P>
	Gifford, who will serve as president of the combined bank, will  
receive 300,000 shares of restricted stock following culmination of 
the deal, and he'll have options to purchase 300,000 more, 
according to the documents filed by Fleet. 
</P>
<P>
	The companies have proposed a maximum offering price per share  
of $43.35, meaning each bloc of shares would be worth about $13 
million. 
</P>
<P>
	Executive compensation specialists said that's in line with the  
going rate. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is within the perspective of executive compensation. It's  
not particularly startling, although all executive compensation is 
startling,'' said Judith Fischer, managing director of Executive 
Compensation Advisory Services of Springfield, Va., a firm that 
helps companies come up with executive payment plans. 
</P>
<P>
	The combined bank, to be named Fleet Boston, would initially be  
headed by Murray. After two years, Murray, 59, would step down as 
chief executive but stay on as chairman, succeeded as CEO by 
Gifford, 56. The following year, Gifford would also take over as 
chairman. 
</P>
<P>
	The documents, which will be distributed to shareholders of both  
companies, said Gifford, will receive a base salary of at least 
equal to that of Fleet CEO Terrence Murray, and a bonus of not less 
than 90 percent of Murray's. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, Murray had a base salary of $992,200, and he received  
a $3.4 million bonus. He also has a multimillion dollar long-term 
stock compensation plan. 
</P>
<P>
	Gifford earned $869,231 in base salary last year, and a $1.9  
million bonus. And BankBoston's board of directors raised his 
salary to $900,000 for 1999, said company spokeswoman Marjorie 
Arons-Barron. 
</P>
<P>
	He is also guaranteed a retirement package of at least $1.25  
million a year, according to the filing. 
</P>
<P>
	Stockholders for both companies will meet Aug. 11 to discuss the  
proposed $16 billion merger. If they approve it, the resulting 
company would be the nation's eighth-largest bank. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal must also be approved by regulators.  



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
