<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jesse Jackson Tours With Clinton </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PINE RIDGE, S.D. (AP) -- It was supposed to be President  
Clinton's moment. After all, he was the first U.S. president to 
visit an American Indian reservation in more than 60 years. 
</P>
<P>
	But some in the audience began chanting for Jesse Jackson, who  
hadn't uttered a word and was struggling to stay in Clinton's 
shadow. 
</P>
<P>
	``Speak, Jesse, Speak!'' a few people called. ``Run, Jesse,  
Run!'' others said. 
</P>
<P>
	This is how it's been since Clinton began his national poverty  
tour in Appalachia three days ago with Jackson at his side. Even 
Clinton gave a nod to Jackson for helping shape his message of 
economic empowerment. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to thank my good friend Jesse Jackson for never letting  
us forget our common obligations,'' Clinton said Wednesday. Jackson 
did not address the crowd. 
</P>
<P>
	At times, their pairing made for interesting political theater.  
Clinton and Jackson may not have literally been competing with each 
other, but their reputations as men of the people certainly were. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not more popular than he is,'' Jackson said as he awaited  
Clinton on the tarmac at South Dakota's Ellsworth Air Force Base. 
``Both of us are well known, but he is the president.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wednesday evening in Arizona, Clinton settled at the head of a  
U-shaped table inside a tortilla factory in Phoenix. There was no 
place at the table for Jackson. He sat with four others on a row of 
chairs perpendicular to the president. 
</P>
<P>
	It was Jackson who invited Clinton to address his Wall Street  
Project, which proposed among other things the notion of treating 
inner cities like foreign markets when it comes to trade and 
investment. 
</P>
<P>
	Since January, Jackson has worked with Clinton's advisers on  
folding his program into Clinton's economic agenda -- and Jackson's 
feelings were a bit hurt in May when Clinton hauled a group of 
corporate executives to Atlanta without inviting him. At the time, 
Jackson was still on the outs with White House officials because of 
his trip to Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	One of Clinton's economic advisers, speaking Wednesday on  
condition of anonymity, said Jackson ``never tried to micromanage'' 
what the president did with his ideas. ``Any good idea has many 
fathers, but he's certainly been an inspiration for many of our 
efforts,'' the official said. 
</P>
<P>
	Monday night in Memphis, Clinton and Jackson went to the civil  
rights museum in the Lorraine Motel, where Martin Luther King Jr. 
was assassinated in 1968. After their tour, Jackson grabbed a cell 
phone and called the widow of Ricky Byrdsong, the former 
Northwestern University basketball coach shot to death last week by 
a white supremacist. 
</P>
<P>
	When Jackson finished the conversation, he handed the phone to  
Clinton so he could chat with the slain man's widow. 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson worked the masses alongside Clinton at Ellsworth. On the  
far edge of the crowd, a woman held up a sign that read, ``Jesse 
Rules.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She wanted to thank Jackson for bringing the three American  
soldiers back from Yugoslavia unharmed. Jackson kissed her, 
autographed the sign and posed for a picture with her and Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson and Clinton also were side by side with Oglala Lakota  
Sioux on a courtyard at the reservation's high school. As Clinton 
finished shaking hands, Jackson was tossing a giggling Aaron Black 
Bull, 2, into the air. He carried Aaron over to Clinton, who kissed 
the boy on the cheek. 
</P>
<P>
	Both men turned to leave -- until a woman called, ``Jesse, we  
want to shake your hand.'' Jackson went back to the crowd and so 
did Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	A blue baseball cap labeled ``Water is Life'' -- which Clinton  
took off and replaced with a black one that read ``Native 
American'' -- somehow found its way onto Jackson's head. 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson attributed the attention he has gotten to the fact that  
he has been out there for at least a year advocating the economic 
investment that Clinton now is touting. Plus, he said, people 
remember when he drummed up votes for Clinton in places like Pine 
Ridge in 1992 and 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have a team,'' Jackson said. He likened himself and Clinton  
to Michael Jordan and Scottie Pippen, who guided the Chicago Bulls 
to six NBA championships. 
</P>
<P>
	``He does have a chemistry, an undeniable chemistry, with the  
people,'' Jackson said of Clinton. ``He's touching a live nerve 
when he's touching the needs of working poor people and the middle 
class at the same time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton left Pine Ridge in his usual limousine. Jackson climbed  
into a van a few vehicles back in the motorcade. The van was called 
``Special 1.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
