<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Senior Open Notebook  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WEST DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- Loran Schiltz and his staff of  
volunteers in the merchandise tent are busy, busy, busy. 
</P>
<P>
	With wave after wave of spectators spilling into the Des Moines  
Golf and Country Club all week, the workers who sell caps, polo 
shirts, coffee mugs and other souvenirs can barely keep the shelves 
stocked. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's moving very, very fast,'' said Schiltz, a tournament  
volunteer who shares the responsibility of running the tent. ``Some 
of the inventory, we can be saved every morning by UPS. Some we 
can't reorder.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As hundreds of people milled through the massive tent Thursday,  
workers carried box after box of merchandise onto the floor and 
moved it to the shelves. Schiltz said volunteers from other 
tournament areas, such as ticketing, were brought over to help meet 
the demand. 
</P>
<P>
	He declined to disclose sales but characterized them as  
``booming.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Not much comes cheap. There are several baseball hats but all  
cost $26. Golf shirts sell for $65 or $70, a fanny pack is $10, an 
umbrella is $32 while a souvenir ball marker and greens-repair tool 
goes for $20. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nice products, a little pricey,'' said one shopper, Tim Davlin  
of Omaha, Neb. ``I'll probably walk around the hats three times, 
complaining the whole time about the prices. Then I'll buy one.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Davlin has plenty of other T-shirts from vacations and sports  
events, all gathering dust in the closet at home. He still wanted 
something else for the collection. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity,'' he said. ``Some of  
these golfers you saw on TV as a kid. We might not ever get another 
event like this in our area.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The merchandise tent also afforded a relatively easy ticket to  
the tournament for Richard and Cheryl Hood of Runnells, Iowa. 
</P>
<P>
	Each paid $105 to volunteer. In return, they got a tournament  
parking pass and the option of working four-hour shifts at the cash 
registers or being assigned to the security detail. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't want to watch a parking lot all day,'' Richard Hood  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Added Cheryl Hood: ``We've really enjoyed it. We're in the  
hustle and bustle, where the action is.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *FUNNY PUTTER:* Bruce Summerhays found himself in the longer  
grass off the fringe when his approach on the par-4 13th stayed up 
in the wind and stopped below the hole. 
</P>
<P>
	Then, from 40 feet, he used a 4-wood to make a birdie putt.  
</P>
<P>
	``All you have to do, you putt the ball,'' he said. ``The wood  
just takes it right out of there and rolls it up to the hole.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Summerhays said he'll use his pitching wedge if the grass is  
standing up and the ball is higher. If the ball is more than three 
feet off the fringe, the 4-wood is not advised. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is an easy way to hit those little shots when it's down in  
the grass right near the green,'' Summerhays said. ``You can't use 
it too far off because it's got to roll through stuff.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *SAD STORIES:* Tickets to the Senior Open are a hot commodity in  
Des Moines. As a result, ticket manager Cory Konrad has heard some 
pretty silly stories from fans who pretended to be panicked. 
</P>
<P>
	One woman claimed her house was burglarized. The only missing  
items were two tickets for Wednesday's practice round. Another tale 
came from a man and woman who went out to dinner but left their 
tickets on the table. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know why people would take their Senior Open tickets  
to dinner,'' Konrad said. ``But a dog hasn't eaten a ticket yet and 
a kid hasn't flushed them down the toilet.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *MEDICAL ALERT:* Bug bites, headaches, blisters, nausea and  
people who complained about the heat are the most common 
discomforts treated by volunteers in the medical tent. 
</P>
<P>
	The temperature dropped Thursday into the low 80s after reaching  
the 90s earlier in the week, and a north wind to 10 mph offered 
some mild relief. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Rick Bratkiewicz said one man was treated for a stroke but  
it was unrelated to the weather. Otherwise, he said all the medical 
complaints during the tournament's first round were minor. 
</P>
<P>
	By late afternoon, 44 people had been treated at one site, 22 at  
another and 24 at a third. Not bad, considering attendance was 
35,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Paramedics from West Des Moines staffed the medical facilities,  
although several volunteer doctors and nurses were available. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
