<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Computer Programmer on Trial in Ohio </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DAYTON, Ohio (AP) -- A Chinese computer programmer was found  
guilty Thursday of obtaining passwords to an Air Force computer 
that tracks the combat readiness of aircraft and weapons. 
</P>
<P>
	A jury deliberated for less than an hour before convicting  
Steven Liu, 25, of two counts of intentionally accessing a computer 
without authorization. He faces up to two years in prison. 
</P>
<P>
	Liu, a Chinese national who was at the time working for a U.S.  
military contractor in Dayton, twice downloaded passwords from the 
computer database near Wright-Patterson Air Force Base in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	However, there was no evidence he used them to get into the  
system, the data of which is not classified. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors said Liu told investigators he downloaded the file  
first out of curiosity and then to ``own'' the system. 
</P>
<P>
	The defense claimed Liu downloaded the passwords in what  
resembled a computer game, with the password file being the prize 
that proved a person had access to the system if they wished. 
</P>
<P>
	Liu pleaded guilty to the charges in December 1997 but then  
withdrew the plea and opted for a trial. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
