<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Charges Dropped in Bahamas Crash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT STEWART, Ga. (AP) -- An Army judge dismissed conspiracy and  
dereliction of duty charges on Thursday against a helicopter 
mechanic seriously injured in a helicopter crash in the Bahamas 
that left two women dead. 
</P>
<P>
	Sgt. William Westgate cried when Army judge, Col. Kenneth  
Pangburn, dismissed the allegations against him. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's been a long, hard year,'' Westgate said.  
</P>
<P>
	Chief Warrant Officer Daniel Riddell and Chief Warrant Officer  
David Guido were with Westgate on a drug-interdiction mission in 
the Bahamas at the time of the crash. The Black Hawk went down on 
Grand Exuma Island on July 6, 1998, killing Riddell's wife, 
Rebecca, and Guido's wife, Pam. 
</P>
<P>
	Army rules prohibit spouses from boarding military helicopters  
without prior approval from a general officer. The defense claimed 
Westgate was not aware the rule. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, Pangburn found Riddell guilty of wrongfully  
appropriating a military aircraft and violating a lawful general 
regulation and sentenced him to a reprimand. 
</P>
<P>
	Guido was convicted in June of conspiracy, wrongful  
appropriation of an aircraft and violation of a lawful general 
regulation. He was sentenced to a reprimand as well. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
