<DOCNO> APW19990708.0230 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 08:00:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Summers: U.S. Economy on Course </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The U.S. economy is on a course to allow  
workers wage increases that exceed inflation, Treasury Secretary 
Lawrence Summers said today. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel good about where the economy is,'' Summers said in his  
seventh day on the job. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we can keep our fundamentals strong and continue the  
terrific productivity improvement, I think we have got room to give 
people wage increases that run ahead of price increases and 
represent really higher standards of living,'' Summers said on 
NBC's ``Today.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The former Harvard economist said the right course for the  
economy was set during the tenure of his predecessor at the 
Treasury Department, Robert Rubin. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our challenge is to carry on,'' Summers said. ``I think we are  
going to be able to do that under President Clinton's leadership, 
to keep paying down that federal debt, to put in place a framework 
for the beginning of the next century, when, I think, our country 
is going to be in a much, much stronger economic position than 
anyone thought likely a few years ago.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Summers said the nation can't become overconfident, and markets  
must be opened and exports promoted. His final concern: ``We have 
got to work as the president is this week on America's new markets, 
the less fortunate parts of our country, to make sure we take 
advantage of what is a terrific and very special opportunity for 
our economy to include all Americans.'' 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
