<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Posse, Sheriff Split Company </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- The county apparently wasn't big enough for  
the two of them -- the sheriff and his posse. 
</P>
<P>
	It didn't involve a showdown at high noon, just a court decree  
filed Wednesday in the Court of Common Pleas. Sheriff Jim Wright 
and what had been known for more than a decade as the Bedford 
County Sheriff's Posse have officially parted ways. 
</P>
<P>
	The group said it will purge the sheriff's name from its  
organization, but they don't need Wright's permission to do the 
public good in and around Bedford, about 80 miles southeast of 
Pittsburgh. 
</P>
<P>
	``He thought he was responsible for us, and he's not,'' said  
Lynford Yokum, vice president of the newly named Bedford County 
Posse. ``He doesn't know what volunteerism stands for.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The posse was formed more than a decade ago to aid then-Sheriff  
Max Norris with searches, rescues and other duties. It has also 
patrolled the county fair and staked out a mall to discourage 
looting during a flood a few years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	All of it was free-of-charge to the county and the sheriff.  
</P>
<P>
	But this spring, Wright told posse members to stop operating  
under the name of his office. He asked them to get rid of the 
badges and uniform patches they used proclaiming themselves part of 
the sheriff's posse. 
</P>
<P>
	Wright, who took office last year, said his concern was  
liability -- he couldn't have a group he didn't control working 
under his office's name. 
</P>
<P>
	Wright said he won't interfere with the group's lawful  
activities. 
</P>
<P>
	``As long as I'm not liable for what they do, I don't really  
care,'' Wright said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Although Yokum acknowledged his group doesn't have the same  
liberties as police, he said volunteerism laws allow the posse to 
provide civic assistance for those who ask for assistance. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990708.0232 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 17:30:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> World Cup Notebook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLAREMONT, Calif. (AP) -- It was the final chance for fans to pay  
tribute to the U.S. Women's World Cup team, and they did it the way 
they might treat a rock star. 
</P>
<P>
	A crowd estimated by police at more than 2,000 came to  
Pomona-Pitzer College on Thursday to glimpse America's newest 
sports phenoms. That was a far cry from the 50 or so who were on 
hand on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The team bus needed a motorcycle escort into the parking lot,  
and the players were protected by members of the Claremont Police 
Department as they walked onto the field. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a blast for us,'' Shannon MacMillan said. ``They were  
cheering and chanting our names the whole time. When the bus pulled 
up, they ran alongside, and when it moved up some more, they ran up 
some more. We had to have the policemen riding motorcycles by us 
just to get us to the field. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's great to see them share the enthusiasm.''  
</P>
<P>
	While the majority of the crowd was comprised of young girls,  
many wearing Mia Hamm No. 9 jerseys and most of them seeking 
autographs, there was a fair number of adults present. That 
impressed Briana Scurry. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can't tell me the little girls are not dragging their  
parents here and dragging them to the games,'' she said. ``The 
parents are seeing how soccer has taken off and they have done well 
in getting the kids out to the games. They feel their daughters 
should see high-quality soccer and they are seeing it in the World 
Cup.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Unfortunately, few of the fans were able to get autographs as  
officials escorted players out a back way to their bus. The Chinese 
team already was on the field and an organizing committee official 
said they were annoyed that their practice was delayed. 
</P>
<P>
	Before an interview session, however, Brandi Chastain sneaked  
away to sign a few soccer balls and shirts. 
</P>
<P>
	Kristine Lilly, playing in her third World Cup, opened her eyes  
wide as she surveyed the size of the crowd. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are more people here at practice than at our first games  
in the '80s,'' she said. ``That tells you how much interest there 
is.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *MOTORCYCLE BRIGADE:* Five officers from the Claremont Police  
Department were on duty for Thursday's practice at Pomona-Pitzer 
College. They surrounded the players as they approached the field 
before the workout, then provided security on the sideline. 
</P>
<P>
	``We never had to do anything like this before,'' Lt. Gary  
Jenkins said. ``A local newspaper reported when and where practice 
was, and you see what happened.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, Jenkins brought his three children to the school  
and his 10-year-old daughter managed to get some autographs. He 
said his children are soccer players and look up to the U.S. 
players. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a real positive thing to see people looking to sports  
figures like these women as role models,'' he said. ``They've taken 
that role seriously and done a great job.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At the end of practice, the players sat on the motorcycles and  
took pictures with the police. Defender Christie Pearce even took a 
short ride on one of the bikes. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *YOUNG AT HEART:* Not all the 2,000 or so soccer fans for the  
U.S. practice were young girls. 
</P>
<P>
	Sitting on rickety bleachers at one end of the field was a  
gray-haired man with a very familiar face. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm 87,'' Karl Malden said, a certain amount of pride in his  
voice. 
</P>
<P>
	The movie and television actor laughed about the bandwagon  
rolling for the American team. ``Of course, I followed everyone 
else,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	His granddaughter, Emily Doerner, plays soccer on the same  
Pomona-Pitzer College field where the Americans were practicing. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've been to some of her games,'' he said. ``Just like a lot  
of these young girls, her father started her playing when she was 
about 6, and she's kept going. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is great.''  
</P>
<P>
                            	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *ANOTHER OCTOGENARIAN:* Dorothy Sherrard has been a soccer fan  
for most of her life, and that's quite a few years. 
</P>
<P>
	``I used to play intramural soccer at the University of Illinois  
back in the 1930s. I loved to run and I loved to play soccer,'' 
said Sherrard, 86, who was watching the American women practice 
their free kicks. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a wonderful sport. I went to the Rose Bowl for the  
(men's) World Cup in 1994. I took my son and had to explain the 
game to him,'' Sherrard said, chuckling. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
