<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hate Groups, Crimes Said Rare in US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	For decades, hate groups have remained a tiny, if lethal, slice  
of America, proselytizing among the mostly young male misfits 
attracted to their messages. 
</P>
<P>
	Before his shooting spree in the Midwest, Benjamin Smith worked  
his neighborhoods, spreading hate-filled pamphlets and putting up 
racist posters. 
</P>
<P>
	His rampage remains a rarity and doesn't reveal a new degree of  
danger, experts say. But the means of advertising hate has changed, 
and the new brochure is the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	``It used to be, in order to attract a kid before, somebody  
would have to mail stuff to them, or go to their neighborhood,'' 
said Gail Gans, director of the Civil Rights Information Center at 
the Anti-Defamation League in New York. ``Now a kid can sit at the 
computer and type in `Nazi.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Though new Web sites may give an impression of growing  
membership in hate groups, observers say that's only a reflection 
of a new medium. 
</P>
<P>
	Estimates of self-proclaimed hate groups with Web sites range  
from 250 to 400. 
</P>
<P>
	At the Simon Wiesenthal Center in Los Angeles, where monitors  
follow links from hate group's Web sites, some 2,000 sites surfaced 
as ``problematic.'' These, for example, offered instructions in 
bomb-making or rock music espousing hatred or youth clubs extolling 
the Ku Klux Klan. 
</P>
<P>
	``(Using the Internet) makes perfect sense for all the reasons  
that business, educational institutions, the media are embracing 
the World Wide Web,'' said Rabbi Abraham Cooper, associate dean of 
the center. ``It's the most incredible medium to mass market and 
advertise.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Though Cooper found no evidence of a huge leap in numbers of  
adherents, he said the risk is real. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the first time America's children have been exposed 24  
hours a day, seven days a week to this level of racism and bigotry 
and packaged in a way that is, quite frankly, attractive,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Other methods of attraction have worked in the past.  
</P>
<P>
	The Southern Poverty Law Center in Montgomery, Ala., estimates  
more than 100,000 followers among the various hate groups, though a 
spokesman concedes that the tally -- from periodicals, news reports 
and police -- is approximate. The center also counts membership in 
such religions as the Christian Identity Movement. 
</P>
<P>
	``The numbers are absolutely soft,'' said Mark Potok, a Southern  
Poverty Law Center spokesman. ``We are talking about a tiny number 
of Americans who are members of hate groups -- I mean, 
infinitesimal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even fewer members of hate groups commit hate crimes. More than  
95 percent of such crimes are committed by those with no hate-group 
ties, said Jack McDevitt, a professor of criminal justice at 
Northeastern University in Boston. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet the Internet offers a home for haters, regardless of ties.  
``It allows people to believe that the number of people who share 
their beliefs is much larger,'' McDevitt said of the Internet. 
``You can log on to the Internet and see you're not weird.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So who are these few haters?  
</P>
<P>
	``Thirty years ago, there was this paradigm of bad people who  
commit hate crimes, who were extremists and they weren't like us,'' 
said Chip Berlet of Political Research Associates in Somerville, 
Mass. ``Now we know they're our neighbors. They're relatively 
normal except for their biased views, and they act out on their 
beliefs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McDevitt offered this overview: Most cohesive hate groups  
consist of 15 to 25 members, predominantly males in their teens and 
20s. The groups appeal to those who feel unwanted by family or 
society. Even if they find a home or a group, they may join for 
only a few months or a few years. 
</P>
<P>
	``Kids get into it and realize this is a lifestyle that doesn't  
offer a lot of a future,'' McDevitt said. 
</P>
<P>
	To the experts, Benjamin Smith was an oddity. That's borne out  
by data that the FBI's Uniform Crime Reporting Program began 
collecting in 1990. Of the 8,049 hate crimes reported in 1997, the 
most recent figures available, only eight were killings. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet Smith's deadly spree last weekend evokes memories of other  
loners who shed blood out of hatred. 
</P>
<P>
	Consider Joseph Paul Franklin, now on death row in Missouri. A  
self-proclaimed white supremacist, he was believed to have killed 
17 people in the 1970s and '80s -- three interracial couples, seven 
black men and boys, three women and a Jewish man -- though he was 
convicted for fewer deaths. And Patrick Purdy, who opened fire on a 
schoolyard in Stockton, Calif., in 1989, killing five Asian 
children before committing suicide. 
</P>
<P>
	``Most hate crimes are not committed with guns,'' McDevitt said.  
``They're committed with people's hands, or rocks, bricks, bats. 
This most recent incident is particularly frightening because it 
was random violence by guns.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
