<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> No Change in British Interest Rate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- The Bank of England left its base lending rate  
unchanged at 5 percent Thursday after a monthly review of the 
country's economic performance. 
</P>
<P>
	The bank's decision to keep the base rate where it is -- at its  
lowest level since 1977 -- followed incremental reductions during 
seven of the previous nine months. The base rate is what the Bank 
of England, Britain's central bank, charges for loans to other 
institutions. 
</P>
<P>
	The bank announced its decision to keep rates where they are  
after a regular meeting of its monetary committee. It did not 
explain the decision. 
</P>
<P>
	A leading business group, The British Chambers of Commerce, said  
the bank was ``right to hold fire on rates,'' due to signs of 
improvement in the British economy. 
</P>
<P>
	However, the BCC urged the bank to monitor the value of  
Britain's currency, the pound, with a view to cutting the base rate 
later in the year if the pound's strength makes British exports 
less competitive. A strong pound makes British goods more expensive 
than exports denominated in other currencies, and exporters have 
long complained that lower interest rates are necessary for the 
pound to become less expensive. 
</P>
<P>
	The Trades Union Congress criticized the bank's decision, saying  
a further reduction in the base rate would have been better news 
for the economy. 
</P>
<P>
	Labor unions, like many manufacturers, fear that Britain will  
lose jobs and sales to foreign competitors. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
