<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Continental Flight Hits Turbulence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HAMILTON, Bermuda (AP) -- A Continental Airlines flight from  
Newark, N.J. to Puerto Rico hit severe turbulence Thursday and 
dropped 500 feet, injuring 16 passengers and forcing it to land in 
Bermuda for medical help, police said. 
</P>
<P>
	Police in Bermuda said 16 of the 159 people aboard Continental  
Flight 743 were hospitalized with serious injuries, most to the 
head and neck, and that another 45 passengers suffered minor 
injuries. 
</P>
<P>
	``In one minute, I saw people flying. It was like an S-shape in  
the air, up and down. I saw one man flip right over the seat,'' 
passenger Diana Munoz of Newark told a reporter at the airport. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was a lot of blood... a lot of neck injuries,'' said  
Miguel Vargas, also from Newark. He said one food cart hit the 
ceiling. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the injuries were minor, nursing supervisor Doreen  
Richardson of King Edward VII Hospital said. 
</P>
<P>
	Continental spokeswoman Karla Villalon said the turbulence came  
amid fairly clear skies, causing the plane to drop 500 feet then 
quickly recover. She said she understood most people had only minor 
injuries. 
</P>
<P>
	A statement from Continental Airlines headquarters in Houston,  
Texas, said the Boeing 737-800 flying from Newark encountered 
turbulence when it was at about 29,000 feet and 180 miles south of 
Bermuda. It said the Boeing 737-800 was carrying 153 passengers and 
a crew of four flight attendants and two pilots. 
</P>
<P>
	All four flight attendants were injured, the airline said, and  
Barnett said two of them were taken to the hospital in neck braces. 
</P>
<P>
	The flight left Newark at 12:20 p.m. and landed in Hamilton at  
about 4 p.m., Barnett said. 
</P>
<P>
	She said the plane was not damaged and suffered only a  
superficial crack in the rear. 
</P>
<P>
	Passengers who were not hurt were taken to the Marriott and  
Grotto Bay Hotels and were expected to be flown to Puerto Rico on 
Friday afternoon, Barnett said. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
