<HEADLINE> Albright's Vacation Not All Play </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Secretary of State Madeleine Albright took  
time out from her European vacation to have lunch with Bernard 
Kouchner, newly appointed chief of civilian administration in 
Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	Seeking to dispel suggestions that the administration was  
unhappy with the choice, State Department spokesman James Foley 
said Albright ``was most impressed with his energy, passion and 
commitment to doing the job.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kouchner, who was French health minister, was appointed last  
week. 
</P>
<P>
	The two had lunch on Tuesday in Innsbruck, Austria.  
</P>
<P>
	Albright also made phone calls to Israeli Prime Minister Ehud  
Barak and Foreign Minister David Levy to congratulate them on 
taking their respective offices. 
</P>
<P>
	She also expressed her interest in working with both to advance  
the peace process, Foley said. She delivered the same message in a 
telephone call to Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat. 
</P>
<P>
	Albright also has had at least two phone conversations with U.N.  
Secretary General Kofi Annan and one with Russian Foreign Minister 
Igor Ivanov. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know if this secretary of state is ever fully on  
vacation,'' Foley said. 
</P>
<P>
	Albright is due back in Washington over the weekend.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
