<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Doctor Indicted on Drug Charges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- A doctor who gained notoriety for distributing  
diet pills over the Internet has been indicted on 34 federal 
charges accusing him of illegally prescribing medicine. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal agents arrested Pietr Hitzig, 56, on Wednesday at his  
mother's home in Lewisburg, W.Va., The (Baltimore) Sun reported 
today. 
</P>
<P>
	Hitzig surrendered his medical license in February over  
allegations of improper sexual relations with patients. But his 
World Wide Web site still advertises drug treatments with the 
banner ``Better than Ever.'' Authorities said it was unclear 
whether the Harvard-educated doctor continues to practice medicine. 
</P>
<P>
	The indictment unsealed in U.S. District Court in Baltimore  
relates to prescriptions for patients between 1996 and 1998, when 
Hitzig was running a Baltimore-based practice. 
</P>
<P>
	Hundreds of patients around the world obtained drugs like the  
diet combination fen-phen from Hitzig after visiting his Web site 
and sending him requests by e-mail. Doctors in Maryland are 
required to examine patients before prescribing medication. 
</P>
<P>
	A federal affidavit says a patient who met Hitzig through the  
Internet was an undercover Drug Enforcement Administration agent, 
who posed as an overweight businessman looking to slim down. The 
agent said Hitzig prescribed him drugs to foster weight loss, 
though the two never met in person, the affidavit said. 
</P>
<P>
	Each of the 34 counts in the indictment carries a maximum  
penalty of three years in prison without parole. 
</P>
<P>
	Fenfluramine, the ``fen'' half of the combination, was pulled  
off the market in 1997 amid concerns that it scarred heart valves 
irreversibly and sometimes fatally. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
