<DOCNO> APW19990708.0252 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 08:57:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  India Army Chief Visits Battle Zone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MUSHKOH VALLEY, India (AP) -- Indian troops seized another peak  
today in Kashmir's northern battle zone, a ridge India says is a 
vital supply route for Pakistan-based fighters. 
</P>
<P>
	A field commander said 70 Pakistani soldiers or Islamic  
guerrillas were killed in an overnight battle for the ridge in the 
Muskhoh Valley. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif's pledge to  
persuade the forces to withdraw from Indian-held Kashmir, Indian 
commanders on the Himalayan battle front said there was no sign of 
a retreat. Instead, the rebels were attacking positions they lost 
earlier this week. 
</P>
<P>
	Sharif returned home today from a weekend summit with President  
Clinton, where he agreed to seek the withdrawal of forces fighting 
in Kashmir. Sharif was due to meet with his army chief and cabinet, 
and may address the nation, his aides said. 
</P>
<P>
	Sharif has been widely condemned in Pakistan by religious  
parties, guerrilla groups and opposition political parties. The 
right-wing Jamaat-e-Islami party accused him of treason and 
threatened to depose him. 
</P>
<P>
	India says Pakistani troops are leading the fighters in Kashmir.  
Islamabad, however, denies that, saying the fighters are Kashmiri 
insurgents that receive only moral support from Pakistan. 
</P>
<P>
	Fighting remained fierce in the mountains above Kargil, around  
the town of Batalik and in the Mushkoh Valley. ``The enemy is 
giving us stiff resistance,'' said Col. Bikram Singh, the Indian 
military spokesman. 
</P>
<P>
	Indian soldiers returning from the battle boasted that they had  
to step over the corpses of Pakistani soldiers or Islamic 
guerrillas strewn across the rocky ridge. 
</P>
<P>
	The field commander said India had 18 casualties, but had no  
breakdown of dead and wounded. Front-line officers cannot be 
identified by name. Wounded soldiers hobbled down the treacherous 
path supported by comrades to receive medical treatment. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere on the front, five Pakistani artillery shells landed  
in Kargil. One shell hit the office of the state-run All India 
Radio, killing one policeman, a local commander said. 
</P>
<P>
	Heavy Pakistani bombardment continued on Tiger Hill, a strategic  
peak retaken by Indian troops over the weekend. Indian soldiers 
were blowing up tunnels large enough for 40 people that were built 
by the intruders. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. State Department officials expressed confidence Wednesday  
that Sharif remains committed to an early resolution of the 
conflict. 
</P>
<P>
	Spokesman James Foley said a resolution means restoring Line of  
Control, as the 1972 cease-fire line is known, and a resumption of 
direct negotiations on the outstanding issues between the two 
countries. 
</P>
<P>
	The militant groups said they would rather die than withdraw  
from their fight to separate Muslim-majority Kashmir from 
Hindu-dominated India. 
</P>
<P>
	By Wednesday, India said 542 Pakistani soldiers and more than  
150 Islamic guerrillas have been killed, while 283 Indian soldiers 
have died, 451 were wounded and 10 are missing. The figures cannot 
be independently confirmed. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990708.0253 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 08:57:19 </DATE_TIME>
