<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 12:00:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cipollini Wins 5th Stage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AMIENS, France (AP) -- As befits his nickname, ``The Lion King,''  
Mario Cipollini is clearly inspired by grandeur. 
</P>
<P>
	With the Tour de France passing a royal palace one day and three  
stunning cathedrals the next, the Italian has won two straight 
stages of cycling's showcase race. 
</P>
<P>
	All this when observers had started to grumble about his  
sluggish performance, and Cipollini had joked about soon being 
unemployed because his team, Saeco, was unhappy. 
</P>
<P>
	``Discussions have resumed about my future,'' he said Thursday,  
after surging across the finish line just ahead of Belgian Tom 
Steels and winning the fifth stage. 
</P>
<P>
	Estonian Jaan Kirsipuu finished third and retained the yellow  
leader's jersey for the fourth day. Robbie McEwen of Australia was 
fourth and German Erik Zabel fifth. 
</P>
<P>
	The stage was one of the longest of the Tour, a 145-mile ride  
through rolling wheat fields and occasional bursts of sunflowers. 
</P>
<P>
	It approached at least three grand cathedrals: the Gothic  
masterpiece at Chartres, with its famed stained-glass windows; a 
graceful one at Beauvais, and France's biggest at Amiens, where the 
stage ended. 
</P>
<P>
	On their way to the Somme region, where the famous World War I  
battle was fought, the riders passed tantalizingly close to Paris, 
only 31 miles away. They might have been tempted to take a short 
cut over to the Champs-Elysees, site of the finale. 
</P>
<P>
	Unlike Wednesday, when a favorable tailwind led to a record  
speed for the stage, the riders faced a headwind Thursday and the 
average speed was nearly six mph slower. 
</P>
<P>
	In the overall standings, Steels moved up to second and  
Australian Stuart O'Grady was third. Lance Armstrong, on the 
comeback from testicular cancer, was fourth, and Cipollini fifth. 
</P>
<P>
	The race was marked by an early breakaway, this time at the  
two-mile mark. A group of 10 riders made the break, instigated by 
Frenchmen Jacky Durand and his Belgian teammate on Lotto-Mobistar, 
Thierry Marechal. 
</P>
<P>
	The group had as much as a 6-minute, 15-second lead, but that  
soon was whittled down by the advancing pack. 
</P>
<P>
	Sweden's Magnus Backstedt took a brief lead near the end. But he  
was soon overtaken, and the race was set for another furious, 
wide-open sprint. Cipollini's Saeco teammates again moved him into 
position, and he sprinted to victory. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, Cipollini chose the former home of French kings to  
win the fastest stage in tour history. 
</P>
<P>
	In the town of Blois, in view of the imposing royal castle, he  
came off a stone bridge spanning the Loire River to win the fourth 
stage in a photo finish -- and a record speed of 31.290 mph. 
</P>
<P>
	For now, the talk at the Tour has been mostly about cycling, not  
drugs, which developed into such a monumental scandal last year. 
</P>
<P>
	But on Thursday, the sport's governing body had to deny a  
published report that a Tour cyclist tested positive for a banned 
drug after the race's prologue. 
</P>
<P>
	The French sports daily L'Equipe said one of four riders tested  
was found to have taken corticosteroids, anti-inflammatory drugs 
that are not classed as steroids but are banned, except when used 
for legitimate medical needs. 
</P>
<P>
	That charge was denied by the International Cycling Union.  
</P>
<P>
	``There was not one positive case,'' UCI spokesman Enrico  
Carpani said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990708.0255 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 07:40:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Pull Back; Dow Down 78.51 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks opened lower today amid rising interest  
rates and a mixed batch of second-quarter earnings reports. 
</P>
<P>
	At 10 a.m. on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was  
down 78.51 at 11,108.85. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were modestly lower. The Standard &AMP;  
Poor's 500 index was down 6.83 at 1,389.03, and the Nasdaq 
composite index was down 4.24 at 2,738.80. 
</P>
<P>
	Bond prices tumbled today, with the 30-year Treasury bond  
dropping 1/2 point in price, pushing its yield up to 6.08 percent, 
from 6.04 percent late Wednesday. The rising yield served as a 
reminder to investors that higher interest rates are taking hold in 
the buoyant economy, and could threaten earnings in future 
quarters. 
</P>
<P>
	Banks and brokerages, seen as most vulnerable to interest rate  
increases, were among the big losers today. J.P. Morgan, a 
component of the Dow, fell 2 to 144. 
</P>
<P>
	Stocks had risen to record levels in recent sessions, due  
largely to a strong outlook for second-quarter profits. But mixed 
earnings today helped take stocks lower. 
</P>
<P>
	General Electric confirmed those expectations, beating analysts'  
estimates by a penny. Its stock, which rose sharply Wednesday in 
advance of the report, slipped 1 3/4 to 116 3/16. 
</P>
<P>
	Airborne Freight said late Wednesday it will miss analysts'  
expectations by as much as 18 cents per share. Its shares slipped 1/8 
to 27 3/16, but other package delivery company stocks fell more 
sharply. 
</P>
<P>
	Philip Morris rose 1/4 to 38 1/8. Its shares had dropped in late  
trading Wednesday afternoon after a Florida jury ruled that tobacco 
makers are liable for making a defective product that causes 
emphysema, lung cancer and other illnesses. The verdict, if it 
stands, is expected to cost the tobacco industry billions in 
damages. 
</P>
<P>
	Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 2-to-1 margin on the  
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 103.2 million shares, 
ahead of Wednesday's pace. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index was down 3.46 at 653.01, and the  
American Stock Exchange composite index was down 2.15 at 799.99. 
</P>
<P>
	Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average rose 0.05 percent. In  
afternoon trading, Germany's DAX index was up 0.3 percent, France's 
CAC-40 was down 0.4 percent, and Britain's FT-SE 100 was down just 
a few points. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990708.0256 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 20:20:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> UN Looks into Use of Annan's Image </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- The U.N. legal office, which spends its  
days considering complex matters of international law, has turned 
its attention to the New York city transit pass. 
</P>
<P>
	The issue concerns an advertisement on the back of the MetroCard  
that features a picture of U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan and 
the phrase ``Got time for a Kofi break?'' 
</P>
<P>
	The ad is for ABC.com, the Web site of the news network.  
</P>
<P>
	U.N. spokesman Manoel de Almeida e Silva said Thursday that  
ABC.com hadn't asked for or received U.N. authorization to use 
Annan's name or photograph for the ad. 
</P>
<P>
	``In as much as this may raise some legal issues, the legal  
office is looking into the matter,'' he told reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	A spokesman for ABC parent Disney's online group, Eric Handler,  
said he couldn't comment because he hadn't received any direct 
complaint from the United Nations. 
</P>
<P>
	Similar ads feature Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and  
Attorney General Janet Reno. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990708.0257 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 23:40:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Courtney Love Helps Crash Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	STRATHMORE, Alberta (AP) -- Courtney Love and members of her band  
came to the aid of two crash victims after an accident on the 
TransCanada Highway. 
</P>
<P>
	Members of the band, Hole, were en route to Calgary for the  
Edgefest music festival when they saw a car flip about 18 miles 
outside of town Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The rockers brought the two victims inside their bus and offered  
them hot tea and first aid until help arrived, the Royal Canadian 
Mounted Police said. The victims were later taken to a hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	``They were obviously in shock, so shelter was important and  
part of the first aid, she provided,'' said RCMP Constable Daryl 
Bedard. 
</P>
<P>
	Bedard said Love later offered the victims free festival  
tickets. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990708.0258 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 23:10:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mormon Humor? Get Serious </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- A new book of Mormon humor? The very idea  
draws horselaughs from some members of the faith known for its 
seriousness and sobriety. Yet it's true -- and the publisher is The 
Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints. 
</P>
<P>
	``We tried hard not to offend anybody,'' said Jack Lyon,  
managing editor of church-owned Deseret Book, which released 
``Best-Loved Humor of the LDS People'' this spring. ``We did select 
things people could use if giving a talk in church.'' 
</P>
<P>
	An example:  
</P>
<P>
	``Question: How are bishops chosen?  
</P>
<P>
	``Answer: The stake leaders find the most righteous, spiritual,  
most loved person in the ward -- and then they call her husband.'' 
</P>
<P>
	OK, this is not comedy club stuff. But it's heading in the right  
direction, say those who want to show there's fun beneath the 
faith's buttoned-down image. 
</P>
<P>
	Robert Kirby, considered by many the preeminent Mormon humorist  
today, thought for years that most of his fellow believers were a 
pretty pinched lot. 
</P>
<P>
	``I equated Mormons with the way they behaved in church,'' said  
Kirby, a humor columnist for The Salt Lake Tribune. 
</P>
<P>
	This was, after all, the church whose canonical Doctrine and  
Covenants states: ``Therefore, cease from all your light speeches, 
from all laughter, from all your lustful desires, from all your 
pride and light-mindedness, and from all your wicked doings.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kirby continued: ``I operated on the premise that church was a  
place where humorless people go. I misinterpreted reverence for 
humorlessness.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That changed with Kirby's first foray into Mormon humor, a  
satirical column about five types of Mormons, which he wrote for a 
newspaper where he used to work. Though his Mormon publisher hated 
it, the column brought a flood of letters from church members who 
loved it. 
</P>
<P>
	Kirby felt like a miner cracking his shins on the mother lode.  
</P>
<P>
	``I was surprised that Mormons, particularly -- I know Jewish  
people do it and Catholics to a large extent -- used humor to make 
their lot in life a little more tolerable,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``And the depth of it was even more surprising, because you get  
people who are very staunch members of the church who laugh about 
the inconsistencies or the vagaries in our behavior and the 
mysteries of the gospel.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In other words, they are able to laugh at themselves.  
</P>
<P>
	Psst! begins a joke that has made the rounds, though it isn't in  
the new book: How do you tell the difference between a Mormon 
wedding and a non-Mormon wedding? At the Mormon wedding, the 
bride's mother is pregnant. 
</P>
<P>
	The punch line plays on the traditional Mormon propensity for  
large families. 
</P>
<P>
	``The really funny Mormon stuff is uniquely Mormon. It's  
something that comes from being part of the family,'' said Pat 
Bagley, political cartoonist at the Tribune. 
</P>
<P>
	Mormons use humor as a decompression device, ``a way to let off  
some of the pressure that builds up'' and to say things that are 
true but which, unadorned with humor, might seem heretical or mean. 
For example, he says, ``It's not politic to say 19-year-old 
missionaries are dumb,'' but it's safe to say the same thing in a 
joke or cartoon. 
</P>
<P>
	Elouise Bell, a retired Brigham Young University English  
professor and author of a collection of humorous essays titled 
``Only When I Laugh,'' observed: ``The essence of really good humor 
is a kind of surprise. Well, I think culturally Mormons don't like 
surprises in outward things. I mean, look at the architecture. And 
there are very few startling pronouncements made from pulpits week 
to week, year to year, decade to decade.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Irreverent humor can be both unsettling and subversive, and its  
purveyors scorned as impious or worse. 
</P>
<P>
	``A humorist is a person who thinks otherwise,'' Bell said.  
``Well, thinking otherwise can get you into trouble in any 
establishment -- in the military, in most churches, in most 
educational institutions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The pitfalls associated with thinking otherwise were very much  
on the minds of three editors who compiled the material for 
``Best-Loved Humor of the LDS People.'' (Kirby likes to call it, 
``The Correlation Committee-Approved Humor of the LDS People.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Oddly, among the dozens of examples of humor from church leaders  
there is nothing in the book from church President Gordon B. 
Hinckley, known for his sense of humor. 
</P>
<P>
	Said editor Jay Parry, ``He is delightful and he is very funny.  
But it's the kind of thing that you had to have been there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kirby credits Hinckley with sensing that Mormonism, in the midst  
of a global expansion, needs to lighten up. 
</P>
<P>
	``How do you assimilate all different types of people into one  
religion?'' It's best done through tolerance and making a human 
connection, he said, ``and humor for me is the best way to do 
that.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990708.0259 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 07:30:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Broadway Shows a Go for Dec. 31 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The show can go on this New Year's eve, despite  
a police department recommendation that theaters stay dark on the 
last night of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	``You have to allow the signature entertainment for New York --  
Broadway -- to take place that night,'' Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said 
Wednesday. The mayor said he first learned of the police plan from 
newspapers Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The police department, fearing that overflowing Times Square  
crowds could create problems, said Broadway theaters should shut 
down Dec. 31. 
</P>
<P>
	``This was a recommendation that was made to the league of  
directors, because of safety concerns,'' police spokeswoman Marilyn 
Mode said. 
</P>
<P>
	Police estimate some 2 million people could pack Times Square to  
ring in 2000. The theater crowd could add an additional 40,000. 
Giuliani said a more sensible plan would be to limit the number of 
people allowed into Times Square. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the risk of losing hundreds of thousands of dollars in  
advance ticket sales, many theater owners said they would follow 
the police suggestion anyway. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's going to be a very, very, very congested area this  
year,'' said Lee Silver of the Shubert Organization, which operates 
16 theaters. 
</P>
<P>
	But one producer, Alexander Cohen of ``Waiting in the Wings,''  
said his show would go on. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990708.0260 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 01:20:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Richardson Agrees to GOP Nuke Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- In the most significant fallout yet from the  
controversy over Chinese espionage and lax security, Energy 
Secretary Bill Richardson has agreed to a semiautonomous nuclear 
weapons agency within his department. 
</P>
<P>
	Richardson until this week has strongly opposed a Republican  
proposal for such an agency saying it would weaken the authority of 
future energy secretaries and create ``a new fiefdom in a 
department of fiefdoms.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But under pressure from Congress -- and reportedly a strong  
signal from the White House to reach some accommodation on 
department reorganization -- Richardson has accepted creation of the 
new agency, with conditions. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm ready to move on this,'' Richardson told The Washington  
Post, adding that he had directed his staff to ``work with Congress 
on details to craft a bipartisan package.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Richardson could not be reached late Wednesday for comment.  
</P>
<P>
	However, an Energy Department official, who spoke on condition  
of anonymity, said Richardson ``has agreed to the notion of a 
semiautonomous nuclear agency'' headed by an undersecretary of 
energy and reporting to the energy secretary. 
</P>
<P>
	The new Agency for Nuclear Stewardship would run the  
department's three nuclear weapons laboratories and other 
facilities that maintain the nuclear weapons stockpile. 
</P>
<P>
	Creation of such an agency to oversee the weapons programs was  
first proposed by Republican Sens. Pete Domenici of New Mexico, Jon 
Kyl of Arizona, and Frank Murkowski of Alaska as a way to 
strengthen security at the laboratories. 
</P>
<P>
	The official said details of the new agency must still be worked  
out in negotiations with Republican lawmakers. 
</P>
<P>
	Richardson was persuaded to endorse the concept of a largely  
autonomous agency when assured that the energy secretary would 
continue to have clear authority over nuclear programs, and that 
the new agency would remain accountable to department-wide 
counterintelligence and security offices. 
</P>
<P>
	The Republican senators' proposal called for the agency to be  
largely insulated from the rest of the Energy Department and to 
have its own budget and authority over personnel mattes. Some of 
those issues remained to be worked out in negotiations, the 
department official said. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Richardson's acceptance of a semiautonomous agency  
represented a major step toward the first major reorganization of 
the Energy Department since it was created in 1977. 
</P>
<P>
	Richardson and Republican senators have wrangled for weeks over  
how the department should be restructured in response to the 
political uproar over lax security at nuclear weapons labs and the 
alleged theft -- mostly in the 1980s -- of nuclear weapons secrets by 
China. 
</P>
<P>
	Richardson until this week had maintained that his proposal to  
strengthen counterintelligence and security, including the naming 
of retired Air Force Gen. Eugene Habiger as ``security czar,'' was 
addressing the concerns. 
</P>
<P>
	But a growing number of lawmakers -- both Republicans and  
Democrats -- have expressed concern that the department's nuclear 
weapons program needs to be made more accountable with a clearer 
chain of command under a single agency. 
</P>
<P>
	Those concerns were reinforced by the findings of the  
president's own Foreign Intelligence Advisory Board, headed by 
former Sen. Warren Rudman of New Hampshire. The panel concluded 
that the Energy Department's ``dysfunctional bureaucracy'' was 
``incapable of reforming itself'' under its present structure. 
</P>
<P>
	The panel, in a report requested by President Clinton, urged  
creation of a largely autonomous nuclear weapons agency within the 
department, or taking the nuclear weapons program out of the 
department altogether. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposed Agency for Nuclear Stewardship, although still in  
the department, would consolidate control over the three nuclear 
weapons labs -- Sandia, Los Alamos and Lawrence Livermore -- as well 
as the Nevada nuclear test site and various nuclear material 
production and assembly plants around the country. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990708.0261 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 08:23:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Two Rookies Favored in Senior Open  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WEST DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- Allen Doyle and Bruce Fleisher were  
walking up to the 18th hole on the final day of the Senior Tour 
qualifying school when Fleisher breathed a sign of relief. 
</P>
<P>
	It had been a tough week and it was almost over. Doyle, though,  
saw it differently. 
</P>
<P>
	``I said to him, `You know, there are going to be two or three  
guys out of this tour school that are going to win over a million 
dollars and they are going to have real good years.' He said, `Why 
shouldn't that be us?''' 
</P>
<P>
	Less than a year later, Fleisher and Doyle rank 1-2 on the  
Senior Tour money list and, yes, each has made more than $1 
million. Today, they began play in the U.S. Senior Open as two of 
the favorites. 
</P>
<P>
	``He has asked me, did I expect to have done what I did?'' Doyle  
said. ``And you know, I said, `Not really.' And he pretty much 
acknowledged that he really hadn't expected to do quite as well as 
he had done.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Neither received much professional acclaim before this year.  
</P>
<P>
	Doyle, whose unorthodox swing resembles a slap shot in hockey,  
spent most of his career as an amateur before becoming, at the age 
of 47, the oldest rookie ever on the PGA Tour. 
</P>
<P>
	Fleisher had a nondescript career as a touring pro and even  
dropped off the tour for a few years in the 1980s to work as a club 
pro so he could make ends meet. 
</P>
<P>
	But they've found new life on the Senior Tour, where younger is  
definitely better. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm finally starting to have some fun this year,'' said  
Fleisher, who became eligible for the Senior Tour when he turned 50 
last October. 
</P>
<P>
	Defending champion Hale Irwin is starting to have some fun again  
after struggling early in the year. He entered the Open with 
victories in three of his last five tournaments, including a 
seven-stroke win in the Senior Players Championship at the TPC of 
Michigan two weeks ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Also in 156-man field were Larry Nelson, No. 3 on the money  
list; Vicente Fernandez, last year's runner-up; Graham Marsh, 
winner of The Tradition this year; and Christy O'Connor, coming off 
a victory in the State Farm Classic. 
</P>
<P>
	The tournament is being played at Des Moines Golf and Country  
Club, a 6,888-yard, par-72 layout that never before had been the 
site of a major tournament. With its undulating greens, the course 
puts a premium on approach shots and putting. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's going to be an exciting tournament,'' Fleisher  
said. ``Hopefully, no one will get so hot like Irwin did a couple 
of weeks ago and blow everybody away. He may do it again. Who 
knows? 
</P>
<P>
	``But I don't think a low number is going to be the answer this  
week,'' he said. ``I think the greens are too difficult. I don't 
know if anyone knows the greens that well to really excel at this 
time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Irwin said a golfer will have to master those greens to win.  
</P>
<P>
	``It is going to be a significant test for all of us,'' he said.  
``I think ... a good majority of the test will come around the 
greens -- not terribly unlike the U.S. Open this year where a good 
bit of the test was around the greens. I think we will see much the 
same here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Handling the course also will require patience, Doyle said. With  
72 holes to play, he said there's no reason to get upset over one 
or two mistakes. 
</P>
<P>
	``You have to handle it properly and realize there is a long way  
to go,'' he said. ``It's not so much the guy who makes the most 
birdies that is going to win, but the guy who makes the fewest 
bogeys.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As for that sour-looking swing, Doyle said he knows it offends  
the purists, but it works for him. 
</P>
<P>
	``As a kid, the club pro used to tell me, `If you can drive it  
pretty good and you've got a pretty good short game, you will be 
able to score,''' Doyle said. ```So don't ever pay attention to 
anybody that can't beat you.' 
</P>
<P>
	``I always have kept that to heart.''  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990708.0262 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 08:23:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cavaliers Hire Wittman As New Coach </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- Randy Wittman has seen the NBA for 16 years as  
a player and an assistant coach, and, frankly, he thinks the league 
needs more zip. 
</P>
<P>
	That's just what the Cleveland Cavaliers wanted to hear, so they  
hired the Minnesota Timberwolves assistant Wednesday as their new 
head coach, even though he's never held the top job before. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to stress the game needs to have more life put into  
it,'' Wittman said as he was introduced at Gund Arena. ``I think we 
need as coaches to look in the mirror a little bit and allow our 
players to play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Cavs have been searching for someone who will bring a spark  
and a more open style to their franchise after six seasons under 
former coach Mike Fratello, who was fired June 1. 
</P>
<P>
	Fratello's teams were often injury-plagued, and he was credited  
with making the most of bad situations by installing a clock-eating 
offense and tough defense. But fans got tired of watching the 
grind-it-out style, even if it meant a few more wins than losses. 
</P>
<P>
	Average game attendance dropped from 18,011 in 1994-95 to 14,120  
last season and the Cavs' postseason performances have been weak in 
recent years. Cleveland hasn't made it out of the first round of 
the playoffs since 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	Wittman's plan for bringing fans back is as simple as putting  
together a team that has a good time on the court. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to instill in them what it takes to work hard, the  
dedication to get there. But I want them -- when they cross the 
sideline -- to have fun,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think if you can put a product on the floor that people are  
entertained with, wins and losses will take care of themselves.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cavs center Zydrunas Ilgauskas, one of a few players who watched  
as Wittman was introduced during a news conference, liked what he 
heard. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's exciting to see a new guy with new ideas come in here.  
He's got the whole team behind him,'' Ilgauskas said. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite never holding a head coaching position, the 39-year-old  
Wittman comes to Cleveland with some strong credentials. 
</P>
<P>
	He played on Indiana's 1981 NCAA championship team and was a  
two-time academic All-American with the Hoosiers. Indiana coach Bob 
Knight on Wednesday called Wittman one of the smartest players he 
ever coached. 
</P>
<P>
	``For a player, he had a rare understanding of just what it  
takes to win and how to go about it,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Wittman was a first-round draft pick of the Washington Bullets,  
but was traded to the Atlanta Hawks before the 1983-84 season and 
played under Fratello there. He also played for Sacramento and 
Indiana and finished his nine-year NBA career averaging 7.4 points 
per game. 
</P>
<P>
	He has spent the last five years as an assistant coach at  
Minnesota and also had one-year stints in Dallas and Indiana. 
</P>
<P>
	Cleveland general manager Jim Paxson, who headed the coaching  
search, said he recommended Wittman to Cavs owner Gordon Gund 
because ``he is the coach who will be most flexible and adaptable 
with respect to both players and the NBA game as it continues to 
evolve.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Others with head coaching experience might be viewed by some  
as safer choices,'' he said. ``For us, Randy Wittman is the right 
choice.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Paxson would not disclose the length of Wittman's contract or  
how much he'll be paid. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cavs were secretive about their coaching search until  
Wittman was introduced. Despite plans to create some excitement 
surrounding the team, the Cavs refused to reveal the names of any 
potential coaching candidates. 
</P>
<P>
	When Wittman arrived in Cleveland on Wednesday, the Cavs sent a  
limousine to meet his plane, so he avoided reporters and fans at 
the flight gate. 
</P>
<P>
	Dave Cowens, Del Harris and John MacLeod also interviewed for  
the Cavs job. 
</P>
<P>
	The hiring of Wittman is part of a continuing makeover of the  
Cavaliers organization in which well-known names are being replaced 
by a younger group. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to the firing of Fratello, known as the ``Czar of  
Telestrator'' for his television commentary work, newly elected 
Hall of Famer Wayne Embry has stepped aside as general manager in 
favor of Paxson. 
</P>
<P>
	And last week's draft saw the Cavs make two other moves which  
could change their look on the court. 
</P>
<P>
	Unable to trade up in the first round to get Miami of Ohio's  
Wally Szczerbiak, Cleveland took Utah point Andre Miller and Duke 
guard Trajan Langdon -- a pair who could potentially challenge 
Brevin Knight and Derek Anderson for their jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	Minnesota wound up with Szczerbiak and the two players Wittman  
thought the Timberwolves would get in the first round -- Miller and 
Langdon -- went to the Cavs. Wittman said he's ``ecstatic'' with 
Cleveland's draft choices. 
</P>
<P>
	Paxson was simultaneously preparing for the draft as he looked  
for a coach. He recommended Wittman to Gund just before the draft, 
and the former assistant met with Gund last Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Gund said he was impressed with Wittman's straightforward manner  
and potential as a teacher. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are absolutely, positively certain we ended up with the  
best choice,'' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990708.0263 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 08:23:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
