<HEADLINE> AP-Aramco-Summary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Here is the Latest News From the Associated Press. Copyright  
1999 by the Associated Press.	

</P>
<P>
	BAGHDAD (AP) -- Iraq has invited foreign companies to exhibit gas  
and oil technology at a trade fair in Baghdad in September, Oil 
Ministry officials said Wednesday. Iraq is bracing itself for a 
possible lifting of U.N. curbs on foreign investment in its oil 
industry. Iraq already has U.N. authorization to spend $300 million 
every six months on oil industry investment. The expenditure is 
allowed under the oil-for-food program which enables Iraq to sell 
limited amounts of oil and spend the proceeds on food and 
humanitarian goods. 

</P>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Iraq's oil managers are squeezing more  
barrels from existing wells using water injection techniques that 
will ultimately lower total yields, according to a report from U.N. 
oil industry consultants released Wednesday, Dow Jones News 
reports. Production may continue to increase in the near-term 
provided badly needed chemicals and equipment on order by Baghdad 
are approved for export by the U.N., according to the report. But, 
the long-term impact is likely to be lower yields and the premature 
closing of many wells. 

</P>
<P>
	KUWAIT (AP) -- Kuwait is inviting foreign investors to attend a  
forum early next year on business opportunities, a newspaper 
reported Wednesday. The move is the latest in a series of steps to 
open up the economy in the face of lower oil prices and the 
lingering effects of the 1990-91 Gulf crisis when Kuwait was 
occupied by Iraq. Trade and Commerce Minister Hisham al-Otaibi said 
the forum, Kuwait 2000, would take place Feb. 5-24. ``We have 
plenty of funds,'' the newspaper quoted the minister as saying. 
``All we need from foreign investors is to transfer technologies 
and to train the national work force, in addition to their 
experience in advanced management and marketing.'' 

</P>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- With the price of oil flirting with $20 a barrel  
for the first time in 19 months, energy companies are beginning to 
spend more freely on exploration but are being cautious before 
reversing thousands of layoffs. As prices sank toward $10 a barrel 
late last year, the oil industry tightened its belt in a harsh 
retrenchment that slashed payrolls and cut budgets. In Texas alone, 
14,200 jobs in the industry were eliminated since May 1998, 
according to state labor officials. 

</P>
<P>
	FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) -- Energy companies are greeting the news  
that crude oil futures surged above $20 a barrel for the first time 
in 19 months as a sign they can get back to work in Texas. Prices 
rose Tuesday before settling slightly lower on continuing efforts 
by world oil producers to cut output. ``The situation is looking 
better for oil and gas prices,'' Louis Baldwin, a senior vice 
president for Cross Timbers Oil Co., told the Fort Worth 
Star-Telegram in today's editions. 

</P>
<P>
	RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- U.S. oil giant Texaco Inc. and  
Brazil's Petrobras will jointly search and drill for oil on the 
continental shelf near Rio, the Brazilian company announced today. 
The companies are expected tomrrow to sign two contracts worth a 
reported $1.5 billion for exploration and production in the Campos 
Basin, which now produces more than half of Brazil's petroleum, a 
Petrobras spokeswoman said. Each company will own 42.5 percent of 
the venture, but Texaco will be the operator, the spokeswoman said. 
Japanese group Nissho Iwai Corp. holds a 12.75 percent stake and 
Brazil's Odebrecht has the rest. 

</P>
<P>
	TORONTO (CP) -- A steep jump in gasoline prices across Canada  
this week may have felt to motorists like a punch from the pumps, 
but the petroleum industry is calling it well-justified relief. It 
took half an hour for gas prices to jump to 60 cents a litre from 
50 cents in the Toronto area Tuesday, with the rest of Ontario 
following overnight. The increases varied across the country, but 
most drivers from Victoria to Halifax are now paying more to fill 
up. 

</P>
<P>
	GRANDE PRAIRIE, Alberta (AP) -- A judge Wednesday ordered the  
leader of a Christian commune and another commune member to stand 
trial in connection with a series of sabotage attacks on oil and 
gas installations in northwestern Alberta. Wiebo Ludwig, a former 
evangelical preacher who moved his extended family from Ontario to 
Alberta 13 years ago, has been the chief suspect for more than a 
year as police investigated some 160 incidents of sabotage and 
vandalism since 1996. 

</P>
<P>
	ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) -- Arco Alaska Inc. said Tuesday it has  
discovered a 50-million barrel oil field just north of its Alpine 
field on the North Slope. The Fiord field contains two oil zones 
that appear to be capable of producing at least 2,500 barrels of 
crude a day, Arco said in a news release. The Alpine field is about 
50 miles west of Prudhoe Bay. It contains at least 365 million 
barrels of recoverable oil, and Arco expects it to produce at least 
40,000 barrels a day when it begins operating next year. That 
should increase to 70 thousand barrels a day in 2001. 

</P>
<P>
	NEW CASTLE, Pa. (AP) -- The Amish residents of Mercer and  
northern Lawrence counties are forbidden from using natural gas 
from wells drilled on their property, but they are quietly 
benefitting from them in another way. In a link with modern society 
that has some Amish leaders concerned, landowners have allowed more 
than 200 wells to be drilled over the last decade, banking on 
monthly gas company checks that can top $600 per well. 

</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Futures prices for refined oil products rose  
Wednesday on the New York Mercantile Exchange amid expectations 
that a weekly report would show a drop in U.S. inventories. 
However, crude prices edged lower a day after spiking above $20 a 
gallon for the first time in 19 months. The contract for August 
delivery of light sweet crude oil settled at $19.77 per barrel, 
down 1 cent. But unleaded gasoline for delivery in August settled 
at 59.17 cents a gallon, gaining 0.69 cent, while home heating oil 
for delivery in August settled at 50.08 cents a gallon, up 0.70 
cent. 

</P>
<P>
	ABU DHABI, United Arab Emirates (AP) -- Saudi Defense Minister  
Prince Sultan arrived here Wednesday as part of a Gulf tour that 
will also take him to Qatar, Kuwait and Bahrain. The four-day 
regional tour is meant to further consolidate ties between the Gulf 
nations, the Saudi Press Agency reported. Ties between Saudi Arabia 
and the Emirates deteriorated last month over improved relations 
between Saudi Arabia and Iran. 

</P>
<P>
 *END NEWS SUMMARY. COPYRIGHT 1999 by the Associated Press.    	

  	   	
</P>
