<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Monte Wants Tyson, Who Doesn't? </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Heavyweights, good, bad and mediocre, used to hope to get a  
fight against Mike Tyson because it got them attention and their 
biggest paycheck. 
</P>
<P>
	Now they want Tyson, not only for the celebrity and the money,  
but because his iron cloak of intimidation turns out to be made of 
cloth. 
</P>
<P>
	One who wants to fight Tyson when the former undisputed champion  
comes back yet again, probably in October, is Monte Barrett. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mike ought to give me an opportunity, just like someone gave  
him an opportunity,'' Barrett said. 
</P>
<P>
	It, however, is not going to happen for the 28-year-old New  
Yorker with a 20-0 record and a gift of gab. 
</P>
<P>
	``Not now,'' said Shelly Finkel, a Tyson advisor. ``Monte's a  
sweet kid. I know him, but it's too early.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Perhaps it is. Barrett didn't turn pro until he was 25, and he  
could use seasoning against tougher competition than he has yet 
met. 
</P>
<P>
	On the other hand, Francois Botha proved Tyson, who turned 33  
June 30, is very vulnerable at this stage of his career. Botha got 
knocked out by a perfect right-hand punch in the fifth round Jan. 
16, but until then he made Tyson look small and slow. 
</P>
<P>
	So it might not be good business at this time to match a hungry  
fighter, who is 6-foot-3 and a good athlete, against Tyson, who 
cannot afford to lose. Nor can the money men behind him afford to 
have him lose. 
</P>
<P>
	Like Tyson, Barrett also has a promotional deal with America  
Presents. The promoter, of course, has a lot more money tied up in 
Tyson, who also has deals with Showtime and the MGM Grand at Las 
Vegas. 
</P>
<P>
	The affable Barrett, married with three children, took up boxing  
at age 21 and says he'll be out of it by age 33. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to have more kids and I want to enjoy life,'' Barrett  
said. Once into boxing, however, a lot of guys have had trouble 
getting out. 
</P>
<P>
	Barrett competed in basketball, baseball, gymnastics (floor  
exercises) and football at John Adams High School in Queens and was 
a good enough linebacker to be offered scholarships to Grambling, 
East Carolina and Southern Mississippi. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was a Prop 48 and I went Westchester Community College for a  
year,'' Barrett said. ``Then they dropped football and I dropped 
out and went to work full time in construction.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One day Barrett was lifting weights, he said, ``and this guy was  
hustling guys in the gym, telling them give me $15 a day, I'll 
teach you how to box.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Barrett started in amateur boxing under 83-year-old trainer Al  
Davis, who, with Jimmy Glenn, trains him as a pro. 
</P>
<P>
	After posting a 37-3 record, with 24 knockouts, Barrett turned  
pro in September 1996 under the management of Joe DeGuardia. 
</P>
<P>
	At the time he was preparing to become a pro, he was introduced  
to promoter Don King. 
</P>
<P>
	Barrett said King offered him a $70,000-$80,000 contract, a  
condo and a salary of $900 a week. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked the length of the contract, Barrett said, ``Forever.''  
</P>
<P>
	Barrett said that on his wedding day June 7, 1995, King flew him  
to Ohio to meet Tyson at his boxing camp at Orwell. 
</P>
<P>
	``We talked about people we know and about boxing,'' Barrett  
said of the meeting. ``We played basketball. He was putting dents 
in the backboard, but they (the shots) weren't going in.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The shot Monte Barrett wants is one at Tyson in the ring.  

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
