<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FAA Proposes Fining Boeing $392,000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- The Federal Aviation Administration has proposed  
fining Boeing Co. $392,000 for allegedly failing to report a safety 
problem on 757 jetliners until a year after it was discovered. 
</P>
<P>
	The FAA says Boeing failed to report the problem within 24  
hours, as required by federal rules. Boeing, however, contends it 
wasn't clear until much later that the problem was serious enough 
to fall under that requirement. 
</P>
<P>
	In another safety matter, Boeing shut down all overhead cranes  
in part of its Renton assembly plant after an operator found a 
15-inch crack in a rail used to transfer the massive cranes from 
one section of the building to another. 
</P>
<P>
	The crack was spotted Tuesday evening in the plant's 4-20  
building, the same part of the plant where crane operator Dean 
Morris of Des Moines fell to his death June 10. A preliminary 
investigation indicated that Morris' crane ran off the end of its 
track when a mechanism designed to stop it was stuck in the open 
position. 
</P>
<P>
	Boeing spokeswoman Shannon Myers said the latest problem was not  
related to the June accident. 
</P>
<P>
	She said Thursday that Boeing was testing the cranes and they  
would not be returned to production work until the company was sure 
they were safe. 
</P>
<P>
	The problem in 757 fuel systems was fixed three years ago.  
</P>
<P>
	If the civil penalty is imposed, it would be the second time  
Boeing was fined over the same manufacturing defect. Last year, the 
company paid a $130,000 fine for failing to properly install 
emergency fuel shutoff valves near 757 engines. 
</P>
<P>
	In a notification sent to the company June 17, the FAA contends  
Boeing discovered the defect in late May 1995, but did not report 
it to the FAA until June 21, 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	Boeing contends that it wasn't until that later date that it  
determined there was a possible hazard. 
</P>
<P>
	``When we knew we had a potential safety issue, we reported that  
within 24 hours,'' company spokeswoman Yvonne Leach said Wednesday. 
She said the company will seek an informal hearing to dispute the 
allegation. 
</P>
<P>
	The fine concerns the misalignment of emergency fuel-shut-off  
valves for the two engines on 757 airplanes manufactured from 1992 
until 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	In August 1996, the FAA issued an urgent airworthiness directive  
for operators to inspect and fix the valves on 236 of the planes. 
It cited the potential for a shutoff valve to fail and continue 
sending fuel from the wing tank to an engine in the event of an 
engine fire. 
</P>
<P>
	Boeing traced the problem to a tool in the 757 factory in Renton  
that was used to measure alignment during assembly. The tool was 
replaced and a new alignment test adopted. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990708.0267 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 13:10:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Navy May Restore Ties to Tailhook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Eight years after the Tailhook scandal of  
drunken escapades and sexual abuse rocked the Navy and forced 
changes in its treatment of women, Navy leaders are considering 
restoring official recognition to the aviators group that was host 
for the debauchery. 
</P>
<P>
	Rehabilitating the Tailhook Association is a remaining piece of  
``unfinished business'' in the Navy's effort to put the scandal 
behind it, Adm. Jay Johnson, the chief of naval operations, said in 
an interview. 
</P>
<P>
	While acknowledging that the Tailhook episode is an ``emotional  
and sensitive issue,'' Johnson said he is weighing only the 
practical question of whether Tailhook belongs back in the Navy 
fold as an organization meant to foster camaraderie and 
professional enrichment. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm seriously at work with the leadership of the Tailhook  
Association, working to make sure that we've learned the lessons we 
needed to learn -- which we have -- and that we've institutionalized 
those lessons,'' Johnson said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The admiral said he would make a recommendation to Navy  
Secretary Richard Danzig shortly. Other Navy officials, speaking on 
condition of anonymity, said the intention is to sanction a modest 
level of official Navy participation in the 1999 Tailhook 
convention, scheduled for Aug. 19-22 in Sparks, Nev. 
</P>
<P>
	Lonny McClung, a retired Navy captain who has been president of  
the Tailhook Association since 1995, said in an interview Thursday, 
``We think the timing is right'' to get back in the Navy's good 
graces. His organization, named for the hook on an aircraft carrier 
that snags an arresting cable on incoming planes, has about 10,000 
members -- down from its 1991 peak of about 16,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Besides its annual conventions, which include professional  
seminars, the group sponsors college scholarships for children of 
former naval aviators and publishes a magazine on carrier aviation 
called Hook. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson attended the September 1991 convention of Tailhook  
members at the Las Vegas Hilton Hotel but was never touched by the 
scandal, which triggered the resignation of Navy Secretary H. 
Lawrence Garrett and the early retirement of Adm. Frank B. Kelso, 
then the chief of naval operations. It also led to lawsuits, 
multiple investigations and a long-lasting black eye for the Navy. 
</P>
<P>
	In October 1991 the Navy ended all support ``in any manner  
whatsoever, direct or indirect'' for Tailhook. For several years 
afterward, the Senate required that it be informed of any Tailhook 
participation by any Navy or Marine Corps officer whose nomination 
for promotion was before the Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson said he has great confidence that Tailhook's new leaders  
will set the right course. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm looking at the organization itself, what their vision is,  
what their commitment is, how they view themselves as we go into 
the 21st century, and what that means for the United States Navy,'' 
Johnson added. If the organization has really changed its ways, 
``then I would be in a position to support it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It is not clear how Congress will react, although Sen. John  
Warner, R-Va., chairman of the Armed Services Committee, wrote to 
Danzig on March 31 urging a restoration of official ties to 
Tailhook. He said it would boost morale and help encourage pilots 
to stay in the Navy and Marine Corps. 
</P>
<P>
	Nancy Duff Campbell, of the National Women's Law Center and an  
expert on issues involving women in the military, said in an 
interview she has mixed feelings. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's one thing for them to say it won't happen again, but are  
they treating women aviators with welcoming arms?'' she said. If 
the organization is sincerely committed to supporting women fliers, 
and not just men, then it probably will be beneficial to restore 
official Navy recognition, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Any discussion of Tailhook is bound to recall the debauchery of  
the 1991 convention in Las Vegas, for which the Defense Department 
Inspector General implicated 117 officers for sexual assault, 
indecent exposure and other acts, and faulted the Navy's leaders 
for failing to stop the behavior. 
</P>
<P>
	Many Navy careers were ruined by the scandal although no one was  
court-martialed. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990708.0268 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 16:40:13 </DATE_TIME>
