<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) -- Special units of the U.S. Army based  
in Panama have helped train Nicaraguan mine-sniffing dogs, a 
Nicaraguan military source said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The 10-week training program cost $500,000 and is the first part  
of a project that includes further canine training at a cost of $2 
million, said the source, who spoke on condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	The army planted about 135,000 land mines, mostly along  
Nicaragua's northern border with Honduras, during the 1980s civil 
war to try to prevent U.S.-supported Contra rebels from crossing 
over. 
</P>
<P>
	Many of the mines have been deactivated during the past five  
years with the assistance of the Organization of American States, 
as well as European and Latin American governments. But experts 
believe about 70,000 mines have not been defused. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- The Mexico City government and the federal  
government have signed an agreement to put more money toward 
anti-crime programs, local media reported Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	As part of the agreement, the federal government will provide  
$49 million for new prisons, better police training, a more 
sophisticated computer system and better telecommunications 
systems. 
</P>
<P>
	Anti-crime efforts in the nation's capital had been stymied  
since opposition Mayor Cuauhtemoc Cardenas' landslide election in 
1997, when the federal government reduced funding to cities. 
</P>
<P>
	In recent weeks, a popular television entertainer was killed in  
a gang-style execution, and two members of President Ernesto 
Zedillo's elite presidential guard were gunned down during a street 
robbery. 
</P>
<P>
	Mexico is also putting almost 5,000 military policemen into its  
new civilian federal police force. 
</P>
<P>
	----	 
</P>
<P>
	LIMA, Peru (AP) -- Peru on Thursday passed a law that effectively  
blocks exiled former President Alan Garcia from running for a 
legislative seat in next year's general elections. 
</P>
<P>
	A new law approved by Congress prohibits Peruvians who face  
pending court cases from running for public office. A prior law 
only blocked those convicted of crimes from running. 
</P>
<P>
	Garcia, 50, governed Peru from 1985 to 1990, leaving the economy  
in shambles with annual inflation topping 7,000 percent and a wave 
of car bombs by leftist rebels that rocked the capital, Lima. 
</P>
<P>
	He was later charged with corruption while in office and fled  
Peru in 1992. He was declared a fugitive from justice by a Peruvian 
court in 1996 and an arrest warrant is still pending in Peru. 
</P>
<P>
	Garcia lives in Paris. He has said he wants to return to  
Peruvian politics. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
