<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bonds Up; 30-Yr. Yield Under 6 Pct. / Bonds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Treasury prices rose sharply Thursday, nudging  
the yield on the bellwether 30-year bond back below 6 percent, 
after a smaller-than-expected sale of corporate bonds buoyed demand 
for U.S. securities. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the 30-year Treasury bond rose 23/32 point, or  
$7.19 per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves in the 
opposite direction, fell to 5.99 percent from Wednesday's 6.04 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Bond prices headed lower earlier this week as investors braced  
for a slew of corporate bond sales, expecting up to $7.5 billion in 
bonds from Ford Motor Co. and its financing unit. Demand for 
corporate bonds tends to lower demand for government bonds because 
corporate offerings generally have higher yields. 
</P>
<P>
	But Ford sold only $6.5 billion in bonds on Thursday, spurring  
some investors to buy U.S. Treasury securities instead. 
</P>
<P>
	Also helping bond prices was a rebound in bonds on the European  
market, which opens before the U.S. market. 
</P>
<P>
	In the broader Treasury market, prices of short-term securities  
rose 3/32 point to 1/8 point, and intermediate maturities rose 9/32 
point to 13/32 point, reported Bridge Telerate. 
</P>
<P>
	In other trading, yields on three-month Treasury bills rose to  
4.65 percent while the discount rose 0.01 percentage point to 4.53 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Six-month yields rose to 4.71 percent, as the discount rose 0.01  
percentage point to 4.54 percent. One-year yields fell to 4.98 
percent as the discount fell 0.02 percentage point to 4.74 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the  
discount is the interest at which they are sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between  
banks, was unchanged at 4.94 percent from late Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively  
traded municipal bonds rose 7/32 point to 118 3/4. The average yield 
to maturity fell to 5.54 percent from 5.55 percent late Wednesday. 



</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
