<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Northwestern Coach Remembered </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EVANSTON, Ill. (AP) -- Three days before he was gunned down in  
front of two of his children, former Northwestern University 
basketball coach Ricky Byrdsong talked with his minister about 
violence in society. 
</P>
<P>
	``He said, 'I would hate to live in a neighborhood where you'd  
have to worry about being killed,''' Pastor Lyle Q. Foster told 
more than 1,600 mourners who gathered Wednesday to remember 
Byrdsong. 
</P>
<P>
	Byrdsong, who was 43, was shot last Friday near his home in  
suburban Skokie. Authorities said he was killed by white 
supremacist Benjamin Nathaniel Smith, whose two-state shooting 
rampage left another man dead and nine wounded. 
</P>
<P>
	Mourners -- family, friends, neighbors and others whose lives  
were touched by Byrdsong -- squeezed into the First Presbyterian 
Church sanctuary or sat outside and listened to the service on 
loudspeakers as Byrdsong was remembered as a devoted family man who 
inspired others. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our coach, he's gone,'' said Pastor Hamon Cross of Rosedale  
Park Baptist Church in Detroit. ``But the game is not over. Evil 
will not win.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said Byrdsong's tragic death should inspire others to fight  
hatred and racial intolerance. 
</P>
<P>
	Some said they were drawn to the service by outrage over the  
circumstances of Byrdsong's death. 
</P>
<P>
	Evanston resident Kathleen Murphy stood outside the church with  
a sign that read, ``Stop the Violence Please'' in English, Japanese 
and Chinese. 
</P>
<P>
	``I put a message on the World Wide Web asking for translations  
and within hours I got response from Russia, Israel, California and 
Australia,'' Murphy said. ``This tragedy meant something to people 
all over the world.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Among the mourners were several Orthodox Jews, who traveled to  
Evanston by bus. Authorities said Smith began his attacks by 
wounding six Orthodox Jews in the Chicago community of Rogers Park. 
</P>
<P>
	``We think it was important to come,'' said Harlan Loeb, a civil  
rights lawyer with the Anti-Defamation League. ``I'm here, in part, 
become some of the people shot at were my friends. But we all are 
here because we have deep sympathies for Ricky's wife and 
children.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mourners who came from across the country testified to the fact  
that the former coach's reach far exceeded the boundaries of the 
basketball court, said Pastor Tom Nesbitt from Life Action Ministry 
in Buchanan, Mich. 
</P>
<P>
	``Forget the court. Forget the playing field. Ricky, you were an  
impact player in life,'' Nesbitt said. 
</P>
<P>
	Current and former basketball players, coaches and athletic  
directors -- including Big Ten Commissioner Jim Delany, University 
of Arizona basketball coach Lute Olsen and NBA players Steve Kerr 
and B.J. Armstrong -- were in attendance. Kerr and Armstrong also 
were pallbearers. 
</P>
<P>
	Arnold Webber, the former Northwestern University president who  
hired Byrdsong, recalled Byrdsong enthusiastically discussing his 
plan to work with youths in the community. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of coaches would say that, but Ricky meant it,'' Webber  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	And Foster pledged to complete one of Byrdsong's unfinished  
projects, a book titled ``Coaching Your Kids in the Game of Life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Isaiah McKinnon, a professor at the University of Detroit who  
served on the committee that hired Byrdsong to coach at that school 
in 1988, recalls informing Byrdsong of his father's death after the 
job interview. 
</P>
<P>
	``He had such dignity and composure at such a terrible time,''  
he said. ``I knew we did the right thing in hiring him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Byrdsong went from Detroit to Northwestern, where he took the  
Wildcats to only their second postseason basketball appearance in 
school history. 
</P>
<P>
	He compiled an 87-165 overall record as a head coach, including  
34-78 in four seasons at Northwestern. He was fired with seven 
games left in the 1996-97 season, effective at the end of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	Byrdsong, who was working for an insurance company, is survived  
by his wife, Sherialyn, and three children. His body will be 
transported to his hometown of Atlanta for services and burial, 
scheduled for Saturday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
