<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Steel Co. Faulte U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japan's largest steel company today criticized a  
U.S. International Trade Commission ruling that Japanese companies 
have dumped stainless steel products in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Nippon Steel Corp., which often acts on behalf of the nation's  
steel industry, called the decision ``extremely regrettable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The company said it had offered its maximum cooperation in the  
ITC's investigation by submitting detailed data, including domestic 
production costs. 
</P>
<P>
	In its final ruling, issued Wednesday, the ITC found that  
stainless steel imports from Japan and seven other nations had 
substantially hurt the U.S. steel industry. 
</P>
<P>
	An official of Japan's Ministry of International Trade and  
Industry said the ministry will fully assess the contents of the 
ruling papers as to whether the ITC's judgment was appropriate. 
</P>
<P>
	Wednesday's ruling came after the Brazilian and the U.S.  
government struck a deal in a separate case hours before its 
midnight Tuesday deadline. 
</P>
<P>
	Brazil agreed to reduce shipments of a core steel product by  
nearly a third to avoid punitive tariffs from the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	In April, the U.S. Commerce Department declared that Japan had  
illegally dumped hot-rolled carbon steel, a common steel product, 
in U.S. markets at up to 68 percent below the fair value. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, the U.S. industry won tariffs of as much as 67  
percent on Japanese hot-rolled shipments. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. steel industry filed a dumping complaint against  
Japanese competitors after their U.S. sales jumped last year to 2 1/2 
times the 1997 level. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
