<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jobless Claims Fall by 6,000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The number of Americans filing new claims for  
unemployment benefits fell unexpectedly last week, marking the 
second consecutive drop and the lowest level in more than three 
months. 
</P>
<P>
	The Labor Department said today that 294,000 Americans filed new  
claims for jobless benefits for the week ending July 3 -- down by 
6,000 from the previous week. Last week's level was the lowest 
since 289,000 in the week ending March 27. 
</P>
<P>
	Many analysts had expected jobless claims to rise.  
</P>
<P>
	The four-week moving average for claims, which smoothes out  
week-to-week volatility, also was down to 299,000, the lowest level 
since April 3, when they were at 296,500. 
</P>
<P>
	The jobless claims applications are remaining at low levels,  
which analysts say reflects an extremely tight labor market, 
something the Federal Reserve is keeping a watchful eye on. 
</P>
<P>
	Karen Dexter, an economist with Merrill Lynch, said the downward  
trend in jobless benefits claims is ``suggesting that laid-off 
workers are not having a difficult time finding a new job.'' Dexter 
said ``the job market continues to look healthy'' and that 
``jobless claims are likely to be volatile in the coming weeks 
because of the 4th of July holiday and car factory shutdowns.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, the government reported that unemployment for the  
month of June crept up to 4.3 percent and that the nation's 
businesses added 268,000 new jobs to their payrolls. Despite the 
rise in the unemployment rate, the nation's labor picture remains 
remarkably strong, analysts say. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, manufacturing has lost 488,000 jobs since March 1998 to  
the global financial crisis, which has cut into exports and 
increased cheap imports into this country. The rest of the U.S. 
economy, however, has continued to steam ahead, propelled by robust 
consumer spending. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawrence Summers, who is in his first week as treasury  
secretary, said today he feels good about the U.S. economy. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we can keep our fundamentals strong and continue the  
terrific productivity improvement, I think we have got room to give 
people wage increases that run ahead of price increases and 
represent really higher standards of living,'' Summers said on 
NBC's ``Today.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Labor Department said that for the week ending June 26, 29  
states and territories reported declines in jobless claims, while 
24 had increases. The state data lag a week behind the national 
figures. 
</P>
<P>
	The state with the biggest decline in applications for jobless  
benefits was Pennsylvania, down 3,844, a decrease officials 
attributed to fewer layoffs in the transportation, textile, trade 
and scientific instruments industries. 
</P>
<P>
	Other states with large decreases were: Illinois, down 2,349;  
Wisconsin, down 1,334; Ohio, down 1,242; and Alabama, down 1,232. 
</P>
<P>
	The state with the biggest increase in claims for the week  
ending June 26 was New Jersey, up 2,761, an increase officials 
blamed on layoffs in the construction, trade and service 
industries. Other states with big increases were: Massachusetts, up 
2,239; Kentucky, up 1,545; Connecticut, up 1,436; and New York, up 
1,288. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
