<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jackson Espouses Triangle Offense </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONG BEACH, Calif. (AP) -- Their confused looks said it all: some  
of the Los Angeles Lakers just don't get Phil Jackson's triangle 
offense. 
</P>
<P>
	Of course, they've had only three practices under their new  
coach and most of the team is still on vacation. But the four 
Lakers from last season who showed up Thursday for Summer Pro 
League practice were befuddled. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not so much an offense as it's just a philosophy about  
basketball,'' said fourth-year pro Travis Knight, sounding like 
he's picked up the Zenmaster's lingo. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a philosophy about how the game is supposed to be played.  
I like it,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	That doesn't mean Knight understands, however.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's going to take a while to adjust to,'' he said. ``I'm  
having a hard time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson isn't completely used to his new team, either.  
</P>
<P>
	Telling onlookers what they could expect this fall, the word  
Chicago slipped out of Jackson's mouth. ``Uh, the Lakers, excuse 
me,'' he said as the crowd laughed. 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson was the most popular draw on the first day of the summer  
league that will feature entries from 12 NBA teams, including the 
Lakers, Clippers, Boston, Cleveland, Dallas, Milwaukee Orlando and 
Seattle. 
</P>
<P>
	The coach who guided the Chicago Bulls to six NBA titles in  
eight years has been labeled a savior for a Los Angeles team that 
hasn't been in the NBA Finals since 1991 and was swept out of the 
playoffs the past two seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson doesn't quite see himself that way.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's a matter of hopefully being the catalyst that can kind of  
grease the machinery that makes this run smoothly,'' he said. 
``It's just a leadership role I hope I can perform and fill that 
void for these players.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Whether Scottie Pippen comes from Houston to rejoin his former  
coach is up in the air. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think Scottie would be interested in coming here,'' Jackson  
said. ``Houston has expressed no interest and right now we don't 
have a situation that could work.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Knight would welcome Pippen, a veteran of the triangle offense.  
</P>
<P>
	``It would help a lot,'' Knight said. ``There's a lot of times  
when the coach can't see and tell everybody what to do. If you 
don't know what's going on, somebody can say, `Hey get over 
there.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Besides Knight, Tyronn Lue, Reuben Patterson and Sam Jacobson  
are also giving up part of their summer vacations to learn 
Jackson's system. Shaquille O'Neal, Kobe Bryant and Glen Rice won't 
get a taste of the triangle until training camp in October. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're going to have to open their minds,'' Knight said.  
``It's difficult to learn the whole concept. There's no stops, it's 
all kind of moving, moving, moving.'' 
</P>
<P>
	John Celestand of Villanova, the Lakers' second-round draft pick  
and 30th overall, admitted he didn't have a clue about the 
triangle. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a mystery and only Phil knows,'' he said. ``There's no  
set plays. You have to read your teammates and feed off them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The offense may be a puzzle, but one thing is clear: the  
individual play that defined the Lakers last season won't be 
tolerated anymore. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're trying to get across to the players how much awareness  
it takes all the time to be part of this team,'' Jackson said. 
``You've got to constantly be aware of what you're doing, you don't 
just go through the motions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While acquiring Pippen hasn't been ruled out, don't expect  
Dennis Rodman to reappear in a Lakers uniform. 
</P>
<P>
	``Unless it's absolutely necessary for us to fill a position  
that this team has a weakness in, Dennis Rodman will not be our 
first choice,'' Jackson said. 
</P>
<P>
	There's been one reunion between Jackson and a Chicago cohort.  
Jim Cleamons, who won four NBA titles as a Bulls assistant, is 
already on board and will oversee the Lakers' summer league team. 
Jackson may still hire his other two Chicago assistants, Jimmy 
Rodgers and Tex Winter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
