<HEADLINE> Religion Briefs / Religion Briefs  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Women held 46.6 percent of the  
professional-level staff positions in Catholic dioceses in 1998, up 
from 44.5 percent in 1995, according to a survey. 
</P>
<P>
	That figure is comparable to percentages for the overall job  
market. The U.S. Bureau of Labor Statistics says women filled 44.4 
percent of executive, administrative and managerial positions as of 
1998. 
</P>
<P>
	The survey, commissioned by the U.S. bishops' Committee on Women  
in Society and the Church, found that women held 26 percent of 
top-rank positions, mostly department heads reporting directly to a 
bishop, up from 23.5 percent in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	Though the Catholic church does not ordain women, the committee  
has urged dioceses to consider appointing more women to the church 
staff leadership. 
</P>
<P>
	Larger dioceses, of 350,000 members or more, consistently  
employed fewer women executives than smaller dioceses, the report 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
 *Methabapterians? Say what?    	
</P>
<P>
	BENTON, Ala. (AP) -- Every Sunday, a couple of Methodist altos, a  
Baptist choir director and a Presbyterian pianist join in song. 
They call themselves the Methabapterians. 
</P>
<P>
	Their churches, Benton Baptist, Benton Methodist and Good Hope  
Presbyterian, should be called miracle workers. For all have 
sanctuaries in or near this town of 48 souls. But with so few 
worshippers, they have shared Sunday services, and choirs, for 
nearly 50 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Benton, about 30 miles west of Montgomery, was a thriving  
Alabama River town in the 19th century. But as nearby Montgomery 
and Selma grew, Benton, which had a tendency to flood, did not. 
</P>
<P>
	Mayor Donny Cooper, 51, joined Good Hope 28 years ago and easily  
adapted to sharing services. ``There's so much more that we agree 
on,'' he said. ``Our differences we tend to overlook.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Judy Spivey, 54, said she had never set foot inside a  
Presbyterian church until she married into Benton Methodist. 
</P>
<P>
	``It makes you realize that church is more about support than  
individual doctrines, at least it has for me,'' she said. ``God is 
God is God.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
 *Church rocks, neighbors riled    	
</P>
<P>
	DAPHNE, Ala. (AP) -- The noise at Bay Community Church got a  
little too joyful. 
</P>
<P>
	After several verbal warnings, the church was handed a $166  
ticket for violating the city's noise code. Now, church supporters 
say the ordinance is unconstitutional. 
</P>
<P>
	During a June 23 church service, a Daphne police officer  
measured the noise with a digital decibel meter and wrote a ticket. 
The noise registered 83 decibels, 13 over the limit for that time 
of day. 
</P>
<P>
	Stuart J. Roth, chairman of the American Center for Law and  
Justice of Alabama, says the year-old ordinance violates free 
speech and religious rights of church members because it exempts 
noise made by educational, recreational and construction 
activities. 
</P>
<P>
	City Attorney Manley Cummins defended the ordinance.  
</P>
<P>
	Responding to neighbors' complaints, the 200-member congregation  
has toned down its music, which at the youth services include 
Christian rock. Taylor said they also are soundproofing the rented 
brick and metal building. 
</P>
<P>
	After receiving the ticket, pastor Jerry Taylor promised to ``do  
what we have to do to make it right.'' He said he contacted Roth 
because ``I wanted to make sure the way it was handled and the 
ordinance itself was on the up-and-up and fair.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
 *Repenting slavery    	
</P>
<P>
	PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) -- In 1636, an area now known as Rhode  
Island became a place of refuge for the religiously oppressed. But 
in the 18th century, its ports accommodated slave trading. No 
colony in New England had such a high proportion of slaves as Rhode 
Island. 
</P>
<P>
	In an act of repentence, the United Church of Christ dedicated  
an 80-pound cast iron ``bell of freedom.'' The bell is in Abbott 
Park, next to the Beneficent Congregational Church, which was part 
of the Underground Railroad that helped slaves in their escape to 
freedom. 
</P>
<P>
	The ceremony took place on the fifth day of the national  
convention of the United Church of Christ, a liberal-minded church 
with an antislavery heritage. 
</P>
<P>
	By 1760, Rhode Island had 184 vessels running between New  
England and the West Indies on the triangular trade route. The 
first leg was made by merchants selling rum to West Africa in 
exchange for slaves to be sold in the Caribbean. Then molasses and 
sugar from the Caribbean would be brought to New England. 
</P>
<P>
	``Americans were only minor players in the whole slave trade,  
but Rhode Islanders were the principal American slave traders,'' 
said Stanley Lemons, a history professor at Rhode Island College. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
