<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-NIH Director To Head Red Cross </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Dr. Bernadine Healy was named Thursday to head  
the American Red Cross, filling the position Elizabeth Dole quit to 
pursue presidential aspirations. 
</P>
<P>
	Healy, a heart specialist who will be the first physician to  
head the 118-year-old organization, also has harbored political 
hopes, trying in 1994 to win the Republican Party's Senate 
nomination in Ohio. 
</P>
<P>
	A former head of the National Institutes of Health, she is now  
dean of the Ohio State University College of Medicine and Public 
Health. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, Norman Augustine, chairman of the Red Cross Board  
of Governors, praised her record in government and academia and as 
a fund-raiser at Ohio State -- valuable experience for an 
organization that spends $2 billion a year and relies on 
contributions for more than 30 percent of its operating revenue. 
</P>
<P>
	She will take over the Red Cross full-time in September.  
</P>
<P>
	At a brief news conference on the grounds of Red Cross  
headquarters, Healy said she was entering the job as ``a humble 
steward'' of ``one of the most effective public health institutions 
in the world.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That was a sharp change from her introduction as head of the  
National Institutes of Health, a position she took in 1991. The NIH 
needed structure, unlike the Red Cross, which already runs well and 
has effective mission plans, she said. ``My role is to make sure 
that we see those plans executed,'' she added. 
</P>
<P>
	Her future staff applauded.  
</P>
<P>
	Healy, 54, looked relaxed and fit, showing no sign of the brain  
surgery she underwent in February to remove a cancerous tumor. 
</P>
<P>
	She was a controversial figure at NIH, where her tenure was  
marked by internal struggles and battles with Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	At one point, Rep. John Dingell, D-Mich., accused Healy of  
interfering with investigations of two NIH scientists accused of 
research fraud, and she countered with complaints about the 
investigators' lack of due process. An NIH investigator quit during 
that period, complaining of pressure from Healy -- an allegation she 
said was ``baloney.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Other fights with Congress involved Bush administration policy,  
notably a ban on using aborted fetuses for tissue transplantation 
research and a decision to test a powerful drug with potentially 
dangerous side effects on thousands of healthy women. 
</P>
<P>
	Several prominent Democrats in Congress favored fetal tissue  
research and opposed the clinical trial of tamoxifen. 
</P>
<P>
	On the latter subject, Healy expressed a sense of vindication  
Thursday. ``Millions of American women are benefiting as a result 
of that trial,'' she said. Tamoxifen was approved last year as a 
way for women at very high risk to lower their chances of getting 
breast cancer later in life. 
</P>
<P>
	``I always try not to be strident but I do try to be forceful  
about things that are right,'' Healy said. 
</P>
<P>
	Healy's record at NIH also included the beginning of a $625  
million women's health initiative, a 14-year study of diseases in 
women as they age that involved a major shift of attention and 
resources. 
</P>
<P>
	Born in New York City, Healy earned her bachelor's degree from  
Vassar College in 1965 and medical degree from the Harvard School 
of Medicine in 1970. 
</P>
<P>
	She completed postgraduate work at the Johns Hopkins University  
School of Medicine and was a member of the Hopkins faculty from 
1976 to 1984. She worked in the Reagan White House and headed the 
Cleveland Clinic Foundation's research institute before running NIH 
for the Bush administration. 
</P>
<P>
	Healy is the mother of two daughters. Her husband, Dr. Floyd  
Loop, is chief executive officer of the Cleveland Clinic. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
