<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Plan: No Fed Contracts to Violators </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Strong evidence that companies aren't  
complying with labor, tax, environmental or consumer protection 
laws could be enough to bar them from doing business with the 
federal government under a long-awaited Clinton administration 
proposal. 
</P>
<P>
	Government contractors also could not charge taxpayers for the  
cost of activities intended to influence whether workers join labor 
unions or for some legal costs under the proposed regulations. 
</P>
<P>
	The new rules would clarify ``the existing principle that the  
federal government should not enter into contracts with contractors 
who do not comply with the law,'' according to a copy the 
administration proposal obtained by The Associated Press. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposed rules were expected to appear in Friday's Federal  
Register, opening a period of public comment. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, business groups were already condemning the new  
rules as politically motivated ``blacklisting'' designed to please 
labor unions. 
</P>
<P>
	``By seeking to politicize federal procurement, the  
administration is putting the political agenda of the unions ahead 
of the interests of the nation,'' said Thomas J. Donohue, the U.S. 
Chamber of Commerce's president and CEO. ``The chamber is dedicated 
to defeating blacklisting.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Clinton administration denied having political motivations.  
</P>
<P>
	``The overarching principle behind this proposal is that it  
makes good sense for the American government to do business with 
good citizens who comply with the law,'' replied Linda Ricci, 
spokeswoman for the Office of Management and Budget. 
</P>
<P>
	Union officials offered praise.  
</P>
<P>
	``These strike us as good and sensible reforms,'' said Lynn  
Rhinehart, associate general council for the AFL-CIO. ``They seem 
to be reinforcing the notion that the government isn't going to be 
doing business with chronic lawbreakers and that seems like perfect 
common sense to us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Vice President Al Gore first promised the new government  
contracting rules to labor leaders in February 1997 in a speech at 
an AFL-CIO meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you want to do business with the federal government you had  
better maintain a safe workplace and respect civil, human and union 
rights,'' Gore said at the time. 
</P>
<P>
	But little on the subject has been heard from the administration  
since the spring of 1997, when Republican senators, including 
Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., threatened to hold up 
confirmation of Labor Secretary Alexis Herman because of their 
objections to the proposed contracting standards. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration proposal has resurfaced as Gore is trying to  
woo labor unions to support his bid for the Democratic Party's 2000 
presidential nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the administration documents, the proposal the  
White House ultimately settled on would go beyond the scope of 
federal contractors' compliance with labor laws. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, the new rules would elaborate more generally on  
existing regulations that simply require federal contractors to 
have ``a satisfactory record of integrity and business ethics.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to labor laws, that standard would explicitly apply  
to a companies' record of compliance with employment discrimination 
laws, tax laws, environmental laws, antitrust laws and consumer 
protections laws. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposed rules would allow the government to take into  
account not only confirmed wrongdoing by a company, such as court 
convictions, but also ``persuasive evidence of substantial 
noncompliance with a law or regulation,'' when awarding contracts. 
</P>
<P>
	Such evidence could not be ``isolated or trivial'' but would  
have to show ``repeated and substantial violations establishing a 
pattern or practice by a prospective contractor,'' in order to 
affect the companies chances of winning contracts. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal contractors also could no longer bill the government for  
any expenses associated with activities intended to influence 
workers' decisions to unionize, such as hiring legal consultants or 
printing pamphlets. Expenses associated with maintaining good labor 
relations, such as hiring shop stewards or printing employee 
newsletters would be allowed, however. 
</P>
<P>
	Finally, contractors could not charge the government for their  
legal fees in cases in which federal regulatory agencies, such as 
the National Labor Relations Board or the Equal Employment 
Opportunity Commission, find wrongdoing -- even if there is no 
punishment associated with the finding. 
</P>
<P>
	Currently, companies can get their legal fees reimbursed by the  
government unless they have faced punishment such as a criminal 
court sentence or civil fine. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
