<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Retail Sales Better Than Expected </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Most of the nation's biggest retailers reported  
today that their June sales jumped to better-than-expected levels 
as the robust U.S. economy encouraged Americans to do lots of 
shopping last month. 
</P>
<P>
	Merchants also benefited from warmer-than-normal weather through  
much of the country, which sent shoppers into stores for everything 
from bathing suits and sundresses to air conditioners and patio 
furniture. 
</P>
<P>
	The strong sales in June followed surprisingly big gains in May,  
giving many Wall Street analysts reason to believe that 
second-quarter earnings will top estimates. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have a very happy consumer who is flush with cash and eager  
to spend,'' said Thomas Tashjian, a retail analyst at Bank of 
America Securities in San Francisco. 
</P>
<P>
	The raging U.S. economy, combined with low unemployment and  
inflation levels has made consumers confident about their personal 
finances and has raised their willingness to spend. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, the stock market is again on a record-setting pace.  
The Dow Jones industrial average and other market indexes reached 
new highs on Wednesday, but retreated this morning. 
</P>
<P>
	Separately today, the Labor Department reported that the number  
of Americans filing new claims for unemployment benefits fell by 
6,000 last week to 294,000, marking the second consecutive drop and 
the lowest level in more than three months. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is a very favorable environment out there and the  
consumer is still feeling very strong,'' said Jeffrey Feiner, 
managing director at Lehman Brothers Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	The big winners in June were the discount chains, as shoppers  
turned to stores like Wal-Mart, Target and Kmart for their wide 
selection and affordable prices. 
</P>
<P>
	Also faring well were specialty clothing chains, such as the  
Limited and the Gap, and the department stores, which lured 
shoppers with seasonal fashions, like capri pants and tank tops. 
</P>
<P>
	Consumer electronics retailers, such as Circuit City, reported  
healthy gains as shoppers flocked to their stores to buy cheap 
computers, digital video-disc players, air conditioners and fans. 
</P>
<P>
	While the weather and the strong economy were mostly responsible  
for the sales gains, retailers also benefited last month from the 
late Memorial Day holiday, which fell on May 31. Most retailers 
began their fiscal month on May 29 or 30, which meant that much of 
the buying over the holiday weekend was included in June's sales 
figures. Last year, Memorial Day was counted in May. 
</P>
<P>
	With sales in the last few months topping estimates, retailers  
haven't had to slash prices on merchandise to move out seasonal 
products and clear store shelves. Analysts expect that will result 
in strong second-quarter earnings, which most retailers will report 
in early August. 
</P>
<P>
	``Second-quarter earnings will reflect the good sales  
performance at full price, and I don't think this party is going to 
end anytime soon,'' said Kurt Barnard, president of the newsletter 
Barnard's Retail Trend Report in Upper Montclair, N.J. ``We do not 
foresee a major downturn of any kind for the rest of the year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While the retail industry overall did well in June, there were  
some chains that struggled. The mid-priced department stores, such 
as J.C. Penney, continued to lose business to the discount chains. 
Stores that specialize in athletic sportswear and footwear, such as 
Sports Authority, also reported weak sales amid a prolonged 
downturn in demand for such products. 
</P>
<P>
	The Merrill Lynch retail index, the investment firm's barometer  
of sales performance at department stores and discount chains, was 
up 6.3 percent in June. It rose 5.4 percent in May and 6.4 percent 
in June 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Wal-Mart, the nation's largest retailer, reported that sales  
from stores open at least a year rose 6.5 percent from a year 
earlier, while total sales rose 13.6 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales from stores open at least a year, known as same-store  
sales, are considered the most accurate measure of a retailer's 
strength.	   Other retailers' reports: 
</P>
<P>
	--Sears: Same-store sales rose 1.9 percent, total sales down 3.1  
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	--Kmart: Same-store sales up 9.2 percent, total sales up 11.3  
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	--J.C. Penney: Same-store department store sales fell 2.3  
percent, same-store sales at Eckerd drugstores rose 10.3 percent, 
total sales rose 6.6 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	--Dayton Hudson: Same-store sales rose 6.9 percent, total sales  
up 11.6 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	--Federated: Same-store sales rose 8.4 percent, total sales up  
18.5 percent. Federated's total sales included revenues from the 
Internet and catalog seller Fingerhut, which it acquired in March. 
</P>
<P>
	--May Department Stores: Same-store sales up 8.4 percent, total  
sales up 12.9 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	--Limited: Same-store sales up 11 percent, total sales were up 11  
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	--Gap: Same-store sales up 13 percent, total sales up 35 percent.  
</P>
<P>
	--Ann Taylor: Same-store sales up 7.7 percent, total sales up  
18.7 percent. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
