<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cavaliers Hire Wittman As New Coach </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- Randy Wittman has seen the NBA for 16 years as  
a player and an assistant coach, and, frankly, he thinks the league 
needs more zip. 
</P>
<P>
	That's just what the Cleveland Cavaliers wanted to hear, so they  
hired the Minnesota Timberwolves assistant Wednesday as their new 
head coach, even though he's never held the top job before. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to stress the game needs to have more life put into  
it,'' Wittman said as he was introduced at Gund Arena. ``I think we 
need as coaches to look in the mirror a little bit and allow our 
players to play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Cavs have been searching for someone who will bring a spark  
and a more open style to their franchise after six seasons under 
former coach Mike Fratello, who was fired June 1. 
</P>
<P>
	Fratello's teams were often injury-plagued, and he was credited  
with making the most of bad situations by installing a clock-eating 
offense and tough defense. But fans got tired of watching the 
grind-it-out style, even if it meant a few more wins than losses. 
</P>
<P>
	Average game attendance dropped from 18,011 in 1994-95 to 14,120  
last season and the Cavs' postseason performances have been weak in 
recent years. Cleveland hasn't made it out of the first round of 
the playoffs since 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	Wittman's plan for bringing fans back is as simple as putting  
together a team that has a good time on the court. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to instill in them what it takes to work hard, the  
dedication to get there. But I want them -- when they cross the 
sideline -- to have fun,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think if you can put a product on the floor that people are  
entertained with, wins and losses will take care of themselves.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cavs center Zydrunas Ilgauskas, one of a few players who watched  
as Wittman was introduced during a news conference, liked what he 
heard. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's exciting to see a new guy with new ideas come in here.  
He's got the whole team behind him,'' Ilgauskas said. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite never holding a head coaching position, the 39-year-old  
Wittman comes to Cleveland with some strong credentials. 
</P>
<P>
	He played on Indiana's 1981 NCAA championship team and was a  
two-time academic All-American with the Hoosiers. Indiana coach Bob 
Knight on Wednesday called Wittman one of the smartest players he 
ever coached. 
</P>
<P>
	``For a player, he had a rare understanding of just what it  
takes to win and how to go about it,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Wittman was a first-round draft pick of the Washington Bullets,  
but was traded to the Atlanta Hawks before the 1983-84 season and 
played under Fratello there. He also played for Sacramento and 
Indiana and finished his nine-year NBA career averaging 7.4 points 
per game. 
</P>
<P>
	He has spent the last five years as an assistant coach at  
Minnesota and also had one-year stints in Dallas and Indiana. 
</P>
<P>
	Cleveland general manager Jim Paxson, who headed the coaching  
search, said he recommended Wittman to Cavs owner Gordon Gund 
because ``he is the coach who will be most flexible and adaptable 
with respect to both players and the NBA game as it continues to 
evolve.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Others with head coaching experience might be viewed by some  
as safer choices,'' he said. ``For us, Randy Wittman is the right 
choice.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Paxson would not disclose the length of Wittman's contract or  
how much he'll be paid. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cavs were secretive about their coaching search until  
Wittman was introduced. Despite plans to create some excitement 
surrounding the team, the Cavs refused to reveal the names of any 
potential coaching candidates. 
</P>
<P>
	When Wittman arrived in Cleveland on Wednesday, the Cavs sent a  
limousine to meet his plane, so he avoided reporters and fans at 
the flight gate. 
</P>
<P>
	Dave Cowens, Del Harris and John MacLeod also interviewed for  
the Cavs job. 
</P>
<P>
	The hiring of Wittman is part of a continuing makeover of the  
Cavaliers organization in which well-known names are being replaced 
by a younger group. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to the firing of Fratello, known as the ``Czar of  
Telestrator'' for his television commentary work, newly elected 
Hall of Famer Wayne Embry has stepped aside as general manager in 
favor of Paxson. 
</P>
<P>
	And last week's draft saw the Cavs make two other moves which  
could change their look on the court. 
</P>
<P>
	Unable to trade up in the first round to get Miami of Ohio's  
Wally Szczerbiak, Cleveland took Utah point Andre Miller and Duke 
guard Trajan Langdon -- a pair who could potentially challenge 
Brevin Knight and Derek Anderson for their jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	Minnesota wound up with Szczerbiak and the two players Wittman  
thought the Timberwolves would get in the first round -- Miller and 
Langdon -- went to the Cavs. Wittman said he's ``ecstatic'' with 
Cleveland's draft choices. 
</P>
<P>
	Paxson was simultaneously preparing for the draft as he looked  
for a coach. He recommended Wittman to Gund just before the draft, 
and the former assistant met with Gund last Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Gund said he was impressed with Wittman's straightforward manner  
and potential as a teacher. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are absolutely, positively certain we ended up with the  
best choice,'' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
