<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Relies on Former Warsaw Pact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- When NATO decided to stop Russia from  
reinforcing its peacekeepers in Kosovo last weekend, it turned to 
former Warsaw Pact foes Hungary, Romania and Bulgaria to block the 
flights. 
</P>
<P>
	In the latest irony of the post-Cold War world, the Western  
alliance is relying on the cooperation of former East European 
adversaries to help shore up its defenses against Balkan unrest in 
the wake of the Kosovo crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	Within months, nearly 100,000 NATO troops will be based in  
former Communist-ruled territory in Bosnia, Kosovo, Macedonia, and 
Albania, supporting peacekeeping operations in Kosovo and Bosnia. 
</P>
<P>
	After training for decades to stop a Soviet invasion of Western  
Europe, NATO faced an identity crisis after the Iron Curtain came 
down in the late 1980s. 
</P>
<P>
	In a fundamental redefinition of its role, NATO has adopted a  
more flexible stance, cooperating with its former adversaries to 
try to quell ethnic uprisings and bloodbaths in the Balkans. 
</P>
<P>
	Now it is NATO that is deploying to the east and absorbing its  
former enemies. 
</P>
<P>
	Hungary is a new member of NATO, having been officially admitted  
in April with Poland and the Czech Republic. Bulgaria and Romania 
are eager to join the alliance, along with Slovenia, when 
membership is reopened in 2001 or 2002. 
</P>
<P>
	Even Russia has a voice in NATO, through the Permanent Joint  
Council set up to liaise with Moscow on European security matters. 
But friction remains along the old East-West divide. 
</P>
<P>
	In Kosovo, Moscow is insisting the 3,600 peacekeeping troops it  
will send must be under Russian command, coordinated through the 
Permanent Joint Council. 
</P>
<P>
	In a throwback to Cold War tactics, Russia tried to create  
``facts on the ground'' in June when it sent 200 paratroopers from 
the Bosnian peacekeeping force to seize the airport at Kosovo's 
capital, Pristina, ahead of NATO troops. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russian move stunned NATO, which was mobilizing its own  
troops to enter Kosovo in the wake of a peace accord with Yugoslav 
President Slobodan Milosevic -- who agreed after an 11-week NATO 
bombing campaign to withdraw his forces from the southern Serbian 
province. 
</P>
<P>
	But after having played a key negotiating role in assuring the  
withdrawal of Serb forces, Moscow wanted to be sure it was deeply 
involved in the peacekeeping force, partly to reassure the Serbs, 
who are Slavs like the Russians. 
</P>
<P>
	Tensions heightened last week when Russia sent two Soviet-era  
Tupelov-95 Bear bombers on a flight toward Iceland. NATO planes 
escorted them out of Iceland's airspace. 
</P>
<P>
	The feint seemed intended to underline Russian ambitions to show  
it is still a near-superpower. 
</P>
<P>
	Moscow also expelled an American military attache from the U.S.  
Embassy last week, implying he was a spy. 
</P>
<P>
	It was against this background of confrontational behavior that  
NATO had to decide what to do when Russia decided it was going to 
fly hundreds more paratroopers to Pristina airport over the 
weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	Talks between NATO and Russian officers last week in Mons,  
Belgium, had failed to resolve outstanding questions on who would 
command the Russians and exactly where they would be stationed. The 
Russians sought to expand into the Italian-patrolled sector of 
Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO decided to ground the Russian flights by asking Hungary,  
Romania and Bulgaria to deny Moscow the right to cross their 
airspace to get to Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	Urgent new talks in Moscow on Monday resolved the differences  
over Russia's Kosovo deployment, and the flights to Pristina 
resumed Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Reliance on the former East European foes is just the latest  
elaboration of the southern and eastern strategic thrust of NATO. 
</P>
<P>
	Another example was apparent during the bombing phase of the  
Kosovo crisis. Advance NATO units were deployed in Albania and 
Macedonia as a forward staging area for the current peacekeeping 
mission. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
