<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Consumer Borrowing Rises Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Americans' rate of borrowing rose sharply in  
May -- the largest increase since January -- reflecting strong demand 
for loans for everything from autos, boats and mobile homes, to 
education and vacations. 
</P>
<P>
	Consumers' credit outstanding, excluding mortgage debt, advanced  
at a hefty 10.9 percent annual rate in May to a seasonally adjusted 
$1.34 trillion, the Federal Reserve said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The increase in May's rate follows much smaller gains in April  
and March and marked the largest increase since January, when 
consumer credit climbed at an annualized rate of 14 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In April, total credit outstanding rose at an annual rate of  
just 0.4 percent, much less than the Fed previously estimated. 
</P>
<P>
	May's increase was led by demand for nonrevolving loans, a  
category that does not include credit cards, which rose at an 
annual rate of 15.7 percent. That category includes loans for 
autos, mobile homes, boats, trailers, education and vacations. It 
was the biggest increase for nonrevolving credit since January, 
when it rose at an annual rate of 17.5 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's been an incredible year for car sales even the industry  
has been kind of surprised by this. That's really what is driving 
consumer credit,'' said analyst Sandra Shaber with the WEFA Group. 
</P>
<P>
	Revolving credit -- primarily credit cards -- also went up in May  
to an annual rate of 4.4 percent. That follows a bigger gain of 5.9 
percent rate in April. 
</P>
<P>
	All told, consumers' borrowed $12.1 billion more in May than  
during the month before, well above many analysts' expectations. 
That, too, was the biggest dollar jump since January, when the 
level of consumer borrowing rose $15.2 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Consumers' robust borrowing is a reflection of a healthy  
economy. The nation's economic growth is being powered by consumer 
spending. At the same time inflation and unemployment are low, 
consumer confidence is high and the stock market is continuing to 
post record gains. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some would wring their hands'' over the upswing in consumer  
credit ``but if you look at consumer borrowing particularly 
relative to the increases in household wealth and in income growth, 
I think that consumers by and large are not acting irresponsible, 
they are responding to really terrific conditions,'' Shaber said. 
</P>
<P>
	Thursday's consumer credit report is the first one in which the  
Fed stopped breaking out automobile loans as a separate category. 
It's also the first report without a separate catchall category 
that lumped loans for things including education, vacations, mobile 
homes and boats. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, these two categories are now folded into one called  
nonrevolving credit. The Fed explained that it was going to a 
larger category because it didn't trust the month-by-month 
reliability of the previous smaller breakdowns. 
</P>
<P>
	In a separate report, most of the nation's largest retailers  
said Thursday that their June sales rose to better-than-expected 
levels. 
</P>
<P>
	Discount chains, such as Wal-Mart, Target and Kmart, reported  
the biggest gains. Specialty clothing stores including the Limited 
and the Gap also fared well as did department stores, which lured 
shoppers with seasonal fashions such as capri pants and tank tops. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
