<P>
	Retail Sales Up; Jobless Claims Off  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The nation's biggest retailers reported  
surprisingly strong sales in June as the robust U.S. economy and 
warm weather sent Americans on a buying bonanza of everything from 
bathing suits to air conditioners. The glowing figures on consumer 
spending were released today as the new treasury secretary said the 
economy appears strong enough to provide wage earners with even 
bigger pay increases without reviving inflation. ``I feel good 
about where the economy is,'' said Treasury Secretary Lawrence 
Summers. Most Americans share his view, and that's helped boost 
retail sales to stunning levels all year. Separately, the Labor 
Department reported today that the number of Americans filing new 
claims for unemployment benefits fell by 6,000 last week to 
294,000, marking the second consecutive drop. 

</P>
<P>
	Consumer Borrowing Rises Sharply  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Americans' rate of borrowing rose sharply in  
May -- the largest increase since January -- reflecting strong demand 
for loans for everything from autos, boats and mobile homes, to 
education and vacations. Consumers' credit outstanding, excluding 
mortgage debt, advanced at a hefty 10.9 percent annual rate in May 
to a seasonally adjusted $1.34 trillion, the Federal Reserve said 
today. The increase in May's rate was the largest since January, 
when consumer credit climbed at an annualized rate of 14 percent. 

</P>
<P>
	GE Profits Rise 15 Percent  
</P>
<P>
	FAIRFIELD, Conn. (AP) -- General Electric reported its  
second-quarter profits rose 15 percent, led by strong performances 
in its aircraft engines, power systems and financial services 
units. The nation's fifth-biggest corporation said today it earned 
$2.82 billion, or 85 cents per share, compared with $2.45 billion, 
or 74 cents per share, in the same period last year. Revenues 
increased 9 percent to $27.41 billion, reflecting growth from 
globalization and product services. GE's results slightly above 
analysts' expectations. GE shares ended at 117 1/16, down 7/8. 

</P>
<P>
	NBC, GE Equity Up ValueVision Stake  
</P>
<P>
	EDEN PRAIRIE, Minn. (AP) -- NBC and GE Equity have doubled their  
stake in ValueVision International Inc. to nearly 40 percent by 
exercising warrants to purchase about $175 million worth of stock 
in the direct marketer. The two companies, both divisions of 
General Electric, already owned a 19.9 percent stake in 
ValueVision. The purchase, announced today, ``is a huge credibility 
boost for ValueVision,'' said Bob Evans, an analyst with 
Craig-Hallum Capital Group in Minneapolis. ValueVision shares were 
at 23 5/16, down 3/4. 

</P>
<P>
	Russell 2000 Kicks Out 375 Cos.  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- After weeks of speculation, the benchmark  
Russell 2000 stock index on today released the list of small 
companies that will make up its roster for the coming year, 
knocking out 375 companies that had grown too large over the past 
12 months. Gone are Ameritrade, E-Trade Group, CMGI, Doubleclick, 
Lycos, RealNetworks and many other sexy Internet companies that 
help drive the Russell 2000's 7.28 percent return in 1999. In their 
place are companies such as 24/7 Media, BarnesandNoble.com, and 
Bebe Stores. 

</P>
<P>
	Oakland Dock Workers End Walkout  
</P>
<P>
	OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) -- Dock workers returned to their jobs today  
after shutting down the Oakland port for two days in the middle of 
contract negotiations. The walkout by 1,400 workers forced 
cargo-laden vessels to slow down across the Pacific Ocean or wait 
at anchor in San Francisco Bay just outside the port, which handles 
12 percent of West Coast shipping. Steve Stallone, a spokesman for 
the International Longshore and Warehouse Union local representing 
the stevedores at Oakland, said talks would resume tomorrow in San 
Francisco with management's Pacific Maritime Association. 

</P>
<P>
	Dell European Chief Steps Down  
</P>
<P>
	AUSTIN (AP) -- Dell Computer Corp.'s top European executive has  
stepped down and will be replaced by Dell's president of 
Asia-Pacific operations, John Legere. The company said yesterday 
that the resignation of Jan Gesmar-Larsen, 39, was due to personal 
reasons. Europe is a critical market for the personal-computer 
maker, and first-quarter sales fell short of company expectations. 
Dell's European revenues grew by 29 percent in the first quarter, 
down from 62 percent in the same quarter last year. 

</P>
<P>
	Online Racial Divide Grows  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The disparity on the Internet between whites  
and black and Hispanic Americans is growing toward a ``racial 
ravine,'' in many cases even after accounting for differences in 
income, a new government report said today. The Commerce 
Department's latest survey showed dramatic gains in the number of 
Americans who own computers and use the Internet. But it also cited 
money, education and whether a person lives in an urban area as key 
factors affecting whether they use technology. 

</P>
