<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	The Southwest suffered monsoon conditions Thursday, pelted by  
showers and thunderstorms that turned streets into rivers and 
stranded motorists on top of their cars in Las Vegas. 
</P>
<P>
	The average annual rainfall in the Las Vegas Valley is 4.1  
inches, but by early afternoon, up to 3 inches had fallen and more 
was expected. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere, a storm created rain in parts of the northern  
Mississippi Valley and the Great Lakes, with showers and 
thunderstorms in Wisconsin, Minnesota and the Chicago area. 
</P>
<P>
	Hot and humid conditions dominated in the central and southern  
Plains, while showers and thunderstorms were widespread across the 
Rockies. 
</P>
<P>
	A few showers and thunderstorms dampened New England, the  
Carolinas and parts of the Gulf Coast, but most of the East 
experienced dry conditions. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pacific Northwest was fair and dry.  
</P>
<P>
	Temperatures in the Lower 48 states ranged from a mid-afternoon  
high of 93 in Needles, Calif., to a morning low of 26 in Stanley, 
Idaho. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
