<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rothschild Collection Could Fetch $40 Million </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Their fortune destroyed by the Nazis during World  
War II, the Austrian arm of the Rothschild clan has placed a 
spectacular collection of art and furnishings on the auction block. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are very few names as big as Rothschild,'' said Alex  
Hope, who organized today's sale for Christie's. ``There will be 
very few collections that will rival this in importance.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 250 paintings, pieces of furniture and decorative objects  
evoke another era -- a time when barons Nathaniel and Albert von 
Rothschild, scions of the Austrian arm of the 250-year-old banking 
dynasty, were the foremost collectors in Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	The fabulous collection they amassed is expected to fetch more  
than $40 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Their descendants are selling the treasures because they no  
longer have opulent homes in which to display the pieces. While the 
Nazis protected the family's art collection, they ruined the 
Rothschilds financially, destroying their factories and 
investments. 
</P>
<P>
	Photographs of Nathaniel Rothschild's home in Vienna, included  
in the auction catalog, demonstrate the dramatic change in the 
family's fortunes since the first half of the century. 
</P>
<P>
	One photo, of the drawing room, shows a painting by the Dutch  
master Franz Hals, ``Portrait of Tieleman Roosterman,'' valued by 
Christie's at $4 million to $5.5 million. 
</P>
<P>
	It was just one of many precious objects in the room, competing  
for attention with lavish furniture and Oriental carpets. 
</P>
<P>
	After the Nazis seized the Rothschilds' property in 1938, the  
art remained hidden, mostly in salt mines, until it was recovered 
by American soldiers after the war. 
</P>
<P>
	The collection then was turned over to the Austrian government,  
which put it on display in the country's museums and libraries. It 
finally agreed to return it to the Rothschild family in February, 
to right what it called an ``immoral'' wrong. 
</P>
<P>
	Hope said only the collection of the Rothschilds' brother,  
Ferdinand -- who worked in the London branch of the family's 
financial houses -- rivals the items on sale at Christie's. 
</P>
<P>
	Together, the three inspired the term ``le gout Rothschild,'' a  
reference to their predilection for works of surpassing quality, 
frequently with a royal connection. 
</P>
<P>
	A wooden commode, or cabinet, that was commissioned by Louis XVI  
and later furnished his private library at Versailles exemplifies 
the Rothschilds' collecting style. It is expected to sell for $2.4 
million to $4 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the other notable items on sale is a Book of Hours made in  
Flanders in the early 16th century. Its red velvet cover is clean 
and soft, and the colors of the 67 full-page illuminations remain 
brilliant. 
</P>
<P>
	The book, expected to fetch $3.3 million to $4.9 million, was  
kept in the National Library of Vienna and rarely displayed. 
</P>
<P>
	The bulk of Ferdinand's collection is on public view at  
Waddesdon Manor in Buckinghamshire, 50 miles northwest of London, 
but the auction could be the last chance for the public to view the 
Austrian treasures. 
</P>
<P>
	Although museums from around the world have shown interest in  
the sale, private buyers are likely to outbid museums for most of 
the pieces, Christie's said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
