<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Trade Group Criticizes IMF Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- The World Gold Council came to the United  
Nations on Thursday to criticize the International Monetary Fund's 
plan to sell part of its gold holdings to help reduce poor 
countries' debt. 
</P>
<P>
	Ghana's mission to the United Nations co-sponsored a press  
conference with the industry trade association to warn that the 
sale would actually hurt the countries it is seeking to help, as 
well as the gold industry in general. 
</P>
<P>
	Ghana is the largest gold producing nation on the IMF's list of  
``Heavily Indebted Poor Countries'' seeking debt relief. 
</P>
<P>
	Leaders of the world's main industrial nations meeting in June  
in Cologne, Germany, gave the go-ahead for the IMF to sell 10 
million ounces of its $27 billion in gold reserves to help finance 
the IMF portion of debt relief for poor countries. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. Congressional approval is required, and already two  
Republican lawmakers have moved to block the sale on the grounds 
that it would hurt many gold-producing nations and the U.S. 
industry. 
</P>
<P>
	The IMF should consider alternative ways of raising money for  
debt relief, such as seeking additional contributions from IMF 
members, said George Milling-Stanley, a gold market analyst at the 
World Gold Council. 
</P>
<P>
	The London-based group has been outspoken in its opposition to  
the plan and to recent gold sales by central banks. 
</P>
<P>
	Milling-Stanley called on IMF Managing Director Michel Camdessus  
to ``bring all his considerable powers of persuasion to bear in 
generating contributions rather than settling for perhaps what 
seemed like an easy answer at the time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Camdessus has acknowledged gold producers and the industry have  
legitimate concerns about the sale but has said the IMF would only 
sell its gold at reasonable prices so as to not drive down the 
market any further. 
</P>
<P>
	International gold prices fell to a 20-year lows in June  
following endorsements of the IMF plan from the United States, 
France and Britain and plans by several central banks to sell the 
precious metal. 
</P>
<P>
	Milling-Stanley said nothing short of a policy reversal by the  
IMF will calm the gold markets and stabilize prices. 
</P>
<P>
	``Selling is what pushes prices down in any market, but negative  
market attitude -- the feeling that the gold price can never rise 
again, which some people in the market have fallen prey to -- is 
what opens the door for speculators to sell short,'' 
Milling-Stanley said. ``That is really what is damaging the 
price.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990708.0309 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 09:50:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Eastern U.S. Finally Cools Off </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- It's finally cooled off across the East, but the  
debate is heating up in New York after 200,000 people endured a 
19-hour blackout during a deadly heat wave that smothered the 
region for three days. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would seem to me that over the years they would develop  
more of a fail-safe system,'' Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said Wednesday 
of Consolidated Edison, which cut power throughout upper Manhattan 
one night earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	Scattered outages continued to plague thousands of people  
Wednesday in mid-Atlantic states and the Northeast. But 
temperatures finally sank below the baking, humid level that 
contributed to at least 25 deaths since last weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	Almost all of the 69,000 customers who lost power in Manhattan  
above 155th Street had their electricity back today, and subway 
service was fully restored in time for this morning's rush hour. 
</P>
<P>
	But Giuliani voiced the frustrations of residents and merchants  
who had slept outside to escape overheated apartments and guard 
their businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	About 500 police officers were deployed in a move designed to  
prevent the widespread looting that happened during a 25-hour 
blackout in 1977. There were nine arrests and only a few stores 
were robbed, though some witnesses described groups of youths 
prowling the neighborhood armed with baseball bats. 
</P>
<P>
	Con Ed didn't have the capability to divert power from any other  
section of the city, and the situation was made worse by 
heat-damaged cables, spokeswoman Toni Yuille said. 
</P>
<P>
	The utility offered partial reimbursement for lost perishables,  
but Giuliani has threatened to sue Con Ed for losses to residents 
and the city. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to lose all the meat,'' said Reso Infante, manager  
of La Mundial specialty meat market in upper Manhattan. The stench 
of spoiled meat wafted from the open freezer door up the rickety 
wooden stairs to the sidewalk. Infante estimated the loss at 
$15,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Rafael Colon threw out about $70 worth of groceries from his  
refrigerator and sent his mother and grandmother to stay with an 
aunt across town. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're on a tight budget as it is, and we didn't need this,''  
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The heat wave started Sunday, bringing temperatures over 100  
degrees and intense humidity to many areas across the Midwest and 
East. 
</P>
<P>
	Farmers also suffered big losses.  
</P>
<P>
	Allen Family Foods Inc. in Delaware lost 33,000 chickens from  
Saturday through Monday, said Tom David, director of live 
operations. The company has more than 20 million birds in the field 
at any one time. 
</P>
<P>
	Maryland-based Perdue Farms Inc., which bills itself as the  
nation's third-largest poultry producer, said it had not tallied 
its losses. 
</P>
<P>
	However, the area's growers produced more than 600 million birds  
last year and it would take a loss of millions of birds to affect 
the price of poultry, said Bill Satterfield of Delmarva Poultry 
Industry Inc. in Georgetown, Del. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990708.0310 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 19:00:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Part II of NY Subway Series on Deck </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- After winning the first leg of the Subway  
Series, the New York Yankees would just as well go on with the rest 
of their season. The New York Mets are relishing the opportunity to 
get even. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a big three-game set against the Yankees,'' Mets manager  
Bobby Valentine said. ``I think we'd like to get a second shot at 
them in our park.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Yankees, who took two out of three against the Mets last  
month, will take the short drive over the Triborough Bridge on 
Friday to begin a three-game series at Shea Stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'll find out if this is too much of a good thing,'' Yankees  
manager Joe Torre said Thursday from Detroit. ``Both owners want to 
win because it's New York. We want to win because it's a game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Yankees have taken two of three in all three series with the  
Mets, starting in 1997. This is the first time the teams will place 
twice in the same season. 
</P>
<P>
	``There hasn't been as much hype about this series as the first  
one,'' Torre said. ``Today's the first day I've had to answer 
questions about it. Last time the questions started 10 games before 
it happened.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The second series starts the way the first one ended, with Al  
Leiter (7-6) taking the mound against Roger Clemens (8-2). The Mets 
came into that game with an eight-game losing streak and having 
just fired three of their coaches. 
</P>
<P>
	Leiter's struggles before that start -- he was 2-5 after signing  
a $32 million, four-year contract in the offseason -- helped lead GM 
Steve Phillips to fire pitching coach Bob Apodaca. 
</P>
<P>
	Leiter allowed one run and four hits in seven innings and the  
Mets pounded Clemens for seven runs in 2 2-3 innings, handing 
Clemens his first loss in more than one year. 
</P>
<P>
	``I remember that last outing too,'' Leiter said. ``And I'll  
just try to duplicate it. So hopefully, if I do my job and we score 
some runs, we'll be OK.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Mets, who were 27-28 with the 11th-best record in the NL  
before that game, turned their season around after leaving the 
Bronx. They are 21-10 since then and now have the fifth-best record 
in the NL. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know that there's a good time or a bad time to play a  
team,'' John Olerud said. ``I think we'd like to have everyone 
healthy and playing well, and we'd like to have some momentum. But 
you don't always have your way in life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Mets will be short-handed this weekend. Closer John Franco  
is out 3-10 weeks with a partially torn tendon on the middle finger 
of his left hand and third baseman Robin Ventura with a bruised 
left foot. 
</P>
<P>
	``If he (Ventura) plays at all this weekend,'' Valentine said.  
``I'd be very surprised.'' 
</P>
<P>
 *Notes:* The Mets' Rick Reed (6-3) will face Andy Pettite (5-7)  
Saturday and the Yankees' Hideki Irabu (5-3) opposes Orel Hershiser 
(9-5) in the finale on Sunday. ... Leiter is 2-4 with a 3.30 ERA in 
11 lifetime appearances against the Yankees. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990708.0311 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 16:31:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  DeCicco Honored To Coach US Women </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLAREMONT, Calif. (AP) -- Tony DiCicco is the man behind the  
women. 
</P>
<P>
	As perhaps 2,000 fans at Thursday's practice session screamed  
for Mia Hamm, Michelle Akers and the rest of the U.S. soccer squad 
that has taken the nation by storm, DiCicco exited the bus and 
calmly strode, almost unnoticed, toward the field at Pomona-Pitzer 
College. 
</P>
<P>
	When the workout ended, 150 or so media members scrambled to  
surround the players as they sat in different areas of the field. 
Television cameramen jostled for position near Julie Foudy and 
Brandi Chastain. 
</P>
<P>
	DiCicco sat nearby, far from the madding crowd, a handful of  
reporters informally chatting with him. That, generally, is 
DiCicco's way: He stays out of the way, except when his team needs 
some instruction or a dressing down. 
</P>
<P>
	``It has been a privilege to coach this team,'' DiCicco said as  
the Americans prepared for Saturday's final with China. ``It's been 
a wonderful opportunity for all of us. This team has grown together 
and is so close to achieving what it set out to do, and they all 
are outstanding women, too. I can't think of a better job to 
have.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When DiCicco took over the job in August 1994 from Anson  
Dorrance -- who guided the Americans to the first Women's World Cup 
title in 1991 and is the mastermind of the University of North 
Carolina soccer dynasty -- he sought guidance from some of his 
players. Hamm told him to ``coach us like men, treat us like 
women.'' He has never forgotten that advice. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't know much about this team,'' said DiCicco, 50, who  
joined the squad as a goalkeepers' coach in '91. ``I had been 
working with U.S. Soccer and boys youth national teams. This team 
had developed a reputation for good play. 
</P>
<P>
	``Once I experienced this team and saw their passion for the  
game and the goals they set for themselves, it was fun to be around 
them. And it became a dream come true to end up their head coach.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Since taking charge, DiCicco has a 96-8-7 record, including this  
World Cup. He's led the Americans to third place at the '95 World 
Cup, gold medals at the Atlanta Olympics and last year's Goodwill 
Games, and now to the finals of the biggest women's sporting event 
ever. Not bad for someone who claims he didn't consider holding the 
job before he got it. 
</P>
<P>
	``Coaching a national team? I don't know if I ever thought about  
being the women's national coach'' he said. ``But certainly playing 
and coaching at a high level was a dream of mind. I sought to coach 
a team that is motivated, talented and has a chance of winning, and 
that I would be proud to be associated with. 
</P>
<P>
	``All those goals have been answered by this team.''  
</P>
<P>
	As a male among these superb female athletes, DiCicco remains a  
bit of an outsider. That gives him a unique perspective about this 
team that, right now, carries the aura of the biggest rock stars. 
He had to chuckle when someone mentioned the hundreds of yelping 
youngsters who surrounded the team bus as it pulled onto the 
college grounds before practice. 
</P>
<P>
	Might this scene be similar to what Bruce Springsteen or Ricky  
Martin experiences at concerts? 
</P>
<P>
	``One of the things that sets this team apart is that they don't  
want to all be the homecoming queen and do the popular thing,'' he 
said. ``They just want to go out and win games and win 
championships and Olympic gold medals. That's an awesome challenge. 
</P>
<P>
	``The genuine pursuit of their dreams and goals is what is so  
enticing for people. Its kind of snowballed and has turned into a 
wonderful phenomena. They are finally getting their due.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So is he.  
</P>
<P>
	``Tony understands us,'' veteran Joy Fawcett said. ``He  
understands we have a different approach to the game and to the 
relationships we build than the men do. He allows us to be 
ourselves, and that's been a very important part of our success.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990708.0312 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 16:31:01 </DATE_TIME>
