<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 12:30:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Down 27.22; Nasdaq Up 21.57 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mixed today as strength in Internet  
and computer stocks helped the technology sector outperform the 
broader market. 
</P>
<P>
	At 3 p.m. on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was  
down 27.22 at 11,160.14. The blue-chip index fluctuated between 
negative and positive territory for much of the session. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were mixed. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500  
index was down 1.39 at 1,394.47, and the Nasdaq composite index was 
up 21.57 at 2,764.61. 
</P>
<P>
	Nasdaq's relative strength came from a wide array of technology  
shares. Yahoo! rose 11/16 to 167 3/4 after reporting earnings that 
topped expectations. 
</P>
<P>
	Computer maker Apple rose 4 3/4 to 54 5/8 after a Wall Street  
investment firm upgraded its outlook on the stock. 
</P>
<P>
	But the broader market struggled to find direction as companies  
released some mixed reports on their second-quarter profits. Strong 
profit forecasts have propelled markets to record levels in recent 
sessions, but even good news today failed to jolt stocks out of a 
tight range. 
</P>
<P>
	General Electric beat analysts' estimates by a penny. Its stock,  
which rose sharply Wednesday in advance of the report, slipped 1 
1/16 to 116 7/8 as investors locked in their profits from that gain. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, other companies continued to warn of weakness.  
Airborne Freight said late Wednesday it will miss analysts' 
expectations by as much as 18 cents per share. Its shares fell 1 
5/16 to 25 7/8, and other package delivery company stocks fell along 
with it. 
</P>
<P>
	Philip Morris rose 3/4 to 38 5/8. Its shares had dropped in late  
trading Wednesday after a Florida jury ruled that tobacco makers 
are liable for making a defective product that causes emphysema, 
lung cancer and other illnesses. The verdict, if it stands, is 
expected to cost the tobacco industry billions in damages. 
</P>
<P>
	Today, however, analysts said the verdict was no real surprise.  
Investors bought the stock back on the belief that legal wrangling 
may delay payments to plaintiffs for many years. 
</P>
<P>
	Rival tobacco companies were modestly lower.  
</P>
<P>
	Stocks were also knocked off kilter today by a vacillating bond  
market. Bond prices initially tumbled today, with the 30-year 
Treasury bond dropping 1/2 point in price and its yield rising to 
6.08 percent from 6.04 percent late Wednesday. The rising yield 
served as a reminder to investors that higher interest rates are 
taking hold in the buoyant economy, and could threaten earnings in 
future quarters. 
</P>
<P>
	But by afternoon, bond prices were recovering, due mostly to a  
recovery in European bond markets. The yield on the 30-year 
Treasury bond slipped back to 5.99 by the afternoon, beneath the 
highly sensitive 6 percent level. 
</P>
<P>
	Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 4-to-3 margin on the  
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 657.4 million shares, 
ahead of Wednesday's pace. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index was down 1.06 at 655.41, and the  
American Stock Exchange composite index was up 3.52 at 805.66. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russell 2000 index, which measures the performance of small  
companies, rose 0.98 to 453.67. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990708.0314 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 16:00:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rains Cause Las Vegas Flood; 2 Dead </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAS VEGAS (AP) -- Heavy rains pounded the Las Vegas Valley  
Thursday, turning streets into rivers, stranding motorists on top 
of their cars and exhausting the city's emergency services. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the worst flood in Las Vegas since at least 1984,''  
said Ron McQueen, a meteorologist with the National Weather 
Service. 
</P>
<P>
	Two deaths were blamed on the weather. A man's body was  
recovered from a wash area Thursday afternoon, and a woman was 
killed in a traffic accident, police and fire officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	By early afternoon, parts of the valley had received up to 3  
inches of rain and more was expected throughout the day, McQueen 
said. The average annual rainfall in the Las Vegas Valley is 4.1 
inches. A flash flood warning was issued for the area. 
</P>
<P>
	Motorists were plucked from flooded vehicles by roaming fire  
trucks and, in at least one case, a police helicopter. 
</P>
<P>
	The severe flooding turned sections of busy Interstate 15 into a  
lake, bringing traffic to a standstill. 
</P>
<P>
	Tourists seeking shelter from the rains poured into the Strip  
casinos. No casinos reported any major damage. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Strip is a lake, up over the curbs, into our fountains,''  
said Phil Cooper, spokesman for Caesars Palace hotel-casino. ``I've 
been here 10 years and it's the worst I've ever seen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Caesars was forced to close part of its casino and the Forum  
Shops because of the flooding, Cooper said. 
</P>
<P>
	Flights at McCarran International Airport were shut down for 45  
minutes, airport spokeswoman Cynthia Markson said. Two planes 
scheduled to land in Las Vegas had to be diverted to Los Angeles, 
she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Intersections across town were closed as the rising waters  
swallowed vehicles. Several motorists were stranded on top of their 
cars and had to be rescued by firefighters as their trucks made 
their way along the flooded streets, picking up stranded motorists 
one by one. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is as serious as it gets,'' said Clark County Fire  
Department spokesman Steve La-Sky. ``Our emergency dispatch 
switchboard is lit up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The heavy rains caused a ceiling to cave in at a Lucky's grocery  
store on the city's southwest side and numerous businesses and 
homes had leaky roofs. 
</P>
<P>
	The heaviest hit areas were in the southwest and west parts of  
the valley. 
</P>
<P>
	Firefighters were trying to contain mudslides and boulder slides  
along the Summerlin Parkway in the northwest part of the valley, 
Nevada Highway Patrol spokesman Scott Flabi said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a nightmare. It's one of the worst things I've ever  
seen,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Several mobile homes were in danger of being washed downstream  
as the waters pushed through the southeast part of the city. A 
storage shed at the mobile home park was swept away, and residents 
watched as their homes dangled in the water. 
</P>
<P>
	McQueen said the flooding was caused by a rich moisture flow out  
of northern Mexico and the gulf of California. 
</P>
<P>
	The rain was expected to continue throughout the day.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990708.0315 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 13:30:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks End Mixed; Dow Down 60.47 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock prices were mixed today as strength in  
Internet and computer stocks helped the technology sector 
outperform the broader market. 
</P>
<P>
	At the close of trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial  
average was down 60.47 at 11,126.89. The blue-chip index fluctuated 
between negative and positive territory for much of the session. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were mixed. The Nasdaq composite index  
rose to a new record, while the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was off 
slightly. 
</P>
<P>
	Nasdaq's strength came from a wide array of technology shares.  
Yahoo! rose after reporting late Wednesday its second-quarter 
earnings easily topped Wall Street expectations. 
</P>
<P>
	Computer maker Apple rose after BancBoston Robertson Stephens  
upgraded its outlook on the stock. An analyst at the firm cited 
strong sales of Apple's iMac computer. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader market struggled to find direction. Alan Skrainka,  
chief market strategist at Edward Jones in St. Louis, said the 
continued strength of the U.S. economy, underscored today by strong 
reports from the nation's biggest retailers, has stunned many 
investors. 
</P>
<P>
	``Investors are wrestling with a tug-of-war between strong  
corporate profits and higher interest rates,'' he said. ``A strong 
economy produces both.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Indeed, strong second-quarter profit forecasts have propelled  
markets to record levels in recent sessions, but even good news 
today failed to jolt stocks out of a tight range. 
</P>
<P>
	General Electric beat analysts' estimates by a penny. Its stock,  
which rose sharply Wednesday in advance of the report, slipped 
today as investors locked in their profits from that gain. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, other companies continued to warn of weakness.  
Airborne Freight said late Wednesday it will miss analysts' 
expectations by as much as 18 cents per share. Its shares fell, 
dragging other package delivery company stocks with it. 
</P>
<P>
	Philip Morris rose modestly. Its shares had dropped in late  
trading Wednesday after a Florida jury ruled that tobacco makers 
are liable for making a defective product that causes emphysema, 
lung cancer and other illnesses. The verdict, if it stands, is 
expected to cost the tobacco industry billions in damages. 
</P>
<P>
	Today, however, analysts said the verdict was no real surprise.  
Investors bought Philip Morris stock back on the belief that legal 
wrangling may delay payments to plaintiffs for many years. Rival 
tobacco company stocks fell modestly. 
</P>
<P>
	Stocks were also knocked off kilter by a vacillating bond  
market. Bond prices initially tumbled today, with the 30-year 
Treasury bond dropping 1/2 point in price and its yield rising to 
6.08 percent from 6.04 percent late Wednesday. The rising yield 
served as a reminder to investors that higher interest rates are 
taking hold in the buoyant economy, and could threaten earnings in 
future quarters. 
</P>
<P>
	But by afternoon, bond prices were recovering, due mostly to a  
recovery in European bond markets. The yield on the 30-year 
Treasury bond slipped back to 5.99 by the afternoon, just under the 
6 percent level that tends to set off selling in stocks. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
